<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARMEL, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sybil Ludington won't be beheaded after all
_ but she might be scalped.
   Both suggestions might have appealed to the British troops who
were bedeviled by the 16-year-old heroine of the Revolutionary War.
But local officials who made the suggestions insist they mean Sybil
no harm _ they just want to help her overcome an embarrassing
problem.
   It seems that Sybil _ a statue of her, that is _ has begun to
foam at the mouth.
   Last month, Putnam County officials were nearly ready to remove
the head of the statue to clean out the mold causing the foam. But
Tuesday night, a committee of the County Legislature heard an
alternate remedy.
   By slicing a small hole in the statue's head, legislator Lynn
Greenwood said, workers might be able to remove the growth.
   Ms. Greenwood said she opposed decapitation, preferring a
``scalp job, which will be done at a more reasonable cost and (be)
less dramatic to the people who see her every day.''
   The bronze statue on the shore of Lake Gleneida depicts the
16-year-old girl riding a horse in 1777, when she dashed through
the countryside warning colonists that British forces were burning
nearby Danbury, Conn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEATRICE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While they know the guest of honor won't
attend, residents of this southeastern Nebraska community are
planning a celebration to mark the birth of the newest member of
England's royal family.
   The birth of Princess Beatrice, pronounced BEE-a-tris, gives the
community of nearly 13,000, pronounced Bee-AT-tris, a reason to
display pride in the name they share.
   ``It's a unique opportunity,'' said Randy Baynes, a member of
the Gage County Visitors Committee.
   Plans call for a Sept. 1 baby shower at the Chamber of Commerce
to honor the princess, born Aug. 8. She is the daughter of Prince
Andrew and his wife, Sarah, the Duke and Duchess of York, and is
fifth in line to the throne.
   ``We're planning on serving iced tea and cake, but maybe tea and
crumpets might be more appropriate,'' said Diane Schwenke,
president of the Chamber of Commerce.
   While residents will be able to drop off cards and gifts for her
royal highness, the town's official presents will include a
T-shirt, mug, honorary Beatrice citizenship papers, a Beatrice
Public Library card, a bib cross-stitched with her name, and a deed
giving her one square inch of land at the Homestead National
Monument near here, Mrs. Schwenke said.
</TEXT>
