<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cow Deaths,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cow Deaths Prompt Dumping Of 32,000 Gallons Of Milk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAVIE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have dumped more than 30,000
gallons of milk at a dairy farm following the recent deaths of more
than 20 cows, possibly from something they ate, authorities said.
   The milk apparently was not contaminated but was dumped as a
public health precaution until the cause of the cow deaths is
determined, according to officials from the farm and the state
agriculture department.
   ``I do not believe there is any contaminant or toxicant causing
the cattle deaths,'' Jay Boosinger, director of the division of
dairy industry for the Florida Department of Agriculture and
Consumer Services, said Wednesday.
   ``But it's better to err on the side of public health and safety
and recommend that they not market the milk.''
   Boosinger said milk, water, and feed samples, as well as tissue
samples from one of the cows that died during the past two weeks,
were collected from the 967-acre Imagination Farms, which milks
1,100 cows. Test results were not expected until later this week.
</TEXT>
