   Lorimar Telepictures tried to characterize
Valerie Harper as a greedy, insane star going through menopause,
the actress' attorney says.
   Barry Langberg confronted Lorimar television president David
Salzman with the accusation during cross-examination Wednesday in
Lorimar's breach-of-contract lawsuit against Ms. Harper and her
countersuit against the company.
   Salzman adamantly denied that the production company sought to
paint such an image of the 48-year-old actress.
   ``You don't agree with the fact that she was greedy?'' asked
Langberg.
   ``I don't agree,'' said Salzman.
   ``Do you agree with the fact that she was insane?'' asked the
attorney.
   ``She said she was insane,'' he replied. Langberg then repeated
the question and Salzman answered, ``I think at times ... she acted
as if she was going insane.''
   ``What about going through a change of life?'' asked Langberg.
   ``No,'' replied Salzman. But he acknowledged that he had written
the words, ``Change of life'' at the top of a page of notes he took
on negotiation meetings with Ms. Harper over her series,
``Valerie.''
   Lorimar ultimately replaced Ms. Harper with Sandy Duncan and
changed the name of the series to ``The Hogan Family.''
   Ms. Harper says she was wrongfully fired. Lorimar says she broke
her contract.
  
