<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Frey; An AMs separate moved as a0630 on Stuckey.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Nat Stuckey</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nat Stuckey, who wrote and recorded the
country hit ``Sweet Thang,'' died Wednesday of lung cancer. He was
54.
   Stuckey was a radio announcer for KWKH in Shreveport, La., when
he wrote his first No. 1 hit, ``Waitin' In Your Welfare Line,''
recorded by Buck Owens. He then began appearing on the ``Louisiana
Hayride'' country music show in Shreveport before moving to
Nashville in 1968.
   Stuckey also wrote the ``Pop A Top,'' recorded by Jim Ed Brown.
``Sweet Thang,'' recorded by Stuckey 20 years ago, also was a hit
as a duet by Ernest Tubb and Loretta Lynn. He most recently had
recorded commercial jingles.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Leonard Frey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonard Frey, who received an Oscar nomination
as best supporting actor for the role of Motel the tailor in the
1971 movie version of ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' died Wednesday of
AIDS at age 49.
   Frey made his New York professional debut as Yellow Feather in
the off-Broadway musical ``Little Mary Sunshine.'' His theatrical
breakthrough came with his performance as Harold in Mart Crowley's
``Boys in the Band.'' He later re-created the role for the 1970
film.
   Frey also played leading roles in ``The Time of Your Life,''
``Twelfth Night'' and Athol Fugard's ``People Are Living Here.'' He
acted in several operas, including ``Die Fledermaus.'' Frey's last
appearance was in an episode of the television series ``Murder, She
Wrote.''
