<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CommunistRanks     08-25 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Communist Ranks,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Membership Declines For First Time In Two Decades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of people throughout the
world who belong to the Communist Party declined slightly from 1986
to 1987, according to the Hoover Institution.
   Total membership decreased from 89.8 million in 1986 to 88.6
million the following year, the conservative think tank at Stanford
University reported in its 1988 Yearbook on Communist Affairs.
   That compares with a 7.6 percent increase in party membership
from 1985 to 1986, the yearbook reported. The publication also has
recorded a leap of more than 70 percent in international Communist
membership since the early 1970s, when the total was about 50
million.
   The small drop from 1986 to 1987 indicates that Communists
around the world are fed up with the Soviet Union, said yearbook
editor Richard Staar.
   ``(It) can be attributed to several factors. ... Most important
is the openly admitted failure of the politico-economic system in
the U.S.S.R.,'' he said.
   ``The system has failed. It no longer serves as a model, even
for Eastern Europe,'' Staar added.
   Another factor is the increased exposure of young people living
in Communist countries to ``the success of capitalist governments
around the world,'' Staar said.
   But while there may be fewer Communists throughout the world,
there are more in California, the party said.
   ``We have found a tremendous renewed interest in Marxism and the
Communist Party in the last year,'' said Kendra Alexander,
chairwoman of the California Communist Party.
   ``Our own membership, while admittedly not very large, has
climbed by about 250 members to about 1,000 people,'' she said.
</TEXT>
