<DOCNO> AP880825-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     08-25 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poultry Production Up Worldwide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World output of poultry meat is up 3 percent
this year and is expected to gain further in 1989, according to the
Agriculture Department.
   A survey of 51 major producing countries by the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service released Wednesday showed 1988 poultry
meat production at 30.12 million metric tons, up from 29.21 million
last year. The forecast for 1989 is for 31.09 million tons.
   The European Economic Community and the United States account
for most of this year's increase, while Brazil will be a major
contributor in 1989, the report said.
   Six countries in addition to the 12-nation EEC account for 23.1
million tons of this year's poultry meat total and 23.8 million
tons of the 1989 forecast.
   Looking at the 1989 forecast, the report showed U.S. production
at 9.79 million tons; Brazil, 2 million; Canada, 700,000; EEC, 6.01
million; Hungary, 500,000; Soviet Union, 3.3 million; and Japan,
1.5 million.
   Other countries, not listed, are expected to account for 7.29
million tons of the 1989 forecast of 31.09 million tons.
   World egg production is expected to be up 1 percent this year,
with the largest increase in the Soviet Union. Production is
expected to grow more slowly in 1989, the report said.
   In a related report, the department said U.S. egg production in
July dropped 2 percent from a year earlier to 5.68 billion eggs.
The total number of laying hens declined to 268 million birds, down
3 percent from July 1987.
   However, July production per hen was up, averaging 2,118 eggs
per 100 birds, compared with 2,097 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says commercial
flower growers will have a new, genetically engineered dwarf
version of the long-stemmed lisianthus next spring.
   Roger H. Lawson of the department's Agricultural Research
Service said Wednesday the deep-purple lisianthus may be the first
commercial flower developed through biotechnology research.
   The dwarf lisianthus will be sold as a potted plant, rather than
seed, and will be available in April 1989, he said. It will be made
available by the Society of American Florists and USDA.
   Lawson, who heads up a new floral crops program funded jointly
by USDA and the floral society, said the new plant bears several
tulip-sized blooms at once, is a 6- to 10-inch mutation of a
2-foot-tall lisianthus that is popular in many parts of the world
as a cut flower.
   Wild lisianthus grows throughout the American prairie region, he
said.
</TEXT>
