<DOCNO> AP880825-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SeatBelts     08-25 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seat Belts,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says NHTSA Seat Belt Probe Is `Back Burner' Maneuver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators hope to put on ``the back
burner'' claims that some Ford Motor Co. seat belts can cause
crippling injuries, an attorney representing a paraplegic child's
family alleges.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration opened an
investigation Wednesday into 1.7 million Ford Escort and Mercury
Lynx cars to determine if the rear seat belts are safe. The agency
turned down a request by the child's family that the cars be
recalled immediately.
   ``Everything I know tells me that study on top of study means
finesse,'' said Harold Sakayan, a Washington attorney for the
family of James Garrett, who was crippled at age 11 in the 1985
crash of a Ford Escort. ``It puts it on the back burner for
awhile.''
   He accused the agency of seeking to placate congressional
critics while deferring action on the issue until after the next
president is inaugurated.
   Garrett in January filed a petition for recall of the 1984-1988
cars on behalf of the child's parents, Larry and Patricia Garrett
of La Plata, Md.
   The couple alleged a strap retainer caused the seat belt to ride
around their child's waist rather than the hips. When the car in
which they were riding smashed head-on into a tractor-trailer, the
seat belt cut through the soft tissue to their son's spine, they
said.
   The Garretts in January won a $3.3 million judgment against Ford
for their child's injuries.
   NHTSA said in a letter to the Garretts' attorneys that a limited
technical review had left the agency ``unable to conclude that the
strap retainer has had an adverse effect on the performance of the
system.''
   The agency said the Lynx and Escort seat belts met federal
safety standards, but added, ``Testing did indicate that the ...
rear safety belts with and without the strap retainer fit
differently on test subjects compared to rear safety belts in some
other cars.''
   The agency ordered a mid-level investigation, an engineering
analysis, to probe the safety effects of the belts' fit.
   Ford said it believes the belts are safe. ``They meet or exceed
all federal motor vehicle safety standard performance requirements,
including those for location, fit, strength and ease of use,'' Ford
said.
   ``We are confident that the agency, too, will conclude that no
safety-related defect is involved,'' Ford said.
   In the 1985 accident, near Annapolis, Md., a second back-seat
passenger, 14-year-old Christopher Gaboury, was killed. The two
front-seat occupants were hospitalized after the accident but
escaped crippling injury, even though the passenger compartment
crumpled in the collision.
   The accident and subsequent lawsuit prompted public questioning
of the safety of rear-seat safety belts, particularly those with
the unusual design found in the Escort and Lynx.
   Belts that ride against the hips are braced on a large mass of
bone in an accident, keeping the passenger anchored while avoiding
damage to the spine. Belts that ride above the hip under the impact
of a crash can slice through the body's soft tissue to the spine,
resulting in paralysis or death.
   NHTSA said its strong recommendation that seat belts be used
remains unchanged.
   ``Whether it be at the front or the rear, ... you are far better
off wearing any kind of belt than no belt at all, and that is based
on studies of hundreds of thousands of accidents and fatalities and
injuries,'' said Ron DeFore, NHTSA spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
