<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan     08-25 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Quayle Experienced on Military Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan came to the defense of GOP
vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle by claiming that the junior
senator from Indiana has more experience on military issues than
Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Reagan, appearing Wednesday at a rally with Vice President
George Bush, offered his lengthiest comments to date about Quayle
since the vice president tapped the 41-year-old last week as his
running mate.
   Since the announcement was made, Bush and Quayle have been
dogged by questions about the conservative senator's use of family
connections to help him join the National Guard and avoid the draft
when many young Americans were being sent into combat in the
Vietnam War.
   Although Reagan made no mention of the flap, he opened his
remarks by praising Bush and adding, ``I like your running mate,
too.
   ``He has had many more years of experience dealing with national
security affairs than the head of the other ticket,'' Reagan said.
   The president lauded Quayle's work on a major job training bill
without mentioning that Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
co-sponsored the measure.
   ``Dan Quayle stands for the same principles as George Bush and I
do,'' the president said.
   ``And he has the most important qualification of all for a
co-pilot _ he won't be trying to turn the plane in one direction
while the pilot is flying it in the other.''
   Reagan argued that Bush is well-prepared for the presidency
after eight years in the co-pilot's seat.
   ``I once said that he is a great vice president, but I know and
I've seen that it didn't come easily. George Bush is a man of
action _ a man accustomed to command,'' Reagan said.
   The president offered no examples of duties he'd handed the vice
president, but said that ``day in, day out, I've sought George
Bush's counsel.''
   Reagan, as he has in several campaign appearances here amidst
his annual August vacation in California, poked fun at the
Democratic ticket, calling it ``a three-headed ticket that doesn't
know left from center.''
   The president has often referred to the Democrats as running a
triumvirate for the White House, attempting to paint Jesse Jackson
as an unseen but powerful force in the campaign of Dukakis and his
running mate Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas.
   The president, who is scheduled to undergo a battery of annual
eye, ear, nose and throat exams during his week-long stay in Los
Angeles, has no public events until Saturday, when he is scheduled
to take part in two fund-raisers for the California GOP and Rep.
Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   Afterwards, Reagan and his wife, Nancy, are to return to their
Santa Barbara ranch until after Labor Day.
</TEXT>
