<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialDebates     08-25 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Debates,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Campaign Gives No Definite Date For Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival presidential candidates George Bush and
Michael Dukakis are saying they want to debate this fall but sound
far from agreement on when or where or how often they will meet.
   ``Vice President George Bush will debate his opponent this
fall,'' said a brief statement Wednesday from the Bush campaign.
But the announcement also said it was ``unlikely that a debate can
occur prior to Sept. 20.''
   That brought an outraged reaction from Dukakis campaign chairman
Paul Brountas, who accused the Bush campaign of ``seeking to
unilaterally reject'' debates scheduled for Sept. 8 in Birmingham,
Ala., and Sept. 14, in Annapolis, Md.
   Brountas said the Bush campaign decision not to accept the
earlier dates ``threatens the full schedule of debates anticipated
for the fall. It is a transparent effort to limit the number of
debates.''
   Dukakis, during a stop in Michigan, said flatly, ``I'm going to
be in Annapolis on the 14th with or without him.''
   The Birmingham debate is being sponsored by the League of Women
Voters, the Annapolis forum by the bipartisan National Commission
on Presidential Debates.
   A Bush spokesman said that while the Republican presidential
nominee had said long ago he would debate his Democratic opponent,
he had never agreed to any specific events.
   Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker III is expected to meet
with Brountas in Washington next week to negotiate the debate
format.
   The campaign statement said they would discuss ``sponsorship,
timing, ground rules and other related matters.''
   The announcement said Bush aides were confident ``the two
campaigns would be able to work out the details of the debate
schedule between themselves.''
   It also said the campaign ``thanked the groups and organizations
which had offered to help expedite the process.''
   Brountas retorted: ``Mr. Baker stated that the campaign is not
prepared for a debate prior to Sept. 20. This is inexcusable. The
presidential commission debates have been scheduled for over a year
and the vice president has known he would be his party's nominee
for more than five months. ...
   ``The American people have a right to the full schedule of these
debates as agreed upon by the two national political parties.''
   Dukakis added during a campaign stop in Cleveland: ``After seven
years of on-the-job training, it seems to me that he ought to be
able to go to work and debate the issues. ... The vice president
has been saying a lot about defense and national security, and I'm
ready to debate him.''
   Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin said: ``There were never any
commitments made on specifics of a debate schedule. We've been very
specific in saying the vice president wants to debate Governor
Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
