<DOCNO> AP880825-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0249EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-AFL-CIO-Dukakis     08-25 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AFL-CIO-Dukakis,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Hopes to Deliver Huge Margin of Union Votes to Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AFL-CIO is gearing up a drive to deliver
Democrat Michael Dukakis a margin of at least 2{ million votes
among its 14 million members on Election Day.
   Presidents of 87 of the labor federation's 91 affiliated unions
gave the Massachusetts governor an unqualified endorsement
Wednesday.
   Union political operatives said the first step in their campaign
for Dukakis is to make sure that 85 percent to 90 percent of union
members and other voters in their families are registered, compared
with 72 percent of the voting age population as a whole in the last
presidential election.
   ``You need about six weeks in most states to have an effective
drive,'' said John Perkins, the labor federation's political
director. Perkins will head the effort using computers at AFL-CIO
headquarters here.
   The next step will use computers to track individual members'
concerns on various issues, with letters sent to them on Dukakis'
position on those issues. The aim is to obtain at least 65 percent
to 70 percent turnout Nov. 8.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland estimated the federation's
endorsement of Walter Mondale in 1984 was worth a net 2 million
votes despite exit polls showing that as many as 47 percent of
voters from union households cast their ballots for President
Reagan.
   ``Our rule of thumb is that we have to do two-thirds or better
in order to be successful in the election,'' Kirkland said. ``We
fell short of that. I'm reasonably confident that the results this
time will be improved.''
   United Steel Workers President Lynn Williams said winning
passage of a law requiring employers to give 60 days advance notice
of plant closings and layoffs has renewed labor's confidence going
into the campaign's final 11 weeks.
   ``In the primaries, we had our members running (as potential
delegates to national conventions) on behalf of every Democratic
candidate, but we have a very united position now in the Steel
Workers, and my sense is it's that way across the labor movement,''
Williams said.
   Owen Bieber, the president of the United Auto Workers, said a
poll of his members by the American Arbitration Association showed
a 96.9 percent level of support for Dukakis.
   ``And that was before Dan Quayle,'' Bieber said, referring to
the Indiana senator tapped last week as the GOP vice presidential
nominee and the controversy since then on his use of family
connections to help him avoid the Vietnam War draft.
   Quayle led the Reagan administration's opposition on Capitol
Hill to the plant closing notices law and has one of the lowest
pro-labor voting records _ 9 percent _ in the Senate.
   Labor leaders acknowledged that an overwhelming majority of
their rank-and-file probably are unaware of Quayle's role in
defeating union-sought labor legislation over the past seven years.
   One of their missions between now and Election Day, they said,
is to educate their members on Quayle's votes.
   ``At this point I just hope he's not forced off the ticket,''
Rachelle Horowitz, political director for the American Federation
of Teachers, said of Quayle. ``I want him out there campaigning.''
   Bush campaign spokesman Mark Goodin called the AFL-CIO's
endorsement of Dukakis ``a classic dog bites man story.''
   ``Every four years the AFL-CIO trots out what has become an
obligatory endorsement of a Democratic presidential candidate and
1988 is obviously no exception,'' Goodin said.
   Among those unions abstaining in Wednesday's endorsement was the
largest, the 1.6 million-member Teamsters, which endorsed Ronald
Reagan in 1980 and 1984 after making no presidential endorsement in
1976.
   Newly installed Teamster President William McCarthy of Boston,
who according to union sources dislikes Dukakis, said he is
withholding an endorsement until a mail poll of his members is
completed Sept. 16.
   Asked if the Teamsters might endorse Bush, a union official
said, ``I just don't see it.''
   ``If the poll comes back strong for Dukakis, we'll probably
endorse him,'' said the Teamster official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. ``If it's close, we'll probably remain neutral.''
   The 30,000-member Air Line Pilots Association said it was
delaying an endorsement until after its convention next month. The
40,000-member Marine Engineers union also voted to abstain,
reaffirming its decades-old policy of making no presidential
endorsements.
   The Newspaper Guild qualified its endorsement, voting 4,000 of
its 25,390 members as abstaining primarily because of opposition by
its 1,000-member Wire Service Guild local to taking sides in the
election.
</TEXT>
