<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-SovietGrain     08-25 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Soviet Grain,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Soviets Agree to Extend Grain Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union have
agreed tentatively to extend their grain deal for another year
while trying to complete a new, longer-range accord, a U.S.
official says.
   The official, who asked not to be identified, said Wednesday
that the two countries agreed through diplomatic channels last week
on an extension that is essentially identical to the current pact.
   A second official insisted that no final agreement had been
reached, but said he believed that one could be completed shortly.
   ``We feel like we made some progress, but we're still far apart
on pricing, minimums and things of that nature,'' Thomas Kay, chief
of the Department of Agriculture's Foreign Agricultural Service,
said of the first three U.S.-Soviet negotiating sessions.
   Kay said the two countries are trying to schedule a fourth
meeting.
   ``I'm optimistic at the next session we'll reach an agreement,''
he said.
   Under the current five-year pact, which expires Sept. 30, the
Soviets must buy at least 9 million tons of U.S. grain annually.
   The grain deal benefits American farmers, now experiencing
severe drought problems, and the Soviet Union, which often looks to
the West for grain even though it has had a good harvest this year.
   Last month, the Agriculture Department estimated that the
Soviets would have a bumper harvest of 215 million metric tons,
which would be their third best crop ever. The Soviets are
importing grain to build up their stockpiles and to feed expanding
livestock herds.
   The Soviets already have been given permission to purchase more
than 12 million tons of grain for this year. As of last month, they
had bought more than 5 million tons of corn, more than 9 million
tons of wheat, 830,700 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of
soybean meal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
