<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CalifLottomania     08-25 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Calif Lottomania,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drawing Machine Fails During Broadcast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE GEISSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California lotto machine that selects
winning numbers jammed Wednesday night during a drawing for a $38
million jackpot, one of the nation's largest gambling windfalls.
   Lottery officials, following disaster recovery guidelines,
hastily conducted another televised drawing a half hour after the
regular time.
   ``There are procedures to handle this sort of thing and they
were followed,'' said Bob Taylor, the lottery's top spokesman at
Sacramento headquarters.
   The first, incomplete drawing was ruled invalid, Taylor said. A
drawing announcer called out the number 33 during the initial
drawing but no ball bearing the number rolled out of the machine.
   At the outset of the second drawing, the announcer said, ``We've
reloaded the machine and are beginning a new drawing.''
   The reason the device failed was still being investigated,
lottery officials said. It was the first failure in the 22-month
history of the game.
   Before the first drawing, Californians were grabbing $1 lotto
tickets at an estimated average rate of more than 500 a second.
   ``The lines are unreal. People who normally buy $5 worth of
tickets are buying $20 worth,'' said Anaheim liquor store owner
Mike Notery Sr. ``Anybody with money to spend is thinking, nothing
ventured, nothing gained.''
   The fast pace of sales left lottery officials unsure of the
exact jackpot total. Officials expected to determine Thursday
whether there was a winner, and verify that person's identity later.
   If nobody picked the correct six numbers out of a choice of 49
numbers, the jackpot will be added to Saturday's drawing, said
officials.
</TEXT>
