<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonCondoms     08-25 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Condoms,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Circumvents Prison Board Disapproval Of Condom Distribution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor W. Wilson Goode circumvented the city
prison board and ordered condoms distributed to inmates as part of
an AIDS prevention program in Philadelphia jails.
   On Monday, the board voted 3-2 with one abstention against
making condoms available to prisoners, despite pleas from health
officials and testimony from an inmate suffering from the deadly
disease.
   Goode said Wednesday his program, which takes effect Sept. 1,
also includes anonymous AIDS testing, counseling and treatment of
prisoners.
   Prison board member M. Mark Mendel, an attorney who strongly
opposes distributing condoms, said Goode had the prerogative to
circumvent the board.
   Mendel said he opposed the proposal because the law prohibits
sex between prisoners.
   ``We're sending mixed signals,'' he said.
   He also said he doubted that prisoners will use the condoms,
especially in cases of rape.
   ``A prisoner with AIDS is an animal'' who would not care whether
his sex partner has protection from the disease, Mendel said.
   Mendel said only eight prisoners in the city's jails have been
diagnosed as having acquired immune deficiency syndrome, indicating
that ``prisons are not AIDS factories.''
   David Fair, director of AIDS programs for the city Health
Department, said earlier this week that two prisoners have died
from the disease. He said the number of prisoners infected with the
AIDS virus would be difficult to estimate but could total more than
half of the 3,700 in custody.
   During a two-hour discussion before Monday night's vote, Public
Health Commissioner Maurice C. Clifford urged approval of the
policy, saying sexual activity was rampant in the city's jails.
   ``We are not condoning sexual activity,'' Clifford said. ``We
are saying it is taking place ... and the best protection against
AIDS is using a condom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
