<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Ethics-Meese     08-25 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethics-Meese,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ursula Meese's China Travel Prompts Clarification of Justice Trip
Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department should not have allowed
former Attorney General Edwin Meese III's wife to accept a free
trip to China last year, the Office of Government Ethics says.
   ``The bottom line is, if the Department of Justice considers it
an official function, then the Department of Justice must pick up
the tab for its own employees,'' said Don Campbell, a spokesman at
the ethics office.
   Ursula Meese accepted the all-expenses-paid trip as a guest of
People-To-People International of Kansas City, a non-profit
organization.
   She and Deborah Morris, the wife of Joseph Morris, head of the
office of liaison services, accompanied their husbands to an
international legal seminar after Justice officials said it was
proper for them to do so, Campbell said.
   ``We disagreed with them in the outcome,'' Campbell said. ``They
analyzed it, and they saw it a little bit differently than we
did.'' Federal regulations prohibit relatives of federal employees
from accepting trips and gifts.
   The Justice Department paid for travel by the attorney general
and other department employees.
   The ethics office plans no more action, Campbell said, terming
the decision on the China trip ``a close call,'' but the office has
sent a letter to Justice spelling out how similar trips should be
handled in the future.
   Five Justice officials, along with Meese _ who resigned Aug. 12
and is now a private citizen _ plan to attend a similar legal
conference in Tokyo between Aug. 29-Sept. 1.
   ``What we basically said was that we are not going to challenge
anything on the China trip, but here is guidance for the Japan
trip,'' Campbell said.
   The Justice employees who are traveling to Japan are Patrick
Korten, the department's chief spokesman; Charles Rule, assistant
attorney general for antitrust; Morris of the liaison office;
Cheryl Nolan, one of Morris' subordinates, and Richard Abell,
director of the office of Justice programs. Mrs. Morris is not
scheduled to go on the trip, a secretary in Morris' office said.
   Deborah Burstion-Wade, a Justice spokeswoman, said the
conference is designed to explore legal and economic relations
between Japan and the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
