<DOCNO> AP880825-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DestituteAuthor     08-25 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Destitute Author,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Graduate' Author Nearly Destitute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His 1962 novel ``The Graduate''
became a smash-hit movie evoking the discontent of a generation fed
up with materialism. Today, however, Charles Webb finds himself
looking for a handout.
   ``The things he stands for and believes in are principles he
can't live by any longer,'' said Webb's ex-wife Fred, who has
accompanied him through two itinerant decades that has left the
couple virtually homeless.
   Webb, 49, says his abhorrence of material things led him to give
away two houses during the good times. He says he is nearly
destitute, living out of a van on a few thousand dollars a year.
   ``It's hard to make anybody believe the author of `The Graduate'
needs money,'' he said Wednesday.
   Webb said hard times have driven him and his 48-year-old ex-wife
out of the southern California campground where they lived for the
past decade to the Massachusetts town where Webb went to college 30
years ago.
   He came East, he said, in hopes of finding a publisher for his
latest project, a compilation of writings on prejudice.
   His plight, however, has taken him to the welfare office in
North Adams, which rejected him because he has no permanent address.
   The novelist, whose hero in ``The Graduate,'' Benjamin Braddock,
struck a chord among young readers with his post-graduate misery at
his parents' suburban home, has lived until now according to what
friends consider impossibly high and even self-destructive
standards.
   ``If he's hard up for dough, it's obviously due to ... his
inclination toward divestiture,'' said Eric Davis, who graduated
with Webb from Williams College in 1961 and teaches at the private
Commonwealth School in Boston.
   He said the couple's tendency to rid themselves of property
explains why they gave their Hollywood house to a real estate agent
in the 1960s and a home to the Massachusetts Audubon Society in
1970, when, Webb said, he felt the need for ``getting free of
things.''
   After the Webbs' marriage in 1962 in Fred's posh hometown of
Lakeville, Conn., they sold their wedding gifts at a yard sale,
many of them to the guests who had given them.
   A yearning to be free also explains their decision to divorce
eight years ago, although they had no intention of separating.
Fred, an artist whom Webb met when she was a student at Bennington
College in Vermont, said the couple felt marriage was a violation
of their constitutional right to freedom.
   Webb, the son of a well-to-do California doctor, espoused odd
views back in college, Davis said.
   ``We always used to wonder whether Chuck was putting us on,'' he
said. ``He's quite sophisticated, a very intelligent person with a
real heart, but he always said things that sounded peculiarly
simple.''
   Webb was the envy of classmates with the publication of ``The
Graduate,'' which he wrote after his own graduation in a small
apartment in Cambridge that he rented with the help of a college
creative writing grant.
   The obscure 1962 novel was catapulted to fame by the movie, and
Webb was declared a highly gifted writer with a keen ear for
dialogue. ``The Graduate'' was followed by four other novels,
including ``The Marriage of A Young Stockbroker,'' which also was
made into a movie. His last work, ``Booze,'' was published in 1978.
   Webb says he received only $20,000 for the film rights to ``The
Graduate,'' which starred Dustin Hoffman, in the days before
authors insisted on a percentage of the movie's sales. The novel,
however, is still in print and continues to earn a few thousand
dollars in royalties annually.
   But he doesn't regret the unusual life that led to his dilemma.
``It's hard to think there would be another way to do it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
