<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     08-25 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Percent on Newspaper Payrolls Are Minority Members, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study by the American Newspaper Publishers
Association shows the newsroom is the least likely place in a
newspaper's plant to find blacks and other racial minorities.
   The study, made public Wednesday, found racial minorities make
up 16 percent of the workforce of American newspapers, but only 8
percent of the news and editorial staffs.
   The ANPA survey also said that 37 percent of the papers'
employees are women. Nationally, women constitute 47 percent of the
workforce and racial minorities 21 percent.
   The ANPA said 10 percent of newsroom employees were minorities,
but one-fifth of those were clerical or administrative workers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Military Families Move Inside Bases In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than half the U.S. military families
living in Panama have moved onto American bases over the past five
months, Defense Department officials said.
   At the same time, a growing number of servicemen going to the
troubled Central American nation are making the tour without their
families, allowing the U.S. to move more military families inside
bases.
   Maj. Kathy Wood, a Pentagon spokeswoman, said Wednesday that
1,134 military families were living off-post in Panama City as of
Aug. 1, down from 2,450 on March 1. About 12,200 American
servicemen are stationed in Panama.
   The effort to move dependents onto the bases has taken on more
momentum this summer because of what the United States has
described as a deliberate campaign of harassing Americans.
   The United States is continuing to press economic sanctions
against Panama in a bid to oust military leader Manuel A. Noriega,
who has been indicted in the United States on drug trafficking
charges.
</TEXT>
