<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 3rdLd-Writethru a0458 08-25 0893</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0458,0916</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BANGKOK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Burma Releases Leading Dissidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with details, color, from freed reporter.
CHANGES byline. Picks up 6th pvs, `The demonstrations ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's government on Thursday freed the
country's top dissident and nine others arrested in a crackdown by
former hard-line President Sein Lwin. A day earlier, the new
president lifted martial law in the capital and called for a
referendum on multiparty democracy.
   Those released included this correspondent, who on the drive
home from Insein Jail saw for the first time in 26 years people
shouting for democracy without any official hindrance.
   People of all ages, wearing red headbands symbolizing defiance,
road in open trucks around the capital shouting, ``Give us
democracy immediately!'' Banners hung across the roads said: ``We
want democracy! We want a multiparty system!''
   On Wednesday, President Maung Maung, beseiged by mass street
protests, said the ruling party soon will hold an emergency
congress to consider popular demands for an end to authoritarian
rule.
   Maung Maung, in power for only a week, is the country's first
civilian leader since military-dominated, one-party rule was
instituted in 1962.
   This correspondent was arrested during July 29-30 raids that
also netted leading dissident Aung Gyi and others. The official
government News Agency of Burma accused them of ``attacking the
state.''
   The demonstrations that led to Sein Lwin's ouster after just 17
days in office left 112 people dead by official count and led to
martial law being imposed in Rangoon.
   A tourist said people danced in the streets of the capital on
Wednesday when Maung Maung ended martial law, ordered troops from
the city center and lifted curfews throughout the country.
   Maung Maung, Burma's first civilian leader in 26 years, called
for a popular vote on restoring multiparty democracy and said his
government would resign if the ruling party rejects his plan.
   ``General elections will be held as soon as possible'' if the
people approve a multiparty system, and no top government officials
will run, the president said.
   Maung Maung noted that Ne Win, who led the 1962 military coup
that began authoritarian one-party rule in Burma, proposed a
referendum on multiparty government when he resigned July 23 but
that members of the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party rejected
the proposal.
   The party leadership will meet again in the next month to
consider the referendum again, he said. State-run Radio Rangoon
said the party will meet Sept. 12.
   ``If the congress refuses to hold a referendum, I and ... the
Central Executive Committee will resign from the party,'' said
Maung Maung, one of 14 members of the committee.
   If the party congress approves the idea of a referendum, the
People's Assembly, or parliament, will meet the next day and
``arrangements will be made to hold a national referendum in the
quickest time possible,'' he said.
   If the people then approve a multiparty system, the Constitution
will be amended, the People's Assembly will be dissolved and
general elections will be held as soon as possible, he said.
   ``Neither I nor any personnel of the State Council, the Council
of Ministers, the Council of People's Justices, the Council of
People's Attorneys and the Council of People's Inspectors will run
in those elections,'' the president said.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
the United States welcomes ``this movement toward democracy.''
   But a U.S. official who spoke on condition of anonymity said
protesters want a clear announcement that elections will be held
within a week or two, not a process that could take months.
   Ne Win, a former general, organized the military-dominated party
in 1962. In 1964, he outlawed all other parties and began pursuing
the rigid socialism and international isolation that turned one of
Southeast Asia's wealthiest nations into one of its poorest.
   When he resigned last month as chairman of the 1.1
million-member party, Ne Win, 77, cited his age and accepted
indirect responsibility for bloody student-led riots against his
government in March and June.
   He said then that the rioting ``showed the lack of trust and
confidence in the government'' and called for a referendum on
multiparty government.
   The rallies Wednesday, the third straight day of mass
anti-government protest, attracted ``from several hundred thousand
to up to 1 million'' people in the capital city of 3.5 million, a
Western diplomat said.
   When the radio announced martial law was lifted, ``the soldiers
started to immediately pull up the barbed wire barricades, pull
them away and retreat,'' Tom Lubin, a Chicago attorney traveling as
a tourist, said after reaching Bangkok from Rangoon.
   ``The crowd immediately began to gravitate toward Sule pagoda
and the town hall. People were dancing in the streets, shouting,
`We have won,''' said Lubin, 26. He said monks threw water on each
other in a traditional celebration.
   ``A few of the soldiers were beginning to crack smiles at the
people,'' he said. ``They seemed much more relaxed.''
   No violence was reported.
   Diplomats said the demonstrators marched along main streets in
Rangoon and dispersed after five or six hours.
   About 5,000 people sat outside the U.S. Embassy listening to
Burmese writers, lawyers, doctors and other professionals speak
over loudspeakers, a Western diplomat said. The demonstrators sent
frequent messages to the embassy asking for publicity and moral
support, he said.
</TEXT>
