<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Miners     08-25 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Miners,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Isolate Mines, But Strikers Stay Determined</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JASTRZEBIE, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As authorities tried to shut them off
from the outside world, striking coal miners communicated through a
clandestine network of couriers and listened in the dark to radio
reports of the standoff.
   Provisions in stores in Jastrzebie, a southern mining city of
100,000, dwindled after the strikes began Aug. 16, with cheese and
fresh meat virtually disappearing from the shelves.
   But food still reached the strikers. Farmers donated food and
funds for the strikers and on Wednesday, 330 pounds of fresh pork
arrived from Solidarity supporters in Bialystok, a city 335 miles
away near the Soviet border.
   The police presence at the July Manifesto mine increased
dramatically when more than 30 police vehicles took up positions at
the main gate.
   A few hours later, 103 police vehicles, including an armored
personnel carrier, jeeps, trucks and three water cannons, rolled
through the city in the direction of another mine.
   The road leading to July Manifesto, where the leaders of the
Silesian mine strikes set up headquarters, was sealed off by an
army roadblock.
   A nightime curfew took effect Tuesday. Residents were ordered
off the street from 11 p.m. to 5 a.m. to ``preserve the peace,''
according to signs posted throughout the city.
   The miners helped organize an effective network of couriers to
relay messages among the striking mines and through a strike
information center in the city's Blessed Virgin Mary Church.
   Police detained at least two couriers and accused them of
speculating in bread and butter Wednesday. The two later were
released and immediately resumed their rounds at the mines.
   Strikers resolved to continue their occupation until they won
legalization of Solidarity and better wages.
   ``There are fewer people, but they are in an excited mood and
they will stay to the end,'' said a regional Solidarity leader who
visited several mines Wednesday.
   Not all the town's attention focused on the strike.
   Mothers in Jastrzebie were busy buying school supplies and new
clothes for children who return to school Sept. 1.
   Those items take a big bite out of the family budget. A new
school bag costs the equivalent of $4.50, or a miner's wages for a
full day.
   At the church, a group of students from universities in Warsaw
and Krakow typed newsletters and communiques. They put the latest
word on strikes around the country on a blackboard, and flags of
Poland were pinned on a map of the country to mark strike locations.
   In between radio news bulletins, students listen to the Doors
and other old rock groups.
   At least two mines, July Manifesto and 30 Years of People's
Poland, printed daily strike newsletters on the premises. On
Tuesday, 125 miners at the latter mine descended 500 yards
underground because they feared a police assault.
   On Wednesday, the miners decided to divide up shifts to have
about 40 at time underground.
   Music soothed strained nerves, and whenever possible miners
played cassettes over the loudspeakers.
   Still, according to the couriers inside the mines, radio news
was the first priority. On the hour, strikers huddled together to
listen to the latest news of the situaion of those who joined them
in their struggle.
   They tuned by turns to Polish state radio, Radio Free Europe and
the Polish-language service of the British Broadcasting Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
