<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-25 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Higher, Dollar Down On Japan Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices inched up on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
while the U.S. dollar lost ground against the Japanese yen in
trading Thursday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 130.24-point
loser Wednesday, closed at 27,870.44, up 70.77 points, or 0.25
percent.
   The market recovered in the afternoon following a 31.32-point
decline during the morning session.
   The dollar, which opened at 133.93 yen, fell to close at 133.76
yen after moving in a tight range of 133.75-134.05 yen.
   ``Investors are very cautious ahead of the scheduled West German
(central) bank's decision on its discount rate, which has been
keeping them from buying stocks,'' said an analyst at a major
securities firm.
   ``Although the recovery on Wall Street overnight led to the
Tokyo market's rebound this morning, lack of direction in the
market reversed the trend,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the U.S. currency fell partly
because dollar-selling intervention by U.S. and European central
banks to support the West German mark finally has become effective.
   But the dollar's sluggishness will continue until investors
determine whether the German central bank will raise its key
lending rate to support its currency, they said.
</TEXT>
