<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Ali-Treatment     08-25 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ali-Treatment,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ali Gets Blood-Cleansing Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muhammad Ali is receiving
blood-cleansing treatments by a doctor who blames the former boxing
champion's weakened condition on household pesticide poisoning and
not blows to the head.
   The 46-year-old former heavyweight champion walked into a
hospital waiting room throwing jabs in the air minutes after
undergoing an eight-hour blood treatment to relieve the slurred
speech and tremors that have plagued him in recent years.
   ``I feel like I can fight (heavyweight champ Mike) Tyson,'' Ali
said in a hoarse voice slightly above a whisper at Hilton Head
Hospital.
   Ali referred questions to his physician, Dr. Rajko Medenica, an
immunologist who specializes in cancer and blood disorders.
   Ali arrived in Hilton Head on Tuesday night to undergo
plasmapheresis, during which his plasma was removed and replaced
with an artificial product prepared by Medenica. Plasma is the
yellowish fluid in which other components of the blood circulate in
the body.
   Although Ali has been diagnosed as having parkinsonian syndrome,
possibly brought on by blows to the head during his boxing career,
Medenica disagrees.
   Calling it ``The Muhammad Ali Syndrome,'' he blamed household
pesticide poisoning, which probably affected him so severely
because of his rapid metabolism when he was in peak physical
condition.
   Ali likely will return to Hilton Head for the treatments every
three months or so, Medenica said.
   ``My goal is to remove the circulating toxins. By the end of the
year, he should be much better,'' he said.
   Although Ali had trouble speaking, he moved with ease and
appeared to be in good spirits. Moments after a brief
question-and-answer session, he playfully pulled a small red
handkerchief from his pocket and made it appear and disappear
several times.
   ``I like to show people how easily they can be deceived,'' he
said. Ali then performed other tricks, signed autographs and posed
for photographs with delighted hospital workers.
   His wife, Lonnie, said that other than the slurred speech, Ali
is doing better than many people realize. ``He feels no pain. He's
never sick. There is no hard part living with Muhammad. There is
nothing special I have to do for him, except make sure he takes his
medication.''
   Ali called Medenica the greatest doctor in the world. ``He's got
methods I've never seen before,'' he said.
</TEXT>
