<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-PrisonBreak     08-25 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Prison Break,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmates Escape In Second Break From Same Prison in Six Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DONCASTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven convicts escaped from a
low-security prison by cutting a hole in a fence while other
inmates rioted, police said today. It was the second such escape
from the prison in six weeks.
   South Yorkshire police said 10 convicts remained at large
following the break late Wednesday from Lindholme Prison in
northern England. One was captured on a farm near the prison, they
said.
   A police statement said the escapees were not considered
dangerous and were serving time for such crimes as robbery and
theft.
   Police were called to the prison after a small number of the 753
inmates started smashing windows. The violence spread, and some
inmates broke into the prison kitchen and hospital, causing minor
damage, police said.
   Meanwhile, the 11 cut a hole in a wire mesh fence surrounding
the compound and fled.
   Prison guards managed to restore order after about two hours
while 100 policemen, aided by dogs, ringed the prison to prevent
further escapes while the fence was repaired.
   Officers set up roadblocks and began searching the surrounding
countryside for the escapees. No injuries were reported in the
disturbance.
   On July 16, six inmates escaped from the prison by cutting a
hole in the fence while other prisoners went on a four-hour
rampage, smashing buildings and setting them on fire. Four of those
escapees were captured.
   Britain's overcrowded and often antiquated prison system has
been plagued in recent years by riots and demonstrations. Prisoners
have complained about overcrowding, poor living conditions,
brutality by guards and petty restrictions.
   Authorities admit living conditions are bad in some prisons and
say the government is trying to solve the problem by building new
prisons.
</TEXT>
