<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Bomb     08-25 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Bomb,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Placed in Aeroflot Plane, Fails to Go Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crude bomb was placed in the luggage of a Soviet
woman flying from the Ukrainian capital Kiev to the Volga River
city of Kuybyshev, but it failed to explode, the official Tass news
agency said.
   Tass said in a dispatch Wednesday that police suspect the
woman's husband, a former army colonel, of making the bomb and
planting it.
   ``The device had a tremendous explosive potential. Experts are
trying to find out why it did not work,'' the agency said.
   It said the woman, who was not identified, found the device in a
suitcase as she unpacked her bags at the home of a relative she was
visiting. She was traveling with her 15-year-old daughter.
   The woman called police when she found the device, which
contained parts of an ordinary alarm clock, and experts were called
to dismantle it, Tass said.
   The bomb was set to explode 35 minutes into the 870-mile flight,
it said.
   ``Police who conducted an investigation in Kiev found in the
house and garage belonging to the woman passenger's family the
things similar to those of which the explosive device was made,''
Tass said.
   ``It was found out as well that her husband disappeared after
learning about the safe landing of the plane in Kuybyshev,'' the
article said.
   The woman's husband, a former colonel in the Red Army, was
working as an engineer at a Kiev plant.
   Tass did not say when the flight occurred or what kind of
explosives were used.
</TEXT>
