<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Pounds Southern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms doused sections of Arizona and
dampened much of New England today after pounding rain triggered
dozens of car crashes and lightning knocked out power to 82,000
customers in Southern California.
   ``You couldn't see your hand in front of your face,'' Officer
Ron Kauffman of the California Highway Patrol said of Wednesday's
cloudburst.
   Along a 4-mile stretch of Interstate 15, the rain helped cause
16 crashes involving 27 vehicles, injuring 15, officials said.
   Those accidents included one involving a mortuary van that
overturned, spilling two bodies onto the highway, said patrol
Officer Mark Mezzano. Motorists put the bodies back in the van.
   The downpour soaked a Los Angeles apartment building, forcing 75
residents into a shelter. An activist led 30 homeless people camped
out in a park to the Los Angeles County Building for shelter.
   Lightning cut power to 82,000 homes and businesses in Southern
California, including 70,000 in Los Angeles suburbs and 4,000 in
the city, utility officials said.
   Showers and thunderstorms that produced heavy rain in parts of
Arizona Wednesday night continued today. At the Grand Canyon, 2
inches of rain had fallen by Wednesday afternoon.
   Showers were widespread from northern New England to the
southern New England coast. Showers and a few thunderstorms
lingered over sections of Florida and the northeast Gulf Coast.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers from the Great
Lakes to New England, with showers most numerous in Upper Michigan
and northern New England; widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms from southern Texas to the Gulf Coast and northern
Florida; and showers and thunderstorms from Arizona to southern
Utah.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s or 90s across much
of the nation, the 60s in Maine and upper Michigan, the 70s from
North Dakota to the lower Great Lakes, upper Ohio Valley, and
southern New England and along the Pacific Coast; and between 100
and 105 in the desert Southwest, the central valleys of California
and parts of the southern Plains.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 93 degrees at Chandler and
Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 62 cloudy; Buffalo 63 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 75 fair; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 62
fair; Miami 79 fair; New York 63 partly cloudy; Philadelphia 66
fair; Pittsburgh 64 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine 63 drizzle;
Washington 71 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 60 fair; Chicago 64 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
80 fair; Denver 73 partly cloudy; Des Moines 63 fair; Indianapolis
59 fair; Kansas City 67 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71 partly
cloudy; Nashville 64 fair; New Orleans 75 fair; St. Louis 68 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 70 cloudy; Anchorage 48 fair; Las Vegas 85
cloudy; Los Angeles 68 fair; Phoenix 93 partly cloudy; Salt Lake
City 74 cloudy; San Diego 72 fair; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle
58 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 partly cloudy; Toronto 59 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
