<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ParkRiot     08-25 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Park Riot,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chief Resigns As Commissioner Blasts Supervision During
Riot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police chief in charge of hundreds of
officers at a demonstration that turned into a riot resigned as the
police commissioner released a scathing report blaming the violence
on poor supervision.
   The report on Aug. 6's confrontation at Tompkins Square Park
criticized Deputy Chief Thomas Darcy, 56, for a series of mistakes,
beginning with his leaving the scene for about 90 minutes at a
crucial time to use the bathroom.
   ``It was clear from the review that some police officers engaged
in the excessive use of force against private citizens by striking
demonstrators with nightsticks and kicking other apparently
defenseless people,'' said Commissioner Benjamin Ward.
   Darcy, a 31-year veteran who was the designated commander of the
hundreds of officers deployed at the Lower East Side park, offered
his resignation shortly before Ward released the report Wednesday.
   The two other supervisory officers at the confrontation, Deputy
Inspector Joseph Wodarski and Capt. Gerald McNamara, also were
disciplined. Departmental charges also were brought against two
other officers, and more were expected, Ward said.
   The demonstration against enforcement of a 1 a.m. curfew that
has since been suspended ended with injuries to more than 50
people, including passers-by.
   More than 100 charges of police brutality were filed.
   A police review board, U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau are conducting separate
investigations into the complaints.
   ``The control of the situation was lost during the first
confrontation between police and demonstrators and never
sufficiently regained,'' wrote Chief of Department Robert J.
Johnston in the report.
   A key mistake, according to Ward, was McNamara's decision at the
beginning of the demonstration to transmit an emergency signal that
mobilized 300 officers from all over the city without making any
provisions for adequate supervision.
   Other major errors included use of a low-flying helicopter with
a search light, whose hovering presence acted as a magnet and drew
people to the confrontation, and the premature decision to send
police on horses into the crowd.
   Wodarski was reassigned from his prestigious post as commanding
officer of the Midtown South Precinct to a command in Queens, but
he did not lose his rank. Ward said McNamara will be temporarily
removed from his job commanding the a precinct for six to seven
months of retraining.
   Darcy will receive a $55,000 annual pension.
   The police review board has identified several officers involved
in the melee, relying in part on videotapes taken by neighborhood
residents, and recommended charges against two.
   The commissioner noted that 17,000 of the department's 26,000
officers had been hired since 1980, and they, as well as their
superiors, had no experience with riots.
   However, he said, ``The New York City Police Department is
better than the events in Tompkins Square Park would have you
think.''
   Among the report's recommendations was a major training program
in crowd control and policing of street disorders.
</TEXT>
