<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     08-25 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects PTL Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL's bankruptcy trustee says he'll
shorten the time the ministry has to sell its assets when he
submits a revised reorganization plan to a bankruptcy judge who
rejected his first proposal.
   In rejecting the reorganization plan Wednesday, U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Rufus Reynolds said it failed to take into account the
ministry's poor financial health.
   ``This plan does not work,'' Reynolds said. ``It does not
reflect the situation.''
   He gave PTL bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton until Oct. 1
to prepare a new plan, and until Sept. 10 to return with
information on potential buyers of the ministry's assets.
   Benton said PTL's secured creditors rejected the plan because it
allowed five years for the sale of the assets. PTL's major
contributors, called lifetime partners, also rejected the plan, he
said.
   Reynolds could have approved the plan despite the negative votes
from creditors, but decided against it.
   Proceeds from the sale of assets would repay PTL's debts, which
could top $130 million.
   Reynolds rejected the idea of closing down operations, saying
that would kill PTL's revenue sources, which include donations from
viewers of the televised ministry and proceeds from the Heritage
USA Christian retreat near Fort Mill.
   The ministry, which entered bankruptcy proceedings in June 1987
after the resignation of founder Jim Bakker in a sex-and-money
scandal, has been divided into the newly named Heritage Ministries
and a corporation holding PTL's assets.
   Benton said after the hearing that he would propose speeding up
the time required for the sale of assets to six to seven months.
   Benton did not address the effect of the reorganization plan's
rejection on potential buyers of the assets. But he said setting a
sale within seven months would let creditors know how much they
would be receiving much quicker than the five years allowed in the
original plan.
   Benton told the court the debtor corporation has been losing
$400,000 a month, and needed $885,000 from the sale of other assets
to survive 30 more days. Reynolds approved that request.
   Benton said he expected to have by a Sept. 1 a firm offer from
Canadian Peter Thomas of the Samoth Capital Corp. to buy the
Heritage USA theme park, satellite television network and other
property. The company has offered $113 million for the network,
park and 1,700 acres of undeveloped property.
   He said there also may be offers from Bakker, Charlotte, N.C.,
businessman George Shinn and an Oklahoma group he declined to
identify.
</TEXT>
