<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Singapore-Elections     08-25 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Singapore-Elections,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exchange Between Leader And Designated Successor Overshadows
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Formal campaigning began today for next month's
general elections, but the contest has been overshadowed by a
public exchange between the only leader Singapore has known and his
designated successor.
   The tension began in a three-hour speech Aug. 14, when Prime
Minister Lee Kuan Yew cited the shortcomings of Deputy Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong. On Monday, he suggested Goh see a
psychiatrist.
   Goh said that Lee really meant a psychologist, and added that he
planned to nudge the prime minister out of office, probably within
two years.
   Lee said Monday that his deputy could not communicate as well on
television and at mass meetings as he could in small groups. ``I
don't know why. I have suggested to him perhaps a bit of
psychological adjustment, maybe a psychiatrist, something holds him
back.''
   Goh told reporters Tuesday that Lee suggested he consult a
psychologist, ``not a psychiatrist, who is for mentally distressed
people.
   ``I do not believe that a psychologist could help me. A speech
therapist and trainer will, and I have been seeing my speech
trainer for over a year,'' said Goh, who sometimes appears stiff
and uneasy during televised speeches.
   ``I am not President Reagan. I am not good at one-liners.
Neither am I Prime Minister Lee. I am not good at making three-hour
speeches.''
   Goh quoted Lee as saying the prime minister ``is only waiting to
be nudged out by a firm elbow. When the time comes, probably inside
two years, I will gently nudge him out.''
   Goh was picked as the next leader by Cabinet members in 1984,
but Lee will remain in power following the Sept. 3 elections and
there are no formal plans to end his rule.
   The dispute and the eventual shift in power has overshadowed the
election in the rich island nation, a former British colony that
separated from Malaysia in 1965. Lee has been its only prime
minister and the People's Action Party its only governing party.
   The Business Times said in an editorial today that ``the 1988
election is really about the handing over of the baton from Lee
Kuan Yew to Goh Chok Tong, the final passing of power ...''
   The governing party captured unopposed 11 of the 81 seats in
Parliament when nominations closed Wednesday. Formal campaigning
started today.
   The party is favored in most of the contested districts against
137 candidates from seven opposition parties and four independent
candidates. Only 51 opposition candidates ran in the last election
in 1984.
   All but three seats in Parliament, which was dissolved last
week, were held by the governing party, which needs at least 41 to
form a new government and run the country for the eighth
consecutive term.
   Opposition leaders have denounced changes in the constitution as
attempts to strengthen governing party rule.
   One proposed constitutional amendment is to change the now
ceremonial presidency into an elected office with enhanced powers.
   It is widely assumed that if the 46-year-old Goh takes power,
Lee, who will be 65 on Sept. 16, will become the first elected
president.
   In that role, he would have veto power over the nation's
spending and nominations of Supreme Court judges, the attorney
general and other senior posts.
   The new president would lack full executive power, but would be
able to make speeches in Parliament and have access to all
government departments.
</TEXT>
