<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Eliana-AIDS     08-25 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eliana-AIDS,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS-Afflicted, Retarded Girl to Stay Home for Present</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mentally retarded 6-year-old girl afflicted
with AIDS may stay in a home instruction program while an appeals
court decides whether she must be enclosed in a glass booth if she
attends school, a federal judge ruled.
   Eliana Martinez earlier won the right to attend school with
other retarded children when the fall term begins Monday in
Hillsborough County. But she would be isolated in a special
6-by-8-foot booth until she is potty trained and stops sucking her
thumb.
   The child's adoptive mother, Rose Martinez, fought in court for
two years to get her daughter in the class but balked at the glass
cage required by District Judge Elizabeth Kovachevich.
   Ms. Martinez' attorney, Steve Hanlon, appealed to the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. He also filed a motion for a
local stay, asking that Eliana be allowed to attend classes with no
restrictions or be kept in the county's homebound school program
until the Atlanta court rules.
   Chief Judge William Terrell Hodges ruled on that motion
Wednesday, allowing the girl to continue her instruction at home
until the appeal is heard.
   Hanlon said he asked the appeals court for ``expeditious
consideration'' that, if granted, could mean a ruling in late
September or October.
   The school board Tuesday displayed the glass booth, equipped
with a desk, toilet and sound system, to about 150 parents of other
children who will attend the Manhattan Exceptional Center this
fall. Only 11 of the school's 189 students would be in Eliana's
classroom.
   Several parents expressed concern over having their children in
school with the AIDS-afflicted girl. One parent, Rob Preston, said
his child would not go to school if Eliana shows up.
</TEXT>
