<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0605EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sweden-SpyRing     08-25 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Spy Ring,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spy Suspects Were Under Surveillance for Years, Reports Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Spy Ring, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swedish authorities kept three East
bloc immigrants under surveillance for several years before
detaining them this week on suspicion of spying, authorities were
quoted as saying today.
   The suspects _ a married couple and a man _ faced arraignment
today on charges of illegal intelligence activity, the Aftonbladet
daily said. Swedish radio, however, said the woman was released
after questioning and was no longer suspected of criminal activity.
   The New York Times reported that the three were among eight
people involved in a spy ring that stole defense plans for Western
Europe and gave them to the Soviet Union.
   The ring was based in West Germany, while couriers who aided it
were based in Sweden, the Times reported.
   The identities of the suspects were kept secret. Under Swedish
regulations, their names may not be published even after they are
charged in court.
   Aftonbladet said all three were in their 40s and that one was a
physician. They were detained Tuesday morning in the southwestern
port city of Goteborg, it said. The couple has lived in Sweden at
least 10 years, and the man came to Sweden in 1958, the newspaper
said.
   The Goteborgs Posten quoted Torsten Bjorkhede, the Goteborg head
of the security police, as saying the case was handled in
cooperation with other intelligence agencies, which he refused to
name.
   ``In any case, it's a question of activity which went on
continuously for a long time. It is not a matter of a single
incident,'' he said.
   The surveillance had gone on for ``years,'' he said.
   Authorities refused to elaborate on the affair. ``This is such a
special crime that we cannot say much now at the beginning of the
investigation,'' Chief Prosecutor Sven-Olof Hakansson was quoted as
saying in the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper.
   Hakansson was quoted as saying the suspects could not be
arraigned on spying charges since their actions were not directed
against Sweden. ``Illegal intelligence activity'' is a lesser
charge.
</TEXT>
