<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0618EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     08-25 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0636</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Collaborator Hacked To Death; Fifth Arab Dies In Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 30 masked men hacked to death a West Bank
Palestinian accused of collaborating with Israeli agents, Arab
residents and Israel radio said today.
   The army said he died in a clan dispute, but the village's
Israeli-appointed mayor, when asked who was responsible, told The
Associated Press: ``The whole village.''
   Palestinians meanwhile shuttered stores and stayed home from
their jobs today in the second day of a general strike called in
honor of four Arabs who have died in Israeli jails.
   A fifth Palestinian died Wednesday in a Gaza Strip jail, and the
army said it was investigating the circumstances. It acknowledged
force was used against him as he was being detained.
   The army imposed a curfew on Nablus, the West Bank's largest
city, and surrounding refugee camps after 14 Palestinians were shot
and wounded Wednesday in clashes with troops.
   Another were four were wounded Wednesday in the Gaza Strip
refugee camp of Shati.
   The strike was widely observed in the occupied territories.
Streets were deserted in Gaza City, and columns of black smoke from
burning tires were visible.
   On the Jerusalem-Bethlehem highway, assailants stoned several
Arab cars to enforce the strike, injuring four Palestinians. They
threw a firebomb at an Israeli passenger bus northeast of
Jerusalem, slightly injuring two Israelis, Israel radio said.
   In the West Bank village of Yatta near Hebron, the masked men
broke into the home of Saadi Hazaza late Wednesday, dragged him
outside and hacked him to death with axes, Arab witnesses and
Israel radio reported.
   The army said Hazaza apparently was killed in a clan dispute,
but villagers said he was targeted because he collaborated with the
Israeli authorities. Mayor Ismail Abu Hamid said the whole village
was responsible for his death.
   Hazaza carried a gun, a privilege only granted to West Bank
Arabs who cooperate with Israelis. He was stabbed in Hebron a month
ago and was released from a hospital three days before his death,
Israel radio said.
   Hazaza was the third suspected collaborator to be killed since
the Dec. 8 start of the uprising against Israel's 21-year rule in
the West Bank and Gaza.
   His death brought the Palestinian death toll to 253. Four
Israelis also have died.
   The army said it was investigating the death of 42-year-old Hani
Shami, who died Wednesday in army custody. Shami, a resident of the
Jabaliya refugee camp, was arrested Monday night when he tried to
stop soldiers from detaining his son, the army said.
   ``Some force was used against'' Shami as he was being detained,
an army spokeswoman said. She said he was examined twice by doctors
while in custody and found to be in good condition. On Wednesday,
he was discovered unconscious and later pronounced dead.
   Following U.S. criticism of Israel's deportation of Palesinians
suspected of subversion, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said today
that authorities only deported Palestinians as a measure of last
resort.
   ``There is no policy of deportations. There are individual
decisions on deportations,'' he told Israel radio.
   Israel has expelled 33 Arabs since the beginning of the
Palestinian uprising and has issued deportation orders against 25
more.
   Israel television reported military courts will begin hearing
the appeals of the 25 next Sunday. If the judges turn them down,
they may turn to the Supreme Court.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said
the United States was ``shocked by ... Israel's decision to expel
an additional 25 Palestinians.''
   In a first such warning to the Jewish state, U.S. officials said
relations could suffer if the deportations continued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
