<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FuelBarge     08-25 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Barge,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Says Barge Has Stopped Leaking Fuel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KILMARNOCK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A petroleum barge that sprang a leak
after possibly being damaged in a storm has stopped spewing fuel,
and an 18-square-mile slick won't do serious environmental damage
to the Chesapeake Bay, the Coast Guard says.
   ``While she's been aground, she's lost effectively all of her
cargo from two tanks,'' said Cmdr. George Naccara, executive
officer of the Coast Guard's Marine Safety office in Hampton Roads.
   The vessel, which leaked about 4,000 barrels, or 168,000
gallons, of light fuel, remained in containment booms set up
Wednesday afternoon, Naccara said late Wednesday.
   The 240-foot barge ran aground Wednesday morning in about 12
feet of water in Indian Creek on the Chesapeake's western shore.
The Coast Guard diverted the barge into the creek in an attempt to
get it to a pier where it could unload the fuel.
   The barge held 19,500 barrels of diesel fuel and gasoline,
Naccara said.
   ``We had a three-mile-by-six-mile sheen,'' said Coast Guard Lt.
Rod Walker. ``It will disperse over time.''
   Mike LaCivida, a spokesman for the Virginia Department of
Emergency Services, said some of the fuel washed ashore. The Coast
Guard said it expected minimal to moderate environmental damage.
   ``It's such a light oil that dissipates and evaporates
rapidly,'' said Naccara, adding that no migratory birds are in the
area this time of year.
   Naccara said the barge's owner, Eastern Carriers Inc. of
Hockessin, Del., accepted responsibilty for the accident and sent a
second barge to help offload the fuel from the damaged barge.
   The 37-year-old barge, en route from Baltimore to Richmond, was
being towed by a tug when it reported a leak, Naccara said. The
tug's crew said the barge might have been damaged in a storm about
two hours earlier, he said.
   ``Winds picked up to 25 knots and the operator of the tug
reported waves of about five feet,'' Naccara said.
</TEXT>
