<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Solidarity-Funds     08-25 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Solidarity-Funds,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Office Abroad Seeks Funds For Polish Strikers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The international office of the
Solidarity free trade union movement today appealed for funds for
strikers, their families and ``victims of repression'' in Poland.
   ``The needs are great,'' Jerzy Milewski, head of the
Brussels-based international office of Solidarity, said in a
statement. ``If the authorities adopt the worst possible tactics,
thousands of strikers are threatened with dismissal from work and
extreme poverty.''
   On Aug. 16, strikes began in the coal mines of southern Poland.
Since them more than 20 enterprises joined in, including shipyards,
transport companies and steel mills.
   Strikers demand higher pay, better working conditions and the
legalization of the Solidarity trade union movement, which was
outlawed in 1982.
   In a separate statement, the European Trade Union Confederation
called on the 12 European Economic Community nations to urge the
Polish authorities to stop using violence to end the strikes.
   The European union federation said it ``fully supports the
aspirations and demands of Polish workers and Solidarity.
   ``The strikes now under way in Poland show clearly the absence
of trade union liberties.''
   The federation said five East European nations _ the Soviet
Union, Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Hungary _ have
asked for formal diplomatic relations with the EEC and that a
Polish request was expected soon.
   As part of its improving relations with Eastern Europe, the EEC
must raise the issue of respect for trade union rights, the
federation said.
</TEXT>
