<DOCNO> AP880825-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Strike     08-25 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Strike,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Miners Return to Work After Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 employees of a coal mine
in southern Hungary returned to work today after a 20-hour strike
that posed the first worker challenge to the strict economic
policies of premier Karoly Grosz.
   In negotiations with senior government officials, the strikers
won a promise the government would try to iron out a quirk in a new
income tax law that allows workers on sick leave to earn more than
those working regularly.
   The strikers at the Komlo mine 100 miles south of Budapest
threatened to halt work again if parliament does not remove this
quirk.
   In addition, the government instructed companies to pay bonuses
to miners who complained they had lost 30 percent to 50 percent of
their bonuses under the new tax laws.
   The daily Magyar Nemzet published the text of a letter sent by
the strikers to Grosz, who in May became Communist party leader,
urging him to settle ``the oft-repeated problems'' of miners at
Komlo, 100 miles south of Budapest.
   The letter attacked the personal income tax introduced Jan. 1 as
part of Grosz's attempts to stimulate the stagnating economy. It
said the tax ``does not stimulate increased production or the
undertaking of extra shifts.''
   ``We all realize the present position and the problems both in
the national economy and in our own company, but we are faced with
a situation in which our own living conditions have become worse,
our real income having been reduced as a result of the inflationary
impact,'' the letter added.
   Inflation has reached 18 percent this year. The income tax has
reduced the net income of many workers by introducing taxes on
bonuses and earnings from second and third jobs.
   Grosz' government is trying to stimulate the economy to curb a
foreign debt of $18 billion.
   The letter justified the strikers' demands for changes in the
tax system by noting government and party leaders have said for
years that ``they consider the demands of workers legitimate and
will see that these are met.''
   ``We miners have always honestly done our duty toward the
dictates of the national economy, and feel it is the ethical duty
of the government to meet our requests now,'' the letter said.
   Reports of strikes in communist Hungary are extremely rare, and
the relatively swift media coverage of the stoppage at the Komlo
mine appeared to reflect the greater openness of the state-run
media since Grosz became party leader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
