<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Melville,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Civilian to Witness U.S. Atomic Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emma M. Melville, the nation's first civilian
to witness an atomic test, has died in a Baltimore hospital. She
was 87.
   In 1953, Civil Defense officials selected the 51-year-old
homemaker and grandmother to witness an atomic bomb test in the
Nevada desert.
   Mrs. Melville's trip was featured on Edward R. Murrow's ``See It
Now'' television news magazine. The national program broadcast a
special CBS report titled, ``Mrs. Melville's Atomic Bomb.''
   Of the experience she said, ``Movies and other pictures ...
aren't enough. ... It's something a person cannot realize or
imagine without first-hand experience. It was beautiful, too, if so
dreadful a thing can be linked with beauty.''
   Mrs. Melville, who died Tuesday, is survived by a son and two
daughters.
</TEXT>
