<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PleaForDimes     08-25 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plea For Dimes,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Looks For Grubstake, Gets About $2.50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple trying to raise $15,000 to
start a new life in California placed a newspaper ad asking for a
dime from each resident of San Francisco but won't get far on the
$2.50 raised so far.
   The ad in last week's issue of the weekly San Francisco Bay
Guardian cost $23, said Ed Hatley, who had hoped San Francisco's
680,000 residents would bankroll the move from northwest Arkansas.
   ``A dime from everyone in San Francisco will help us move to
California,'' Hatley and his wife, Bonnie Mae, wrote in the
advertisement.
   They've received about two dozen responses. Most included an
encouraging word or two: ``Come on out to this great state. Hope to
see you soon,'' was one offering. All included a dime, nothing more
than that. As of Wednesday night, eight days after the ad appeared,
Hatley had collected about $2.50, he said.
   ``We were just interested in moving out to California,'' he said
by telephone from Bentonville, population 9,000. The Hatleys have
no children and have lived in Bentonville for nine years. He does
theater, movie and video production work and says there's not much
work for him in northwest Arkansas.
   Hatley had hoped he could find work in San Francisco.
   Hatley, 35, who came here from Florida, said he didn't have
another plan in the works to get money for the trip.
   ``I really like northwest Arkansas a lot,'' he said. ``If the
money did happen, though, we'd make the move. It's simply that the
American dream is to have work you can enjoy.''
</TEXT>
