<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySelling     08-25 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Selling,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Ordered To Stand Trial In Baby Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOYLESTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young couple who offered to sell their
third child _ a 2-day-old girl _ said they didn't want to put up
with another diaper change, a Maryland state trooper said at their
preliminary hearing.
   Gino Gargone, 24, and his wife, Doris, 22, were ordered
Wednesday to stand trial on charges of trying to sell the infant
for $30,000 to the trooper, who posed as a divorcee desperate for a
child, a prosecutor said.
   Mrs. Gargone was held in lieu of $100,000 bail and her husband
was being held on $500,000 bail, according to Bucks County
Assistant District Attorney Dale A. Reichley.
   District Justice Catherine Stump Wednesday ordered the Gargones
to face formal arraignment Oct. 7 on charges of dealing in infant
children and conspiracy. If convicted, they could be sentenced to
15 years in prison and fined a total of $50,000, according to
District Attorney Alan Rubenstein.
   A third suspect, Steven Schwartz, 40, a Baltimore auto body shop
worker who acted as a go-between, is still at large, Reichley said.
The case started when the Maryland State Police responded to an
advertisement in the Jewish Times of Baltimore offering a child for
sale; the number given was the body shop where Schwartz worked.
   The Gargones were arrested July 16 after they turned their
daughter over to Maryland State Trooper Angelique Rutledge at a
motel in the Philadelphia suburb of Quakertown.
   Rutledge said Gargone told her in a telephone conversation that
his wife already had two boys, ages 1 and 2, and they wanted the
third baby placed in a good home.
   ``He told me about the family history ... that his wife was
pregnant two times in the last two years,'' Ms. Rutledge said. ``He
said he didn't want to put up with another diaper change.''
   Mrs. Gargone, who sat quietly next to her husband during the
hearing, lowered her head and cried when she saw photographs of her
husband allegedly handing over their infant.
   The baby girl was turned over to the Bucks County Children and
Youth Services Agency, which placed her in foster care. The
Gargones' two boys are being cared for by their maternal
grandmother.
</TEXT>
