<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Simon     08-25 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Simon,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon, Botha Air Differences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon met today with
South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha, and the two men said they
aired their differences over apartheid without yelling at each
other.
   ``You name the controversial agenda ... we talked about it,''
said Simon, D-Ill., who favors U.S. economic sanctions against
South Africa. ``We had a good, frank discussion.''
   Simon, who unsuccesfully campaigned for the Democratic
nomination for the presidency this year, is on a five-day,
fact-finding tour of South Africa.
   Simon is chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee
on African Affairs and will play a major role in deliberations on
pending legislation to intensify U.S. sanctions against South
Africa.
   Limited sanctions have been in effect since 1986.
   ``We never yelled at each other,'' Botha said after the meeting
in a Johannesburg suburb. ``The senator has put all the difficult
questions. But he has given me the opportunity to put my side.
That's all I can ask.''
   Botha and other South African leaders say they are pursuing
gradual race reforms at their own pace and will not be pressured by
sanctions. They also say black South Africans stand to suffer the
most from any economic hardships caused by sanctions or foreign
disinvestment.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Simon predicted Wednesday that Congress would intensify
sanctions against South Africa unless the government agreed to a
timetable for dismantling apartheid.
   ``(Simon) came here determined to find justification for
sanctions,'' The Citizen, a pro-government daily, said in an
editorial today.
   ``But then Americans do tend to have a simplistic _ should we
say a Simple Simon _ approach to other countries, and South Africa
is probably the worst example of this American madness to recreate
countries in their own image,'' the newspaper said.
   Simon visited several black townships and met with black leaders
such as Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   The senator's request to meet with imprisoned African National
Congress leader Nelson Mandela was rejected by the government.
   The 70-year-old Mandela, South Africa's best known black leader,
is in Cape Town's Tygerberg Hospital being treated for tuberculosis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
