<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Mrs.Dukakis-Flag 1stLd-Writethru a0452 08-25 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mrs. Dukakis-Flag, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0452,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campaign Says Kitty Dukakis Rumor `Beneath Contempt'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BOSTON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 4 grafs new with Dukakis comments today; picks up 2nd
graf pvs, Symms' comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis complained today about recent accusations by Republicans
against him and his wife, saying the charges are becoming a
distraction to the campaign.
   Speaking at a roundtable discussion with local reporters,
Dukakis said he and his wife, Kitty, are having to ``deny
nonexistent facts.''
   ``I think there's a pattern here,'' he said, raising his hand
above his head. ``I hope to keep a high place.''
   On Wednesday, the Democrat's campaign issued a statement saying
that a suggestion by Idaho Republican Sen. Steve Symms that Mrs.
Dukakis had burned an American flag is ``totally false and beneath
contempt.''
   Symms' comment was the third time in a few days that prominent
Republicans have aired allegations that the Democrats have rebutted
swiftly.
   The allegations come at a time when Republicans are struggling
to shift the campaign focus away from GOP vice presidential nominee
Dan Quayle and questions about his Vietnam-era service in the
National Guard.
   In an interview Tuesday with a radio station in Blackfoot,
Idaho, Symms raised the allegation that Mrs. Dukakis burned the
flag during an anti-war demonstration in the 1960s.
   ``As I've been told, I haven't seen this, but I heard that there
are pictures around that will surface before the elections are over
of Mrs. Dukakis burning the American flag while she was an anti-war
demonstrator during the '60s,'' Symms said.
   But Paul Costello, an aide to Mrs. Dukakis, issued a denial
Wednesday that read:
   ``Senator Symms' statement about Mrs. Dukakis is totally false
and beneath contempt. Mrs. Dukakis believes that the American flag
is a symbol of our nation's commitment to freedom and she respects
everything for which it stands.''
   The suggestion that Mrs. Dukakis had burned a flag was
``absolutely false,'' Costello said, adding that while she opposed
the Vietnam War, she could not recall ever participating in
anti-war protests.
   Dukakis aides twice called back to heap abuse on Symms.
   ``I guess the Republicans are doing the limbo to see how low
they can go,'' Costello said.
   Dukakis aide Mark Gearan added, ``Senator Symms should be
especially careful with rumors.''
   The other incidents:
   _On Sunday, in an appearance on ABC's ``This Week with David
Brinkley,'' New Hampshire Gov. John Sununu referred to a ``report I
saw in the press'' that allegedly said Democratic vice presidential
candidate Lloyd Bentsen had run ``to get his son'' admitted to a
special slot in a National Guard unit.
   Bentsen's son denied the allegation and said he enlisted in the
Texas National Guard in 1968 after personally contacting the
commander of the unit he wanted to join. ``He was wrong,
absolutely, categorically wrong,'' Lloyd M. Bentsen III said of
Sununu's comment.
   _On Monday, New York Rep. Gerald Solomon, the senior Republican
on the Veterans Affairs Committee, called reporters to talk about
Dukakis' draft deferments. ``I just want to point out that Dukakis
received his first of three educational deferments eight months
before the Korean War ended,'' Solomon said in Chicago. ``My point
is not to point fingers at Dukakis, because what he did was legal.
But he avoided combat by using his education deferments. There's
nothing wrong with what he did because it was allowed.''
   Dukakis swiftly denied any suggestion that he had used college
deferments to avoid combat in the Korean War, saying, ``I served my
country proudly.''
   Dukakis attended Swarthmore College from 1951-1955, requesting
and receiving draft deferments in 1952, 1953 and 1954. He said he
went to his draft board with several weeks of school left and asked
to be drafted immediately. He spent slightly less than two years in
the Army, including 16 months as part of a United Nations
contingent assigned to the demilitarized zone in Korea after the
fighting ended.
</TEXT>
