<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Portugal-Fire 2ndLd-Writethru   08-25 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Portugal-Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0535,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Dead, 29 Hurt In Fire That Guts Historic District Of Libson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 16 grafs to UPDATE with fire under control, raises
injury count, adds details. Pickup 10th graf pvs, ``Regular
Lisbon...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire today destroyed much of Lisbon's
historic shopping district, killed one person and injured 29 before
firemen brought it under control 10 hours after it began in a 19th
century department store.
   Maj. Anibal Matos Silveira, the official coordinating more than
800 firemen at the scene, told reporters that the Chiado shopping
district would ``continue to smolder'' for another day.
   President Mario Soares, who toured the 10-square-block area four
hours after the fire broke out in the Armazens do Grandela
department store on the Rua do Carmo pedestrian mall, said one man
was killed.
   Spokeswoman Ersilia Soares at San Jose Hospital said 29 people
were being treated for burns and smoke inhalation, and six were in
serious condition.
   The Portuguese news agency LUSA said the fire was Lisbon's worst
disaster since a fire and earthquake destroyed much of the city in
1755.
   LUSA earlier quoted fire officials as saying they didn't have
enough water to fight the blaze. Firemen with sooty faces
complained that pressure was too low to get the water to the upper
stories where the flames leapt from one building to another.
   Silveira said the shells of the burned-out, five- and six-story
buildings on Rua do Carmo, Rua Garrett, Rua Nova do Almada and Rua
Sacramento may collapse.
   The fire also destroyed Grandes Armazens do Chiado, Lisbon's
other department store, and numerous speciality shops that had been
a fixture of Lisbon's commercial life for the past 150 years.
   The fire reportedly began around 5 a.m.
   Officials said they did not know what caused it, but Lisbon
residents were awakened by explosions of bottled gas in the stores.
   Officials at the scene said hundreds of people were left
homeless by the fire and ``at least 2,000'' were out of jobs. No
exact figures were available.
   The Grandela and Chiado department stores were among the oldest
in Western Europe with wooden floors and stairways and
old-fashioned booths for cashiers. They had no sprinkler systems.
   The Chiado district is next to Lisbon's central Rossio Square 10
blocks in from the Tagus River estuary. It forms a part of the city
rebuilt by the Marques de Pombal after the 1755 disaster.
   Soares, viewing the flames pouring from buildings on the rua do
Carmo from the platform of the 19th century Santa Justa elevator
built by Gustave Eiffel, said the fire was a ``catastrophe.''
   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva, an economist, told reporters
at the scene the city faced an ``enormous task of reconstruction.''
   ``We are indebted to the firemen, and now we have to get down to
work to rebuild this area,'' Cavaco said.
   Regular Lisbon firemen were joined by volunteer companies from
surrounding areas. Radio stations called on firemen on their annual
August holidays to return immediately to Lisbon.
   Virgilo Madeira, a 67-year-old florist, looked out on Rua
Garrett as flames swept up the street toward his tiny Pequeno
Jardim flower shop.
   ``In all the 50 years I've been here, I've never seen such a
thing,'' he said. ``But I'm not leaving. I have nowhere to go.''
   Police ordered residents of the area to evacuate their homes as
firemen dragged orange hoses up old wooden staircases and onto the
red tile roofs.
   Old women in black huddled in doorways holding dogs and cats in
their arms, and men in suits and ties slipped down the wet, cobbled
streets carrying parakeets in cages.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-BurundiMassacre 2ndLd-Writethru a0554 08-25 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burundi Massacre, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0554,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burundi Refugees Tell Of Ethnic Warfare That Killed At Least 5,000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to simplify lede. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Nearly
two...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRARAMBOBO, Rwanda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers in Burundi shot to death
hundreds of Hutu tribesmen and dropped firebombs on villages after
Hutus burned and hacked hundreds of rival tribesmen to death,
refugees say.
   The Hutu refugees are pouring into Rwanda from neighboring
Burundi, where ethnic warfare with the rival Tutsi tribe has killed
at least 5,000 people and sent more than 40,000 fleeing for their
lives across the border.
   Nearly two weeks after the flare-up in a centuries-old tribal
feud between the majority Hutu and dominant Tutsi, refugees from
Burundi are arriving at the rate of 2,000 a day into Rwanda,
Africa's most densely populated country.
   ``We're trying to help them, but they are overwhelming us,''
Fredric Karangwa, governor of this province, said Wednesday.
   The influx of refugees, all Hutu, began Aug. 15. The refugees
say that a day earlier, Hutus turned on Tutsi tribesmen in two
northern communes, hacking hundreds to death with machetes and
burning others in huts.
   None of the refugees admitted involvement in the slaughter, and
it was not known what prompted the massacre.
   Refugees said the Tutsi-dominated army, sent north as
peacemakers, turned into executioners when they arrived and found
the carnage against their brethren.
   ``The soldiers were rounding up Hutus and shooting them,''
refugees said. ``They are collecting them into groups, taking them
inside houses, closing the doors and windows and then shooting.''
   The Burundi government denied the allegations and blamed the
bloodshed on exiled Hutus who infiltrated the tiny central African
nation. But many of the refugees in Rwanda have knife slashes,
bullet or shrapnel wounds and burns.
   The refugees, most of them peasant farmers, said government
helicopters dropped firebombs on fleeing villagers.
   The short, stocky Hutu account for 84 percent of Burundi's 5
million people, but the tall, lanky Tutsi _ about 15 percent of the
population _ control the military and the government.
   About 8,000 people were crammed into three camps in this section
of southern Rwanda. Most were camped on hills overlooking a
marshland and the Akanyaru River, the route to safety for fleeing
Burundians.
   In a local clinic, a doctor and several nurses said they treated
dozens of bayonet and bullet wounds.
   In one crowded waiting room, Reverin Ndururutse, 32, held his
5-year-old nephew, Immaculata. The boy's right side was peppered
with shrapnel. A bandage covered a finger on his right hand, where
the tip had been torn away by a bullet.
   Ndururutse said his nephew and his own 3-year-old son were the
only survivors of a family of 15 herded into a house by soldiers
who opened fire.
   The adults threw themselves on top of the two children,
Ndururutse said.
   Thousands of Burundians have used dugout canoes to cross the
slow-moving Akanyaru River. They hid in papyrus reeds near the
river until dusk and then crossed during the night.
   Beyond the marshes on the Burundi side, Rwandan officials say,
the Burundi military has closed the border and set up machine-gun
posts to stop the exodus.
   The site of most of the killing is in Burundi's remote north
around the farming communes of Ntega and Marangara. The army has
sealed off the areas.
   But the refugees keep coming and the influx has put a strain on
Rwanda, which already is hard pressed to deal with its own
population of 6.1 million.
   Rwanda has appealed for international aid. A team from the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees, which said 41,000 refugees had
arrived by Wednesday, is assessing the needs.
   Rwanda and Burundi, former Belgian colonies, each are about the
size of Maryland.
   The current bloodletting was the first reported ethnic violence
since Maj. Pierre Buyoya seized power in Burundi in a bloodless
coup Sept. 3, 1987 while former President Jean-Baptiste Bagaza was
out of the country.
   After an abortive 1972 coup attempt by Hutus, Tutsis massacred
100,000 Hutus, including most of the tribe's intelligentsia, human
rights groups said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Daniel     08-25 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Daniel,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Texas Governor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIBERTY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Texas Gov. Price Daniel, who once
said he would rather hold that job than the presidency, died in
this southeast Texas town early today. He was 77.
   The former governor and U.S. senator died at about 1 a.m., said
George Christian, a former press secretary to Daniel.
   Daniel apparently suffered a massive stroke at his ranch and was
taken to Yettie Kersting Hospital at Liberty, Christian said. He
was dead upon arrival, a spokeswoman said.
   Daniel was brought in at 1:10 a.m. and had no vital signs,
hospital spokewoman Margie Hagan said. Paramedics were unable to
determine the cause of death immediately.
   Daniel served three two-year terms as governor from 1957-63 but
lost an unprecedented bid for a fourth term in a Democratic primary
race won by John Connally.
   ``The death of Price Daniel is a loss to the people of America.
He never, never overlooked the problems with which the people were
concerned. We're going to miss people of his caliber,'' said former
Gov. Preston Smith. ``I've lost one of my best friends.''
   Smith appointed Daniel to the Texas Supreme Court in January
1971. Daniel retired from the court eight years later.
   Daniel started his public career as a member of the state House
of Representatives in 1939, became speaker in 1943 and later waived
his legislative exemption and enlisted in the Army as a private. He
left the service in 1946 with the rank of captain.
</TEXT>
