<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LateMedals     08-25 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Late Medals,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Veteran's Medals Arrive In Mail 32 Years Late</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Ralph Hume didn't receive his World War
II medals or discharge papers by 1955, he decided it wasn't ``worth
all the hassle.''
   But 15 days ago he got a surprise _ a package from the Navy that
contained his American Campaign, Asiatic Pacific and Victory medals
he earned while in the South Pacific for five years.
   The package also contained an envelope with a copy of his
discharge papers that were first mailed in 1956 to a Florida base
where Hume had been stationed in the late 1940s.
   ``I was shocked beyond words,'' Hume said Wednesday from his
home in Moores Hill, Ind., about 30 miles from Cincinnati.
   ``I knew in my heart I had earned them, and I guess at that time
I just didn't think it was worth all the hassle,'' he said. ``I
figured I'd go to a surplus store and buy them some day, but I
never did.''
   The package had been mailed this month from the Navy Liaison
Office in St. Louis, Mo. Inside, an envelope postmarked August 1956
had been mailed from the Bureau of Naval Personnel in St. Louis to
Eglin Air Force Base in Florida. Hume had been stationed there
while in the Air Force following his naval career.
   The address, however, had been crossed out and ``return to
sender'' stamped on the envelope.
   Dina Martin of the Navy Liaison Office could confirm only that
the package had come from her office, but not why. Nor did she know
where the items had been for the past 32 years.
   ``We don't send out anything unless there is a request for it,''
Ms. Martin said. Hume, however, said he's hasn't talked to the Navy
since 1955.
   That may change.
   He said he's still waiting for the Purple Heart and a Good
Conduct medal from the Navy and the Air Force.
</TEXT>
