<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PledgeDebate     08-25 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pledge Debate,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Attorney General, Bush Campaign Debate Pledge Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis did the right thing when he
vetoed a ``clearly unconstitutional'' 1977 Massachusetts law
imposing criminal penalties on teachers who failed to lead their
classes in the Pledge of Allegiance, state Attorney General James
Shannon said today.
   But Deborah Steelman, domestic policy director for George Bush's
Republican presidential campaign, said, ``Criminal penalties are
not the issue. What's at issue here was leadership.''
   Shannon, a supporter of Dukakis' Democratic presidential bid,
said on ABC's ``Good Morning America'' that the legislation
required criminal penalties against teachers who refused to lead
their classes in the pledge, ``even if their own religious
convictions said they shouldn't do that.''
   In vetoing the bill, Dukakis obeyed an advisory opinion from the
Massachusetts Supreme Court that the legislation was
unconstitutional. The state's governors have been given about 25
advisory opinions by the high court on legislation in recent years,
Shannon said.
   ``Never once, with all those different governors, has any
governor signed into law in Massachusetts a bill which our state's
highest court said was unconstitutional,'' he said.
   ``Since he took an oath of office to uphold the Constitution, he
had an opinion from our state's highest court that that law was
unconstitutional and he did the only thing that he could do under
the circumstances,'' Shannon said of Dukakis.
   On the same program, Steelman said Dukakis was not bound by the
court's advice.
   ``If he wanted to test this issue all he had to do was sign the
bill into law and press his case to the national Supreme Court.
   ``What's at issue here is leadership, whether you've got a
candidate who will stand up for the majority of Americans beliefs,
or whether you've got a candidate who won't even stand up for his
own beliefs.''
   The veto was overriden by the Legislature and the law went on
the books, but it has never been enforced and its constitutionality
has not been challenged.
   The court said the bill was unconstitutional because the state
cannot force citizens to take an oath that may controvert their
religious beliefs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
