<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mandela     08-25 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mandela,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister: Mandela May Be Moved From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jailed black leader Nelson
Mandela may be moved soon from the hospital where he has been
treated for tuberculosis, a Cabinet minister indicated today.
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe declined to say
whether Mandela would go back to Pollsmoor Prison, where he has
been serving a life sentence for plotting an anti-government
sabotage campaign.
   The African National Congress leader, jailed since 1962, was
moved from Pollsmoor to nearby Tygerberg Hospital on Aug. 12.
Doctors say he is expected to recover fully after a recuperation
period of about five months.
   ``Hospitals are for people that are in need of immediate
treatment,'' van der Merwe said. ``If he is not in need of
immediate treatment, then it becomes logical to move him somewhere
else. Whether inside Pollsmoor or outside Pollsmoor is another
question.''
   Asked if Mandela was still in need of immediate care, van der
Merwe replied: ``Not as immediate as before.''
   The government has said it is seriously considering the
possibility of freeing Mandela, whom many blacks consider their
leader. Some officials have suggested that Mandela, after he is
discharged from Tygerberg Hospital, would be moved to a private
clinic and kept there under custody while the government continues
to assess the consequences of his possible relesase.
   About 60 black women from an anti-apartheid organization came to
Tygerberg today with flowers for Mandela. They left the flowers at
a reception desk, then left the hospital dancing and chanting
pro-Mandela slogans.
   The African National Congress is the major guerrilla group
fighting the white-dominated government and its system of apartheid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
