<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-PCBFire     08-25 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-PCB Fire,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evacuated Residents Spend Second Day Away From Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 evacuated residents spent a second
day away from their homes today awaiting the results of soil and
water tests to see whether a PCB fire caused long-term
contamination of their community.
   ``We don't know if we and our homes have been contaminated,''
said Louis Charbonneau, one of 150 frustrated evacuees from
suburban St. Basile-le-Grand being sheltered in a local school.
``My wife is pregnant. What tells us that her pregnancy won't be
affected?''
   The first test results were to be made public later today, but
there was no guarantee the residents would be allowed back into
their homes. Most were staying with friends and relatives.
   The fire burned overnight Tuesday at a depot storing 23,400
gallons of oil tainted with PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls. The
flames sent a toxic black cloud over a 5.5 square mile area. No one
was seriously injured but at least 50 were treated for lung and
skin irritation.
   Quebec Agriculture Minister Michel Page estimated that 400 cows
could have been contaminated, as well as hundreds of acres of
farmland.
   Authorities sealed off the normally tranquil suburb, 15 miles
east of Montreal, and told residents not to eat fruit or vegetables
from their gardens, drink tap water or use backyard pools until
tests were completed.
   PCBs are suspected of causing cancer and production of the
chemical is banned. But supplies formerly used to cool
hydroelectric transformers are stored at depots throughout the
province, which has no facility capable of neutralizing or
destroying the chemicals.
   Some of the 3,000 residents who were whisked from their homes
hired a lawyer on Wednesday to give legal clout to their anger over
the presence of potentially deadly chemicals in their neighborhood.
   ``Clearly, they're looking at a terribly serious type of damage
from the health, economic, commercial ... points of view,'' said
Montreal lawyer Irwin Liebman.
   Dr. Gaetan Carrier of De Maisonneuve-Rosemont Hospital in
Montreal said exposure to PCBs could cause cancers, liver
disorders, skin rashes, birth defects and spontaneous abortions.
   Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa and Environment Minister Clifford
Lincoln flew to St. Basile on Wednesday to face hostile residents
who have lobbied for years to have the PCB dump removed.
   Bourassa said the incident was ``serious but not dramatic,'' and
promised compensation to the victims.
   But residents were not mollified. ``Get that damned stuff out of
here,'' shouted Charbonneau to cheers and applause from the crowd.
``You have turned our town into the garbage can of the province.''
   Quebec Fire Commissioner Cyrille Delage, directing an inquiry
into the fire, said the warehouse's fire and burglar alarm didn't
work.
   But he said the depot's owner, North Central Dynamics Inc., had
conformed with safety regulations introduced by his department in
1985 for storing PCBs.
   Residents have charged, however, that the lack of a fence,
sprinkler system and security guard made the site a time bomb.
   Lincoln said he intends ``to go after'' the company, whose major
shareholder is former Environment Canada employee Marc Levy.
   No cause of the fire has been determined but officials were
considering the possibility of arson because of the manner in which
the warehouse exploded and blazed.
   Only about 5,720 gallons of the PCB-contaminated oil burned,
leaving the problem of how to dispose of the remainder, officials
said.
</TEXT>
