<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ParodySong     08-25 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parody Song,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Station Decides Not To Air Quayle Parody Song</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A musical spoof of Sen. Dan Quayle's
National Guard service has been banned from the radio station where
it first aired, the station manager said today.
   The parody, ``I Spent the War in Indiana,'' was ruled off-limits
by WFBQ's manager Chris Wheat after a close vote by listeners on
whether to continue playing the song.
   The spoof, co-written by station disc jockey Tom Griswold and
local song writer Rickey Ridell, first aired Monday. It was pulled
by Wheat the next day after listener complaints. Wheat then asked
listeners to vote on whether they wanted to keep hearing it.
   The song spoofs Quayle's alleged use of family influence to get
into the Guard in 1969 while others were sent to Vietnam.
   The final tally of the 24-hour call-in vote was 5,182 votes for
the station to continue playing it and 4,676 votes against playing
it.
   Wheat said the 500-vote margin was inconclusive and he feared
the station would alienate half its listeners if the song continued.
   ``Quayle has not been accused of being a draft dodger,'' Wheat
said. ``There has been no proof of that. There was enough in the
song that we felt it was in our best interest to discontinue it.''
   Wheat said he believes Griswold and his sidekick, disc jockey
Bob Kevoian, ``understand that we wanted to protect the radio
station as a whole, and that it wasn't going to be a yes-no,
black-or-white vote. The vote was close and it led me to believe
that to continue playing it would be a detriment to the station.''
   Griswold said he was considering releasing the song on an
inexpensive cassette with proceeds from sales going to the Vietnam
Veterans of America organization.
</TEXT>
