<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--PCBTruck     08-25 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--PCB Truck,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Truck Carrying PCB Contaminated Dirt Stolen On Way To Toxic Dump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck carrying 19 tons of dirt
contaminated with toxic PCBs was stolen outside a truck stop and is
the object of a nationwide alert, police said.
   The truck was stolen Wednesday night when the driver stopped to
eat, Lt. David Hartin said.
   The contaminated dirt apparently was destined for a toxic waste
landfill at Emelle in rural southwest Alabama near the Mississippi
line, Hartin said.
   Ray Strickland, a coordinator for the federal Environmental
Protection Agency in Atlanta, said officials believed the truck was
loaded with dirt from the Texas Eastern pipeline leakage which has
required an extensive cleanup.
   State troopers issued a nationwide bulletin to law officers in
an attempt to locate the black 1980 Peterbilt truck. Hartin said
the truck's trailer was clearly marked with yellow and white
placards warning that its contents were dangerous PCBs.
   PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, can cause cancer and can
cause burns on contact.
</TEXT>
