<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BaikalSwimmer     08-25 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baikal Swimmer,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Plans to Swim Across Lake Baikal Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American swimmer Lynne Cox will take the plunge
into Lake Baikal for a 9.92-mile swim Friday, two days earlier than
scheduled because of forecast bad weather, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said in a dispatch Thursday from the
eastern Siberian city of Irkutsk, where Ms. Cox is training, that
the weather service forecast a heavy storm for the weekend. She had
planned her swim in the world's deepest lake for Sunday.
   ``I am now sure that I will swim well the whole
16-kilometer-long distance from the Tolsty Cap to the Listvyanka
settlement,'' she told Tass after swimming Thursday in the Angara
River.
   The main concern will be the water temperature. Lake Baikal,
shaped like a crescent, is rarely warmer than about 50 degrees
Fahrenheit.
   Ms. Cox, 31, of Los Alamitos, Calif., hopes to be the first
person to swim across Lake Baikal, which reaches a depth of 4,800
feet at some points. It is about 1,800 miles east of Moscow and
north of Mongolia.
   Soviet media have been reporting extensively on her
preparations. Radio Moscow, Tass and Soviet newspapers have run
frequent reports.
   Ms. Cox has been making long-distance swims for more than a
decade. She has tackled the English Channel, the Strait of Magellan
and the Cook Strait. Last year she swam 2.7 miles across the frigid
Bering Strait.
   The endurance swim in Lake Baikal is meant to promote
U.S.-Soviet friendship, peace and sports, she said.
   She has been training by staying in Baikal waters for several
hours a day, Tass said.
</TEXT>
