<1ST_LINE>u a PM-NavyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0527 08-25 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Navy Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0527,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Stands Trial In Death Of Diving-School Recruit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with opening and recessing of
court-martial today. Picks up 5th graf, `A guilty ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers today asked the Navy to
dismiss a dereliction-of-duty charge against a lieutenant who
sought a court-martial in an effort to clear his name in the
training death of a rescue-school recruit.
   The military judge, Cmdr. Newell D. Krogmann, made no immediate
decision on that request.
   He did, however, grant a defense motion for Vice Adm. N.R.
Thunman, who convened the court-martial, to be called as a witness
to answer questions about whether he might be biased against Lt.
Thomas A. Torchia, 32, of Princeton, Ill.
   The trial was then recessed while lawyers met with the judge to
discuss procedural matters.
   In asking for the court-martial, Torchia put his Navy career on
the line, since he was offered unspecified non-judicial punishment
that would have been less severe than what he faces if convicted at
the court-martial.
   Testimony at a June investigative hearing indicated Airman
Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis., was literally scared to
death when Navy rescue swimmer instructors allegedly pushed him
back into a pool and held his head underwater after he had panicked
and climbed out during a drill.
   Mirecki had a phobia about being pulled under water, which
triggered heart failure followed by drowning at Pensacola Naval Air
Station, a pathologist testified.
   Torchia, 32, was formerly in charge of the Navy Rescue Swimmer
School.
   A guilty verdict could bring him up to three months of
confinement, loss of pay and a formal reprimand that could made
advancement in the Navy extremely difficult.
   But by opting for a trial he has an opportunity to exonerate
himself.
   The Navy accuses Torchia of negligently failing to ensure that
Mirecki was permitted to drop out of the voluntary course during a
dangerous training exercise although he knew the recruit had tried
to drop out and was afraid of the water.
   Torchia was in his office overlooking the pool talking on the
telephone at the time of Mirecki's death, witnesses said.
   He is one of two Navy men facing courts-martial as a result of
Mirecki's death. Scheduled for trial Monday is Petty Officer 2nd
Class Michael W. Combe, 26, charged with the more serious counts of
involuntary manslaughter, battery and conspiracy to commit battery.
   Combe is accused of holding Mirecki underwater. If convicted, he
could be dishonorably discharged and sentenced to prison for more
than three years. He was denied the option of accepting less severe
non-judicial punishment.
   Four other instructors, all petty officers, accepted
non-judicial punishment that included reductions in rank for two of
them and fines.
   Mirecki died during a drill known as ``sharks and daisies,'' in
which instructors, playing the role of panicked air-crash
survivors, would randomly grab trainees in head holds.
   Students were supposed to pull the instructors under to break
their grip, then put them in rescue holds and tow them to the side
of the pool.
   After Mirecki was forced back into the pool, Combe put a head
hold on him, according to investigative testimony. Witnesses
differed on whether Mirecki collapsed while in the instructor's
grasp or extricated himself and collapsed while towing Combe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
