<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TropicalWeather     08-25 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tropical Weather,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Flooding Expected From Tropical Depression That Killed Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tropical depression blamed for
three deaths in Puerto Rico began moving over the Dominican
Republic and Haiti today with more flooding expected, forecasters
said.
   The depression was centered about 35 miles west-southwest of
Santo Domingo and was packing winds of 35 mph with storm-force
gusts, according to a 6 a.m. EDT advisory by the National Hurricane
Center in Miami.
   ``The movement over land is the only thing that's keeping this
from strengthening into a tropical storm,'' said forecaster Bob
Case.
   The depression, moving toward the west-northwest at 15 mph, was
expected to trigger rainfall totals of 5 to 10 inches in the
Dominican Republic, where flash-flood warnings were in effect.
   Flash-flood warnings remained in effect for Puerto Rico, where
6.6 inches of rain were reported over the past 24 hours.
   Two men and a 12-year-old boy were killed in Puerto Rico in two
separate incidents Wednesday night when trees crushed their cars as
they were driving along rural roads, police said.
   State Secretary Sila Calderon declared a state of emergency and
National Guard units were mobilized to rescue families trapped by
swollen rivers.
   In Mayaguez on the western side of the island, the Civil Defense
ordered hundreds of residents in low-lying areas to abandon their
homes.
   More than 100 homes in different parts of the island were
destroyed or seriously damaged by flooding, according to the Civil
Defense.
   Education Department Secretary Awilda Aponte Roque closed public
schools throughout Puerto Rico because of flooding danger.
   A second depression remained far off in the Atlantic, about
1,000 miles west-northwest of the Cape Verde Islands off west
Africa. It was moving west at about 17 mph and had sustained winds
of 35 mph.
   ``As far north as it is now, the chances of it getting here are
pretty slim,'' Case said.
   Depressions are upgraded to tropical storms when their sustained
winds reach 39 mph and to hurricanes when winds hit 74 mph.
   There have been two tropical storms so far in the 1988 Atlantic
Ocean hurricane season, but neither reached hurricane strength. The
season runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
