<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0603 08-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0603,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Helicopter Gunships Raid Palestinian Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with details on attack, ADD byline. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli helicopter gunships today rocketed
densely populated districts and Palestinian bases inside a refugee
camp.
   Police said 10 people, including one guerrilla, were wounded in
the six-minute attack south Lebanon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp
that began at 5:45 p.m. Police said three Israeli helicopter
gunships flew in from the Mediterranean Sea to blast their targets.
   The camp is on the outskirts of Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   The helicopters fired at least 10 rockets at civilian
neighborhoods and Palestine Liberation Organization bases on the
main Ein el-Hilweh road, usually crowded at that time of day.
Police said three rockets crashed on the main road, wounding nine
civilians and damaging a car.
   Sidon-based reporters said black smoke billowed from the
stricken targets in Ein el-Hilweh, the largest refugee camp in
Lebanon with 60,000 people.
   Police said four rockets hit an empty two-story base used by the
Palestine Popular Struggle Front, the fourth time in one year the
center has been raided by the Israelis.
   Three other rockets slammed into the one-story office of George
Habash's Marxist group, the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine. Those rockets wounded a guerrilla from the front and
blasted gaping holes in the building.
   A spokesman for the Israeli army command in Jerusalem confirmed
the raid and said its aircraft had returned home safely. He
provided no other details, but Israeli military sources confirmed
that helicopter gunships were used.
   Both officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The raid was Israel's 13th into Lebanon this year. By police
count, 65 people have been killed and 93 wounded in the 12 previous
air raids.
   The last attack was on Aug. 9, when Israeli warplanes bombed a
guerrilla-run radio station in southern Lebanon.
</TEXT>
