<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0510 08-25 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0510,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede ST. LOUIS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Quayle today; pick up 4th graf pvs bgng
``And you know...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle said today he was tired of talking about the controversy
surrounding his military record, saying ``I've answered questions
for seven days now.''
   The Indiana senator said he thought the public also had heard
enough on the issue.
   ``The American people want to talk about the future. I believe
that they're getting a little sick and tired of going back twenty
years,'' he told reporters en route to the Missouri State Fair.
   After avoiding reporters for days, Quayle made himself available
several times today and scheduled a late afternoon news conference.
   On Wednesday, Quayle depicted himself as an expert on defense
matters during a speech before a supportive National Guard group,
and said he won't ``run away'' from the dispute over his own
military record.
   Speaking to a uniformed crowd of 1,000 current and former Guard
members, the Republican vice presidential nominee sought to answer
allegations that he pulled strings to get into the Guard and avoid
duty in Vietnam.
   ``I was not seeking special treatment. I wasn't looking for
favors,'' Quayle said. He said when he joined the Guard in 1969,
``I had no reason to be ashamed of my service.''
   ``And you know what, I'm sure as hell not ashamed of it now!''
Quayle said as his audience cheered.
   Quayle's speech came after a day in which he was carefully
shielded from reporters. Aides acknowledged that they were trying
to shift the focus away from questions about Quayle's own military
record and personal life as he opened his first solo campaign trip.
   David Prosperi, Quayle's press secretary, said the speech was
intended to deal with the Guard question and then ``go beyond to
talk about defense'' and other issues the campaign wanted to stress.
   Quayle sprinkled his speech with sarcastic remarks about ``my
newfound friends in the news media.''
   ``I did in fact eat graham crackers'' as a youngster, ``was very
partial to Superman and Dennis the Menace comic books'' and
``traded Valentine cards with a beautiful second-grader named Penny
who lived across the street,'' Quayle said in a mock ``tell-all''
moment with the audience.
   He said, however, that the scrutiny is a consequence of his vice
presidential candidacy and he is prepared to confront that.
   ``It's not fun, but I knew what I was getting into and I can
tell you, I can take the heat,'' Quayle said.
   In his speech, Quayle said he believed Democratic presidential
nominee Michael Dukakis ``is enjoying this firestorm because it's
helped distract people from the issues of this campaign.''
   He attacked Dukakis for an ``anti-defense attitude'' for
opposing such weapons systems as the Strategic Defense Initiative
and the MX missile.
   ``One of the worst false impressions Michael Dukakis has put
forward is the idea that he stands for a strong national defense,''
Quayle said. ``Maybe he sincerely believes that. But he stands for
the opposite, and that position has been clouded over by the
distractions of the last few days.''
   Quayle had a good-natured encounter at the Lexington, Ky.,
airport with his Democratic counterpart, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, who had just warned Southern state legislators not to ``risk
youthful indiscretion'' in someone like Quayle who might someday
ascend to the presidency.
   Quayle ignored reporters' questions seeking a response to
Bentsen's remarks.
   Bentsen had noted Quayle's abrupt about-face earlier this week
in which he told a Veterans of Foreign Wars convention that
``youthful indiscretion'' was to blame for his vote last month
against elevating the Veterans Administration to a Cabinet-level
department.
</TEXT>
