<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PsychiatricEmergency     08-25 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Psychiatric Emergency,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Declares Emergency at 2 Brooklyn Psychiatric Centers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe overcrowding at two Brooklyn psychiatric
centers led the state commissioner of Mental Health to declare a
state of emergency today, a spokesman for the agency said.
   The declaration will allow the state to immediately transfer 190
patients from the state-run Kingsboro Hospital and 50 from the
Kings County Psychiatric Center, a city-run facility, said
spokesman Steve Osborn.
   ``We're declaring a state of emergency because the extreme
overcrowding is affecting the life and safety of patients at both
hospitals,'' said Osborn, a spokesman for Mental Health
Commissioner Richard C. Surles.
   Most of the patients will be transferred to state facilities on
Long Island and Rockland, Dutchess and Orange counties, he said.
   The Kings County Psychiatric Center has 160 beds for mental
health patients and a current population of 195, Osborn said.
   Matters are worse at the neighboring Kingsboro State Psychiatric
Center, where there are 566 beds and 736 patients, he said.
   The result is that psychiatric patients have been sandwiched six
in a room instead of four, and have been left in beds in hallways
and day rooms, Osborn said. At Kings County, patients have been
left in the emergency room for days, waiting for a room, he added.
</TEXT>
