<DOCNO> AP880825-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Library     08-25 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Library,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Ronald Reagan Library Starts to Take Root</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan will have been out of office
for over two years _ and 80 years old _ when a library housing his
papers and recalling his time in office opens on a cactus-covered
hillside northwest of here, if all goes according to plan.
   Officials originally hoped to make it the first presidential
library to open while the president it honors was still in office,
but those intentions were scuttled by years of controversy and
delay.
   Nonetheless, plans are moving now.
   The city council of Simi Valley, which must provide water and
sewer service to the site on a cactus-covered hillside northwest of
Los Angeles, gave its approval this week.
   ``Everything is chugging along pretty nicely,'' said Ann Rock, a
city council member. ``It looks like we're going to go ahead on
it.''
   Ventura County, which must grant a conditional use permit for
construction, will hold an environmental hearing Aug. 31.
   ``We don't anticipate or see any snail darter incident, although
anything can happen,'' said Carl Morehouse, a staff planner for the
Ventura County government.
   The library will be reached by a winding road that will rise
from an altitude of about 920 feet to 1,190 feet above sea level.
The site commands a spectacular view of the countryside and, on a
clear day, the peaks of the offshore Channel Islands in the
distance.
   It will be the ninth presidential library in the National
Archives system and the first west of the Rockies. The others are
for Herbert Hoover at West Branch, Iowa; Franklin D. Roosevelt at
Hyde Park, N.Y.; Harry S. Truman in Independence, Mo.; Dwight D.
Eisenhower at Abilene, Kan.; John F. Kennedy in Boston; Lyndon B.
Johnson in Austin, Texas; Gerald R. Ford in Ann Arbor, Mich., and
Jimmy Carter in Atlanta.
   Officials of the Ronald Reagan Presidential Foundation are
aiming at breaking ground this fall, possibly in September. Opening
date is tentatively scheduled for 1991.
   Plans to have Reagan's presidential library open while he was
still in the White House were snagged in a controversy over the
site.
   Efforts to locate the library on the campus of Stanford
University in Palo Alto fell through in April 1987 ran into stiff
opposition from faculty and city landowners.
   Fund-raising also did not go as rapidly as hoped, and not all of
the currently estimated cost of $45 million has been raised.
Officials won't say how much they still need.
   Even in its new location, the project aroused some controversy,
particularly since the part of the 100-acre site on which the
building will stand lies within a greenbelt maintained by a
decade-old, non-binding agreement among the communities of Simi
Valley, Moorpark and Thousand Oaks.
   The real estate development firm of Blakeley-Swartz, which
donated the land, originally announced plans to build a 300-room
hotel and conference center on 540 acres adjacent to the library
site.
   Officials of the three communities told the county they did not
want the library ``used as means for further land-use concessions
on any property within the greenbelt.''
   So plans for the hotel and conference center have been dropped.
   In addition to the switch to a Southern California site, there
have been some changes in design.
   When the library was to be built at Stanford, a separate public
affairs institute was planned. Now the project has been scaled down
to just the library, with some rooms for conferences and work space
for Reagan when he visits.
   The basic, mission-style building designed by architects Hugh
Stubbins and Associates for the Stanford site has been retained for
the new location. An arched colonnade that had been designed to
harmonize with other Stanford buildings was dropped in favor of
straight columns and wooden beams more typical of mission
architecture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
