<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FaithfulRider     08-25 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Faithful Rider,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Faithful Bus Rider Travels Half-Million Miles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bus company's most faithful customer
will get free rides for a year after racking up almost 500,000
miles in 45 years of commuting to and from work.
   Texas Bus Lines Inc. gave Helen Csontos the pass in honor of her
estimated 22,000 Galveston-La Marque round trips.
   Ms. Csontos, her arms filled with a bouquet of flowers presented
by Texas Bus President Scott Keller and Galveston Mayor Jan
Coggeshall, found herself surrounded by photographers, camera crews
and reporters as she stepped off the bus from work Wednesday.
   ``I'm a little flabbergasted, I guess,'' the 72-year-old
Galveston native said of all the attention. ``It's real thrilling.''
   Ms. Csontos, who never learned to drive, began commuting on May
1, 1943, her first day on the job as a laboratory technician in a
doctor's office. Her fare then was $1, but it has since increased
to $5.75, for the round-trip of less than 23 miles.
   ``I haven't figured it out, but I imagine I have bought a bus in
that many years,'' she said.
   The bus line keeps good tabs on their best customer, whom they
call ``Miss Helen.''
</TEXT>
