<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WattsRedevelopment     08-25 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Watts Redevelopment,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Agency Gives Initial Approval to Ambitious Watts
Redevelopment Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Community Redevelopment Agency board gave
initial approval to the largest redevelopment plan in Los Angeles
history, an ambitious refurbishing of homes and businesses in the
blighted Watts area.
   The plan approved Wednesday proposes to redevelop more than
1,900 acres of decaying homes, apartments, small businesses,
industrial sites and public housing projects.
   Also envisioned are new factories on abandoned sites, additional
housing, a vocational school and shops and restaurants near the
historic Watts Towers by the end of the century.
   The South Central Los Angeles community of Watts once flourished
with tire and auto plants and other factories. But it was ravaged
after the 1965 black protests that resulted in riots and fires.
   Although there are nice homes and small businesses in Watts, it
is dominated by vacant lots, boarded-up stores, overcrowded slum
apartments and the abandoned factory sites.
   In the first step of the project, the CRA authorized an aerial
survey of a 3-square-mile area.
   ``We see that the time is ripe,'' said Councilwoman Joan Milke
Flores, who represents most of the area and spearheaded the
project. ``All of this will come together to provide some jobs and
increase business development in the area.''
   ``This is what the promise of redevelopment is about, helping
communities in great need,'' added Councilman Robert Farrell, who
represents part of the area.
   More than 56,000 people live in the area and 86 percent of them
are black and 13 percent Hispanic. Most are poor, with an average
income of $11,427. Most residents rent their homes and have not
completed high school.
   Flores said she hopes the project will be funded through private
funds and with federal and state funds from enterprise zone
programs, in which businesses are granted tax breaks and other
incentives to hire the unemployed.
</TEXT>
