<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AeromexicoCrash     08-25 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aeromexico Crash,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Third Plane' Pilot Dismissed From Lawsuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of the so-called third plane
connected to the 1986 collision of an Aeromexico airliner and a
private plane over suburban Cerritos was dismissed as a defendant
in lawsuits filed by victims' families.
   Roland Paul Furman of Buena Park did not contribute to the
collision by making a radio call to an air traffic controller, U.S.
District Judge David V. Kenyon ruled Wednesday.
   Documents prepared by Furman's attorney, Stephen L. Nelson, said
Furman's plane was 10 miles from the collision when he communicated
with controller Walter White.
   Nelson said White became aware of Furman's plane on his radar
eight to 20 seconds after the airliner and the single-engine Piper
Archer collided on Aug. 31, 1986. Eighty-two people were killed,
including everyone aboard the two planes and some people on the
ground.
   Nelson said Furman had been named in at least 25 lawsuits.
   ``The claims against Furman are based on the theory that his
presence in the Los Angeles Terminal Control Area distracted White
from Aeromexico and (the Piper Archer) somehow contributed to the
cause ... (but) undisputed facts in the case undercut this
theory,'' Kenyon wrote.
</TEXT>
