<2ND_LINE>AM-Vice Arrests,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Promise to Investigate Wrong Arrests in Vice Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Thursday they were
investigating the arrests of teen-agers wrongfully accused of
prostitution during a vice sweep.
   A senior officer was assigned to head the internal police
investigation, said Deputy Commissioner Godwin Mabika.
   Helmeted riot police and uniformed patrolmen rounded up young
women in downtown Harare this week as part of a drive against
street crime and prostitution.
   But police confirmed that vacationing schoolgirls, teen-agers
going to a movie theater and at least one foreign tourist were
caught in the sweep. They were among some 150 girls and young women
detained in communal cells at the central police station in Harare.
   Police did not say how many of the 150 were wrongly arrested.
   Press reports said many of those arrested, including one
14-year-old girl, were made to sign ``admission of guilt'' papers
and pay fines to secure their release. Teen-agers were denied
access to legal advice, the reports said.
   Zimbabwe's biggest daily, The Herald, Thursday attributed
arrests of innocent bystanders to ``bungling'' by police. It quoted
legislator Sydney Malunga as saying police sweeps violated human
rights.
   Several thousand women have been arrested in periodic police
operations against prostitution since independence in 1980.
</TEXT>
