<HEAD>Federal Agents Search Lawmakers' Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators with warrants
searched the state Capitol offices of a half dozen members of the
California Legislature and their aides, the FBI announced today.
   The FBI refused to reveal the names of the lawmakers or even the
subject of the investigation, but a Capitol source, who declined to
be identified, said all of the objects of the search warrants were
involved in the passage of a bill involving investment banking
regulations.
   The searches late Wednesday were part of an ongoing
investigation, said Terry Knowles, special agent in charge of the
Sacramento FBI office.
   A Capitol employee said a team of about 30 federal investigators
from the FBI and U.S. Attorney's office served search warrants on
the offices of at least one state senator and two members of the
Assembly _ all from Southern California.
   The source said the subject of the warrants was a bill
regulating commercial banks which passed the Legislature with only
minimal opposition earlier this year and was vetoed by the governor.
</TEXT>
