<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SelmaMayor     08-25 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selma Mayor,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Selma Elections Spark Arrests; Results Still Not Certified</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MY2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council deadlocked along racial
lines on whether to certify the election of Mayor Joe Smitherman to
a seventh term, with his black challenger claiming the mayor was a
``dictator'' who had stolen the election.
   Two people were charged with disorderly conduct Wednesday in
this town of 27,000 people that is a landmark of the civil rights
movement, after the council split 3-3 on whether to accept
Tuesday's vote.
   Smitherman's main challenger, City Councilman Cleophus Mann, who
is seeking to become Selma's first black mayor, said one precinct
did not open on time Tuesday and that there were other
irregularities.
   ``You stole it!'' Mann shouted at the meeting.
   ``We might as well have been in Panama,'' he said. ``We sit
around and let a dictator run things.''
   Returns showed Smitherman receiving 3,752 votes in Tuesday's
three-way, non-partisan election. Mann received 2,769 votes; Coy
Darby, a white challenger, received 453 votes.
   If the results are upheld, Smitherman would not face a runoff
election, because he received more than 50 percent of the vote.
   After the meeting, Mann nearly came to blows with city attorney
Henry Pitts, and one campaign aide and another man were arrested on
charges of disorderly conduct.
   A second council meeting, Wednesday afternoon, was boycotted by
the council's three black members. Without a quorum, no action
could be taken.
   ``This is one of the worst incidents I've seen since 1964,''
Smitherman said, referring to the year he first took office as
mayor and the year when voting rights demonstrations first brought
national attention to the city.
   ``That's the old civil rights crowd, and they're trying to
rehash the '60s,'' Smitherman said. ``This is not a representative
of the black citizens of Selma. That was a bunch of disruptive
goons and they got what they came for.''
   On March 7, 1965, several hundred civil rights activists began a
50-mile voting rights march to Montgomery. State troopers and
sheriff's deputies, acting under orders from Gov. George Wallace,
beat marchers as they tried to cross the Edmund Pettus Bridge.
   Television film of the beatings shocked the nation. Two weeks
later, a second, much larger march left Selma with the support of
the federal government.
   The clash also was credited with spurring Congress to pass the
Voting Rights Act, which removed the poll tax and other legal
barriers that had discouraged black voter registration.
   Smitherman said he planned to file a lawsuit to certify the
election results.
   Arrested after Wednesday's council clash were the Rev. Ernest
Swift Sr., 42, one of Mann's campaign workers; and Byron Douglas
Smith, 21. Pitts said both men shouted at him and threatened him.
   Swift was arrested a second time when, released from jail, he
returned to City Hall and shouted at the mayor that he was ``still
a crook because you had people crooked at the polls.''
   Later, a policeman was stationed in front of Smitherman's office
and extra patrols were scheduled for his home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
