<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     08-25 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0914</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muhammad Ali, the boxer who
dubbed himself ``the greatest,'' is receiving blood-cleansing
treatments from a doctor he calls the greatest in the world.
   The 46-year-old former heavyweight champion walked into a
hospital waiting room Wednesday throwing jabs in the air minutes
after undergoing an eight-hour blood treatment to relieve slurred
speech and tremors that have plagued him in recent years.
   The doctor blames Ali's condition on household pesticide
poisoning and not blows to the head.
   ``I feel like I can fight (heavyweight champ Mike) Tyson,'' Ali
said in a hoarse voice slightly above a whisper at Hilton Head
Hospital.
   Ali referred questions to his physician, Rajko Medenica, an
immunologist who specializes in cancer and blood disorders.
   Ali underwent plasmapheresis, during which his plasma was
removed and replaced with an artificial product prepared by
Medenica. Plasma is the fluid in which other components of the
blood circulate in the body.
   Although Ali has been diagnosed as having parkinsonian syndrome,
possibly brought on by blows to the head during his boxing career,
Medenica disagrees.
   Calling it ``The Muhammad Ali Syndrome,'' he blamed household
pesticide poisoning, which probably affected him so severely
because of his rapid metabolism when he was in peak physical
condition.
   Ali likely will return for treatments every three months or so,
Medenica said.
   ``My goal is to remove the circulating toxins. By the end of the
year, he should be much better,'' he said.
   Although Ali had trouble speaking, he moved with ease and
appeared to be in good spirits. Ali called Medenica the greatest
doctor in the world.
   ``He's got methods I've never seen before,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American soprano Maria Ewing, who won rave reviews
when she danced naked as Salome in her debut at London's Royal
Opera House in April, is seeking a divorce from husband Sir Peter
Hall, artistic director of Britain's National Theater.
   Her lawyer Anthony Rubenstein said Wednesday that the
38-year-old Detroit-born singer will file a petition for divorce
from 57-year-old Hall as soon as possible.
   The couple married in 1982 and have a 6-year-old daughter.
   Hall, who plans to launch his own production company in
September when his contract expires, has headed the prestigious
state-funded National Theater since 1973. He made no comment on the
divorce.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RIMINI, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French philosopher Jean Guitton accepted
the Fiuggi-Meeting 1988 award, which recognizes those who
``distinguish themselves in defending the cultural and religious
values of man.''
   Guitton, 87, a member of the French Academy since 1961, has
written about the relationship between Catholicism and modern
thought.
   The award, a plaque and $21,645, was given Thursday by Foreign
Minister Giulio Andreotti, who called Guitton ``one of the great
figures of European culture and contemporary Catholicism.''
   Addressing youths in the audience, Guitton said they have the
duty to ``help humanity and the church to continue to live and not
just survive. Maybe the 21st century, thanks to you, will be an
even more enlightening century.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo has agreed to testify in a case
involving his former law firm.
   After almost nine years of postponements and delays, lawyers
this month subpoenaed Cuomo to appear in court with his financial
records.
   ``We were willing to object to the method by which these
subpoenas were served,'' Cuomo's lawyer, Peter J. Johnson Jr., told
state Supreme Court Justice Carmine Ventiera, according to New York
Newsday.
   ``He (Cuomo) almost blew me out of the water when he said,
`Forget about it. I can't wait to testify. I want the truth to be
told,''' Johnson said Wednesday.
   The dispute involves nearly $6 million in legal fees.
   Cuomo is suing his former law partner, Michael Nicholson, and
Nicholson's wife and current partner, Diane, for a share of the
fees earned by the law firm after he left in 1975.
   The estate of Peter E. Dwyer, a late partner in the firm, also
is suing the Nicholsons for a share of the fees.
   The Nicholsons have in turn sued Cuomo, claiming he accepted a
$100,000 liquidation fee when he resigned in 1975.
   Cuomo contends the Nicholsons deliberately underestimated the
firm's assets at the time the liquidation fee was assessed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Distance runner Zola Budd, who
dropped out of international racing in May, says she's engaged to
marry a liquor store owner in her hometown.
   Budd told the independent South African Press Association on
Thursday that the engagement ``happened very suddenly yesterday.''
   Her fiance, Mike Pieterse, 26, who said he had known Budd for
about two years, told the the government-run South African
Broadcasting Corp. that the couple had not set a wedding date.
   Since her return to South Africa in May from Britain, Budd has
been a student at the University of the Orange Free State in her
hometown, Bloemfontein.
   Budd, 21, moved to Britain in 1984 and received a British
passport within weeks, allowing her to compete in the Olympic Games
in Los Angeles that year.
   South Africa is banned from most international sports because of
its apartheid policies of racial segregation. Anti-apartheid groups
have staged demonstrations virtually everywhere Budd raced in the
last four years.
</TEXT>
