<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     08-25 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament in Chaos as Government Presses on With Apartheid Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the anti-apartheid
Progressive Federal Party walked out of Parliament on Thursday to
protest a government manuever aimed at pushing through
controversial legislation.
   One of the bills would strengthen enforcement of the Group Areas
Act, which mandates racially segregated residential areas. Another
would give authorities more powers to evict black squatters.
   President P.W. Botha's National Party holds an overwhelming
majority in Parliament's white chamber and is able to gain support
for most legislation from the majority parties in the two smaller
chambers, one for Asians and one for people of mixed-race.
   The two non-white chambers, however, have refused to consider
the current bills, insisting instead on total repeal of the Group
Areas Act.
   The black majority is excluded from Parliament and has no vote
in national affairs.
   The leader of the white chamber, F.W. de Klerk, announced
Thursday that parliamentary rules would be suspended so the six
pending bills could be dealt with solely by the white legislators.
   Progressive Federal members said the rule change made a farce of
the parliamentary process.
   ``You are doing it to pass laws which are repugnant to the vast
majority of people in South Africa,'' said the party's whip, John
Malcomness. ``If you put them to a referendum of all the people of
South Africa, they will be massively rejected.''
   The far-right Conservative Party, which favors a strengthening
of apartheid laws, joined the Progressive Federal Party in
condemning the rule change, which was approved on a 116-35 vote.
   Last week, Botha said 80 percent of South Africa's whites and 70
percent of Asian and mixed-race voters would endorse residential
segregation in a referendum. The Rev. Allan Hendrickse, leader of
the mixed-race chamber, has dared Botha to arrange such an election.
   The proposed amendment to the Group Areas Act would sharply
increase penalties for violators and would negate a current court
ruling that violators could be evicted only if alternative housing
were available.
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe said the act was
virtually unenforceable at present and needed amendment ``to give
people a sense of security.''
   In the United States, he said, wealthy people could buy their
way into neighborhoods with de facto segregation.
   ``We only want to create the same option for people in South
Africa,'' he said, noting that the government has proposed allowing
some multiracial neighborhoods for people who desire them.
</TEXT>
