<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ByAppearances     08-25 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-By Appearances,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Votes to Let Police Arrest People Who Look Like Drug
Dealers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has voted to let police arrest
and search people who look or act like drug dealers _ regardless of
whether the people are seen making drug deals.
   The ordinance, approved Wednesday, also says such loiterers may
be fined $500 if they are known drug dealers or pass money,
packages or written material to passers-by in an area known for
drug sales.
   Civil libertarians questioned the ordinance, which says someone
may be arrested who ``loiters in a public place in a manner and
under circumstances manifesting the purpose of selling any illegal
controlled substance ...''
   A known drug dealer is defined as someone who has been convicted
of drug charges within the last year.
   Councilman Al Gonzalez said he proposed the ordinance at the
request of Lou Caudell, first assistant police chief.
   ``This allows uniformed police officers to get actively involved
in the war on drugs,'' said police Lt. Doug Kowalski.
   But Joe Cook, president of the Dallas chapter of the American
Civil Liberties Union, said he expected the group to challenge the
ordinance because it treads on due process and civil rights.
   Cook said such an ordinance could be used to harass political
activities and could increase tension between police and the city's
minority communities.
   Councilwoman Diane Ragsdale initially cast the only vote in
opposition to the ordinance, saying she feared the rights of
innocent people could be trampled.
   But she later reversed her vote, saying she would seek
assurances from Police Chief Mack Vines that the ordinance would
not be abused.
</TEXT>
