<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks 4thLd-Writethru a0575 08-25 0734</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0575,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Hold First Direct Peace Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with direct talks ended,
indirect talks beginning, U.N. chief may appoint panel to determine
who started gulf war. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``The Council...'' TRIMS
thereafter to tighten.
^By VICTORIA GRAHAM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq today held
the first direct peace talks between their countries since the
Persian Gulf war began eight years ago. The talks were mediated by
the head of the United Nations.
   Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and his Iraqi
counterpart, Tariq Aziz, sat at separate tables facing each other
across a spacious room. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
faced them from a third table.
   The meeting was suspended after 2{ hours, U.N. spokesman
Francois Giuliani told reporters. Afterward, the Iranian and Iraqi
delegations moved to separate rooms and U.N. officials shuttled
between the two groups and reported to the secretary-general, who
remained in the room where the direct talks were held.
   ``They are consulting,'' Giuliani told reporters. ``It is not a
bad sign, nor a good sign, it's a normal process of consultation,''
he said when asked by reporters if there was a problem with the
talks. ``Please don't interpret this as a sign that things are
going well, or badly. They are going normally.''
   Earlier Giuliani told reporters the talks would continue through
Sunday.
   Western diplomatic sources, meanwhile, said the
secretary-general was considering naming a three-man panel to
determine which side started the war. The sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said one representative could be from Iran,
one from Iraq and one from the International Court of Justice.
   The direct talks were held in the Art Deco-style Council Chamber
of the Palais de Nations. The two foreign ministers and their aides
entered separately from the right and left sides. The ministers did
not exchange greetings.
   Reporters were present briefly and watched the beginning of the
session on closed-circuit television. As reporters left, Aziz
lighted a cigar.
   ``Your excellencies, I warmly welcome you,'' Perez de Cuellar
said in English as he led the meeting. The Iraqi delegation of 15
was seated to his left and the Iranian delegation of 13 was to his
right in a triangular set-up of long, widely separated tables.
   The U.N. chief said he hoped ``our discussions would be
businesslike, constructive and, indeed, productive.''
   The Council Chamber overlooks Lake Geneva and is decorated with
gold leaf and sepia ink murals of human progress and abolition of
war.
   The peace process was expected to be long and troublesome. The
issues are numerous _ from disputed border locations to prisoners
of war _ and the bitterness between the Persian and the Arab sides
runs deep.
   Since a U.N.-supervised cease-fire began six days ago, both
sides have traded charges of truce violations and questioned their
adversary's sincerity and will for peace. But no serious fighting
has been reported.
   Earlier today, Aziz and Velayati met separately with Perez de
Cuellar. Both ministers were accompanied by their delegations and
ignored questions shouted at them from about 100 reporters pressing
against crowd control barriers in the main entrance of the building.
   Perez de Cuellar said he expects direct talks between Iraq and
Iran to last months, but some diplomats believe the peace process
could drag on for years.
   Arriving in Geneva today, Velayati said the talks should
``arrive at a just, comprehensive, honorable and durable settlement
of all outstanding issues between Iran and Iraq.''
   Iran accepted the U.N. cease-fire resolution July 18 after a
string of battlefield defeats. Iraq had agreed to the resolution
shortly after the Security Council passed it in July 1987.
   The agenda for the Iran-Iraq talks could include troop
withdrawal to international borders, resolution of a border
dispute, repatriation of prisoners of war, reparations, freedom of
navigation in the disputed Shatt al-Arab waterway and the gulf and
other issues.
   Iran also is insisting on the creation of an impartial body to
determine which side started the war. It has said that Iraq must be
branded the aggressor if there is to be lasting peace.
   Iraq invaded Iran in September 1980 after border skirmishes.
   Any ruling on guilt in the war would affect the question of
reparations. Official Iranian assessments have put the cost of war
damage at $350 billion. Iraq has not given an estimate.
</TEXT>
