<DOCNO> AP880825-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PizzaFight     08-25 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pizza Fight,0241</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bid Squabble Delays Pizza Delivery To Baltimore Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival pizza suppliers are fighting, and the
result is that school cafeterias will do without for at least five
weeks, officials said.
   ``It's going to cause a riot,'' Leonard Smackum, director of
food service for the Baltimore school system warned the Board of
Estimates on Wednesday. ``Pizza is our most popular item.''
   The board voted to toss out bids on 760,000 slices of cheese
pizza and re-advertise the contract after spending nearly an hour
listening to two vendors argue over whose bid was lower.
   On a 3-1 vote, the board decided the bidding process made it
difficult to determine which of the two bids, $219,000 or $229,000,
was actually the lowest.
   The dispute arose when Nardone Brothers Baking Co. of
Pennsylvania said it would add two-tenths of an ounce of cheese on
each slice beyond the 2 ounces required by the contract, thus
providing tastier pizza.
   The extra cheese would be free to the city as long as the
federal government continued to provide free cheese through a
surplus program, said a spokesman for Nardone.
   But the rival supplier said the federal program could end this
year, raising the cost of the pizza.
   The start of the school year may be saved for pupils, however.
   The Board of Estimates approved contracts with suppliers of
Mexican-style pizza and French-bread pizza.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
