<DOCNO> AP880825-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-25 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget the radio weatherman: A new
sculpture installed downtown gives a multimedia performance along
with the forecast.
   The Portland Weather Machine comes to life at noon.
   It sprays water, blinks lights, plays a trumpet fanfare and
releases one of three weather symbols from a steel globe _ a
gold-leaf sun for clear days, a silvery blue heron for
precipitation, and a roaring copper dragon for a storm.
   The 30-foot sculpture also includes a weathervane for wind
direction and a series of lights that indicate the temperature. To
show air quality, a lens glows green on clear days, amber on hazy
days and red on smoggy ones.
   Some 500 people attended the sculpture's unveiling Wednesday by
another famous weather performer, Willard Scott of NBC's ``Today
Show.''
   ``The Weather Machine will help us recognize and celebrate the
weather in a unique, fun way,'' said David Porter, executive
director of Pioneer Courthouse Square. The contraption, which had
been in the works for nearly five years, was designed by four local
artists.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who found a message in a bottle
washed upon the shore was treated to a cruise of Narragansett Bay
by the yachtswoman who set the bottle afloat.
   Karen Durfee and her four children cruised Newport Harbor and
the bay aboard Iver and Susie Neilsen's 52-foot ketch Tuesday
night. ``It was great; it was really neat,'' Ms. Durfee said.
``They don't get to do something like that ever.''
   Mrs. Neilsen said she dropped the bottle into the ocean Aug. 1
off Cape May, N.J., as she and her husband passed northward while
taking another yacht to Newport. Three days later, Ms. Durfee found
the bottle on the Sakonnet River shore in Little Compton.
   ``It was just a silly idea to see if anyone would find it,'' Ms.
Neilsen said. ``Can you believe it only took three days for the
bottle to float up here? I actually threw two bottles overboard,
and the second one washed up in almost the same place. We got a
call from someone in Little Compton and we're waiting for them to
call back.''
   Ms. Neilsen, who with her husband runs a summertime charter
business, said a similar evening cruise usually costs around $400.
</TEXT>
