<DOCNO> AP880825-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NJSchools     08-25 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NJ Schools,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: School Funding Is Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey's system of paying for public
education is unconstitutional and discriminates against poor urban
districts, an administrative law judge ruled Thursday.
   ``There are unmet educational needs in poor, urban districts and
vast program and expenditure disparities between property-rich
suburban and property-poor urban school districts,'' Judge Steven
L. Lefelt said.
   The ruling comes after nearly two decades of legal and
legislative battles, and once again throws into question the way
the state funds public schools. It could force the state to spend
millions of dollars more each year on education.
   ``I do not believe that poor urban districts, even with better
management practices and the expulsion of politics, could raise
sufficient funds ... to address all of the disparities and unmet
needs that I believe must be addressed under our constitution,''
Lefelt said.
   His ruling capped a seven-year legal battle over a lawsuit
brought on behalf of 20 school-age children in Camden, Irvington,
East Orange and Jersey City.
   The suit charged that the state funding system leaves poorer
districts with far less money than their surburban counterparts and
creates disparities in the quality of education.
   Education Commissioner Saul Cooperman has 45 days in which to
accept, modify or reject Lefelt's ruling.
   Lawyers for the state and the group that filed the suit, the
Newark-based Education Law Center, predict the case eventually will
go to the state Supreme Court.
   Although Lefelt's ruling is a major victory for the law group,
the judge did not agree with the group's contention that New
Jersey's funding system is intentionally discriminatory. Instead,
he said, it is ``motivated by cost efficiency and not race.''
   Lefelt said the Legislature must revamp the system so poor
districts receive more money to improve schools.
   His decision came more than 15 years after the Supreme Court
first ruled that New Jersey's former system of funding education,
with its heavy reliance on property taxes, discriminated against
poorer districts.
   The Legislature then enacted a school funding formula, and
passed a state income tax in 1976 to pay for it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
