<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Chile     08-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Chile,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Praises Chile Move on Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Thursday praised the
lifting of restrictions on civil rights in Chile and expressed hope
that the action will lead to additional steps that will allow ``the
full and free expression of popular will.''
   The move Wednesday by Chile's military leaders was the first
time since they took power in 1973 that the state of emergency had
been lifted.
   The announcement came less than a week before the expected
selection by the country's four-man junta of President Augusto
Pinochet as the sole candidate in a presidential referendum later
this year.
   Successive U.S. administrations have been hostile to Pinochet's
rule, and Thursday's statement by State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley was one of the few positive comments about Chile's
leadership in 15 years.
   ``The U.S. government has stated on repeated occasions that the
continuation of states of exception which limits basic civil rights
is incompatible with democratic electoral processes,'' Mrs. Oakley
said.
   She said the termination of the ``states of exception'' is a
``positive step which we applaud.''
   ``We firmly hope that this decision by the Chilean government
signals a lasting guarantee of the civil rights of the Chilean
poeple,'' she added. ``We also hope that by ending the states of
exception, the Chilean government is indicating a sincere desire to
take further steps to allow the full and free expression of popular
will.''
</TEXT>
