<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FuelBarge     08-25 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fuel Barge,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fuel Removed From Crippled Barge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KILMARNOCK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of a day-old 168,000-gallon gasoline
and diesel fuel spill in Chesapeake Bay dissipated by midday
Thursday and a 2-square-mile slick was fading quickly, a Coast
Guard official said.
   The crippled barge from which the fuel leaked was loading its
remaining 651,000 gallons into another vessel, an operation that
was expected to be completed late Thursday night, said Cmdr. George
Naccara, executive officer of the Coast Guard's Marine Safety
office in Hampton Roads.
   The 168,000 gallons leaked from two ruptured tanks Wednesday,
leaving an 18-square-mile slick near the western shore of the lower
bay. However, Naccara said most of the fuel already had dissipated
by midday Thursday.
   ``We completed a helicopter fly-over of the entire bay, and
there's absolutely nothing to be seen,'' Naccara said Thursday
afternoon.
   Although a 2-square-mile ``rainbow sheen'' remained on nearby
Fleets Bay, he said, that was rapidly disppearing.
   Naccara said state officials planned to meet Thursday with a
representative of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration to discuss the impact of the spill.
   The 240-foot, 37-year-old barge was being towed from Baltimore
to Richmond by the tug Oceola when the leak was reported about 7:30
a.m. Wednesday.
   The barge ran aground in about 12 feet of water as it headed for
a Kilmarnock pier, Naccara said. The barge was surrounded with a
containment boom to halt the spread of fuel.
   The barge is owned by Eastern Carriers Inc. of Hockessin, Del.
Naccara said the company sent a second barge to help offload the
fuel Thursday morning.
</TEXT>
