<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama     08-25 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Claims Noriega `Weaker By The Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, a leader
of forces opposed to Panama's military leader Manuel Antonio
Noriega, said Thursday a combination of factors has led to a
``dramatic deterioration'' of Noriega's public support.
   ``Noriega's government is weaker by the day. The regime is
fighting for its survival,'' Sosa told a news conference he called
six months to the day after Panama's upheaval began with the failed
attempt to oust Noriega as commander of Panama's Defense Forces.
   Sosa continues to serve as Panama's ambassador to the United
States, sharing the U.S. position that President Eric Arturo
Delvalle is the legitimate authority in Panama. Delvalle was ousted
the day after his abortive attempt to fire Noriega.
   Sosa, who retains control over Panama's embassy despite the
Noriega government's attempt to replace him, said public opposition
to Noriega was evident earlier this month when hundreds of
thousands of Panamanians turned out for the funeral of former
President Arnulfo Arias.
   As a further sign of what he called ``the dramatic deterioration
of the regime,'' Sosa said there has been a wave of strikes
recently, widespread anti-government demonstrations by high school
students and loss of diplomatic support in Latin America.
   Noriega has responded by imposing strict curbs on independent
news media, Sosa said.
   ``We do not think that we are in a paralysis. We know we are
making progress. We know that Noriega is today more weakened than
he was three months ago and definitely more weakened than he was
six months ago,'' Sosa said.
   Sosa suggested that Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis was being misleading earlier Thursday when he said the
Reagan administration had engaged in ``criminal'' dealings with
Noriega, ignoring the military leader's alleged involvement in drug
trafficking. Noriega has been indicted on drug charges by two
federal grand juries in Florida.
   Based on what he has read, Sosa said, ``past mistakes'' by the
United States concerning Panama date back to 1972 and have been
committed by every administration since then.
   Insisting that it would be improper to dwell on the past, Sosa
said ``as long as the administration is constructive, positive and
supportive of our efforts, that is what we want.''
   Sosa, alluding to the series of economic sanctions the
administration has imposed against Panama, said he is grateful for
the U.S. contribution to the anti-Noriega cause.
   Among other measures, the United States has imposed a series of
economic sanctions against Panama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
