<DOCNO> AP880825-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burundi Bjt   08-25 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burundi, Bjt,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burundi's Leader Says Soldiers Killed Civilians In Reprisal For
Massacres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burundi's leader said Thursday his
soldiers killed civilians in reprisals for the massacres of rival
tribesmen, and he said the death toll from the ethnic war could
rise above 5,000.
   The leader, Maj. Pierre Buyoya, was quoted on state-run Radio
Burundi, monitored in neighboring Rwanda. More than 41,000
Burundians have fled to Rwanda to escape fighting between the
majority Hutu and the minority Tutsi, who control Burundi's
government and military.
   The government said Monday that 5,000 people were killed, but
Buyoya said some bodies may not have been counted. The government
said its initial figure came from gravediggers sent to bury the
dead.
   Buyoya said the soldiers who killed Hutu civilians were not
acting under government orders but started the slaughter after
discovering the bodies of Tutsi tribesmen.
   Many of the Hutu refugees fleeing to Rwanda arrived with
bayonet, knife and bullet wounds, as well as stories of soldiers
killing Hutu on sight. Until Thursday, the Burundi government
denied those allegations.
   The trouble began Aug. 14 when the Hutu attacked Tutsi in two
communities in northern Burundi, hacking hundreds to death with
machetes and burning people alive in huts, refugees said.
   Buyoya blamed the trouble on exiled Hutu he said had crossed
from Tanzania.
   But refugees blamed most of the deaths on Burundi's
Tutsi-dominated army.
   ``The soldiers were rounding up Hutus and shooting them,'' one
refugee said. ``They are collecting them into groups, taking them
inside houses, closing the doors and windows and then shooting.''
   Reverin Ndururutse, 32, said his 5-year-old nephew and his
3-year-old son were the only survivors of a family of 15 herded
into a house by soldiers who opened fire. He said the adults threw
themselves on top of the two children.
   In Washington, the State Department said Hutu civilians, not the
army, probably initiated the violence. Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
said, ``It's a tragic situation'' and said the United States was
giving emergency aid to the refugees in Rwanda.
   Rwanda appealed for international aid for the sudden influx of
refugees, who still are arriving at an average of 2,000 per day,
according to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees office in
Rwanda.
   Rwanda is the most densely populated nation in Africa, and the
refugees are severely straining the impoverished country's
resources.
   Burundi has asked the refugees to return home and promised to
help them resettle.
   In an appeal to diplomatic missions Thursday, Burundi asked for
international aid to help rehabilitate the 100,000 people it said
were affected by the slaughter.
   The government said it would need enough tents, blankets,
cooking utensils, food and other supplies to aid the affected
population for three months, according to a Western diplomat in
Burundi's capital, Bujumbura.
   ``It just said it had taken stock of what was needed, but did
not state amounts,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of
anonymity in a telephone interview.
   The note did not explain how the government arrived at the
100,000 figure or the three-month time frame, said the diplomat.
   Buyoya said Wednesday his government was trying to restore order
and promised that those found guilty of involvement in the
slaughter would be punished, Radio Burundi reported in a broadcast
monitored in Nairobi.
   He appealed to those who lost their relatives ``to refrain from
acts of violence and revenge. Such behavior may reverse our aim of
forging ahead in developing Burundi.''
   Buyoya, who seized power in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987, said
the victims of the fighting ``belonged to all tribes,'' according
to the broadcast.
   Buyoya said his government would try as soon as possible to lift
a 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew. The government also has restricted
travel between towns and banned meetings of more than five people.
   Rwanda and Burundi, former Belgium colonies, each are about the
size of Maryland. About 6.1 million people are crammed into Rwanda,
while 5 million live in Burundi, Africa's second most densely
populated country.
   The short, stocky Hutu comprise about 84 percent of the
population in both nations and the tall, lanky Tutsi 15 percent.
But the Hutu have ruled in Rwanda since 1959, when they overthrew
the former Tutsi-dominated government and killed an estimated
100,000 people.
   In Burundi, the Tutsi have held onto power. The most serious
threat to Tutsi rule was in 1972, when the Hutu attempted a coup,
killing hundreds of Tutsi before the rebellion was crushed.
   The government retaliated by slaughtering between 100,000 and
300,000 Hutu, incuding most of the tribe's intelligentsia,
according to human rights groups.
</TEXT>
