<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DicksonToDixon Bjt   08-25 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dickson To Dixon, Bjt,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cheering Crowd Greets Soviet Delegation In Dixon</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DIXON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Applause, hearty handshakes and declarations
of friendship and world peace greeted a small delegation from
Dickson, Siberia, on Thursday on the first visit by Soviet citizens
to President Reagan's boyhood home.
   Autograph seekers and well-wishers crowded the yard around the
two-story, white frame house where Ronald ``Dutch'' Reagan lived in
1920 as a 9-year-old boy with his parents, Jack and Nelle, and
older brother Neil.
   A private tour of the Reagan home topped the agenda for Dickson
Mayor Nikolai T. Kartamyshev, journalist Boris S. Ivanov and
interpreter Nikolai S. Vishnevsky of Moscow.
   ``I have written in the special (guest) book inside that a great
man deserved a great memory and I am happy to be at such a special
place,'' Kartamyshev said as the delegation finished its tour of
the three-bedroom house.
   ``There are a lot of great men who have come from small and
ordinary places,'' he said.
   Mayor James E. Dixon of the host city doffed his straw top hat
and officially welcomed the Soviet group.
   ``They are trying to show us that they are good people and they
want peace,'' Dixon said. ``I hope they will go back knowing we are
their friends.''
   Dixon said the Soviet visitors were suffering from jet lag,
having arrived in this town of 15,700 aobut 100 miles west of
Chicago, late Wednesday night. But they appeared enthusiastic when
greeted by a crowd of about 100.
   ``We are carrying with us warmest greetings from all the
residents of Dickson,'' Kartamyshev said. ``Now we can say
something has been achieved with our sister-city ties.''
   Many in the crowd wore buttons proclaiming ``Peace on Earth'' in
English and Russian. Others had pictures of the flags of the United
States and the Soviet Union.
   As the Soviets made their way from their tour car to the house,
they were stopped several times by onlookers who shook their hands,
slapped their backs and welcomed them.
   A local radio station broadcast the ceremonies live, including a
15-minute speech by Kartamyshev, who also answered questions from
reporters.
   ``We associate Reagan with the positive changes in relations
between our countries,'' Kartamyshev said. ``It's interesting to
see where he spent his childhood.''
   The Soviet mayor said he hoped the spirit of ``glasnost,'' a new
spirit of openness in Soviet society, would allow a reciprocal
visit by Dixon's mayor and other Americans to his town. It is a
remote, frontier village of about 5,000 in extreme northern
Siberia, above the Arctic Circle.
   Dickson, named for Oskar Dickson, a 19th-century Swedish
merchant who provided supplies for expeditions for early Arctic
explorers, generally is closed to foreign visitors because of
nearby military installations.
   Kartamyshev said he no longer fears a world war between the
superpowers because of Reagan's recent peace initiatives and said
the Dickson-to-Dixon good-will summit was evidence of the U.S.
president's success.
   The Soviets brought gifts for their hosts, including a medallion
inscribed ``From Dickson With Love'' and bearing the American and
Soviet flags united in a heart-shape.
   Reagan, son of a shoe salesman and a dressmaker, lived in Dixon
from 1920 until he left for college in 1928.
   However, his parents never owned a house and lived in several
places during the 17 years they called Dixon home.
   The house picked as the Reagan museum was the first place the
family lived in Dixon and it's the home Reagan said he remembered
best.
   The Soviets where shown the bed Reagan shared with his brother,
the wallpaper in the living room, decorated just as it was in 1920,
and they even saw the loose tile around the fireplace where Reagan
hid pennies.
</TEXT>
