<HEAD>Police Search For Japanese Suspected of Terrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police were searching Thursday for a
Japanese man suspected of being a leftist radical banned from South
Korea. Authorities are concerned about possible terrorist
infiltration before the Olympic Games.
   Police officials said they were looking for a man identified as
Hiroyaki Kawamura, who arrived in Seoul on a 30-day tourist visa.
They said there is a ban on a leftist of that name, but they did
not know if it was the same man.
   South Korean authorities have been on the lookout for terrorists
who might try to disrupt the Olympic Games, scheduled in Seoul
Sept. 17-Oct. 2.
   A senior member of the Japanese Red Army terrorist group, who
was detained in Tokyo late last year, reportedly was headed for
Seoul. The group has ties to communist North Korea, which is
threatening to boycott the Olympics unless it is allowed to co-host
the Games.
   The International Olympic Committee has rejected North Korea's
bid to co-host the Olympics on the grounds that the Games are
awarded to a single city.
