<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0669 08-25 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Pledges to Help Minorities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new grafs 5-6 with Bush comments on Quayle, bgng ``As
he was...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush pledged
Thursday to help minorities ``who haven't really had a shot at the
starting line'' by giving tax breaks to businesses that locate in
urban and rural enterprise zones.
   In a campaign appearance filled with Hispanic overtones, Bush
said he would revive the faltering oil industry, create a better
climate for small business, fight against federal gun control and
provide jobs for the state's large minority population.
   Standing on the historic San Antonio riverfront in a
sweat-drenched guayaberra, a Latino-style cotton shirt, Bush touted
the Reagan administration record of 17 million new jobs, but did
not repeat his own pledge to create 30 million new jobs. Some of
Bush's own advisers said that promise was a bit hyperbolic.
   ``I want to help these minorities who haven't really had a shot
at the starting line,'' he said, pledging to do that by creating
tax breaks for businesses that locate in rural and urban areas.
   As he was leaving San Antonio, reporters asked Bush if he
thought the cntroversy over running mate Dan Quayle was behind him.
``Yes, I do,'' he said. ``There does seem to be forward motion _
it's something in the air.''
   ``It smells like victory,'' Bush added.
   Bush, a New England native who has made Texas his adopted home
state, made repeated mention of the fact that 40 years ago he and
his wife Barbara chose to move here.
   ``I knew that Texas was where I wanted to raise our family and
where we wanted to go out and make a living,'' he told the rally.
   His voice rising, Bush continued, ``I was drawn to this state by
two things _ Texas was a place of big opportunity, a can-do place,
and it was strong in the traditional values _ family, faith and
peace and patriotism. I keep those values uppermost in my mind,''
he said.
   Bush also said he would ``put some incentive back into the
energy business'' and decrease dependence on foreign oil. And he
said he would cut the capital gains tax and keep Congress ``from
strangling small business with regulation.''
   Bush arrived at the rally of a few hundred supporters after
taking a tour by tourist barge for about a mile down the river. He
was serenaded by mariachi guitar players. The rally closed with a
mariachi version of ``Hail to the Chief,'' and a song that has
become one of the Republican theme songs this year, ``La Bamba.''
   Bush compared opponent Michael Dukakis to former president Jimmy
Carter, saying voters did not want to return to the ``malaise''
that occurred ``the last time a governor came out of nowhere and
became president of the United States.
   ``We need proven tested leadership,'' he said.
   He continued his criticsm of Dukakis' veto of a Massachussetts
measure that would have required teachers to lead their classes in
the Pledge of Allegiance.
   ``I think it's time he let the Pledge of Allegiance out on
furlough,'' Bush said. Referring to the fact that courts have
upheld the Dukakis point of view, Bush said he would appoint judges
who would interpret the Constitution _ ``not legislate.''
   Bush made the remarks during a four-day swing through Texas, a
state where his campaign is focusing with increasing intensity
since the Democrats named Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen to their ticket.
   ``I'm proud to be back in my home state of Texas,'' he said.
   Bush flew to San Antonio from Houston, where he maintains an
official address at the posh Houstonian Hotel.
   Bush's roots in Texas go back to the 1940s when he and his wife
Barbara moved here, and Bush began his career in the oil business.
Eventually he started his own company, and then was elected to
Congress from Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
