<HEAD>New Defense Agency Chief Seeks Public Support</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's new defense chief said Thursday the
government must win the people's ``understanding and support'' and
he expressed regret over the collision of a submarine and a fishing
boat that killed 30 civilians.
   Kichiro Tazawa spoke to senior agency officials and officers one
day after he was appointed by the prime minister as the agency's
new director-general, replacing Tsutomu Kawara.
   Kawara resigned Wednesday to take responsibility for the deaths
in the incident July 23, when a naval submarine and a sport fishing
boat collided in Tokyo Bay. Thirty of the 48 passengers aboard the
fishing vessel were killed.
   ``The nation's defense is first established based on the
people's understanding and support. In this regard the collision
between the submarine and the fishing boat is truly regrettable,''
Defense Agency spokesman Youichi Fukumori quoted Tazawa as saying.
   Tazawa, 70, a former minister of Agriculture, Forestry and
Fisheries and head of the National Land Agency, also said the
agency will take ``all possible measures'' to prevent similar
accidents from recurring, according to Fukumori.
