<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Press Plane,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Press Stranded After Charter Flight Aborted Near Takeoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A press plane chartered by George Bush's
presidential campaign was forced to abort its takeoff from a
Houston airfield Thursday, the third time in less than a week that
problems plagued a Bush press plane.
   In the latest incident, a United Airlines Boeing 737-300 was
beginning its takeoff at Ellington Field when the pilot suddenly
applie the brakes.
   No injuries were reported but about 50 reporters and
photographers were temporarily stranded and were unable to cover
the vice president's trip to San Antonio.
   John Clark, 49, the pilot, told reporters one engine had
overheated and that he decided to abort shortly before the plane
reached the critical point of takeoff.
   ``The indicator lights showed the engine was hot and we decided
to abort at 60 knots,'' he said.
   The journalists were told that immediate repairs were not
possible. A smaller group of reporters accompanied the vice
president aboard Air Force Two.
   Bush was scheduled to return to Houston and spend the night
there before flying to Longview, Texas, on Friday for another
appearance.
   The Bush campaign's press plane problems began last Saturday
when fumes from an air conditioning vent filled the cabin as a
Boeing 727 landed in Columbus, Ohio. That plane is owned by Key
Airlines.
   Two days later, the same plane had just taken off from Chicago
when the pilots noticed the jet's wing flaps would not retract. The
plane returned to Chicago after the pilots dumped fuel into Lake
Michigan.
   Reporters covering Bush refused to fly on another Key Airlines
plane, so the campaign chartered a new press plane from Sun World
Airlines for an uneventful flight Tuesday night to Sacramento,
Calif.
   Thelma LeBrecht, an AP Network News reporter covering Bush, said
reporters were not told why the campaign had switched to a United
charter on Thursday, but she said most reporters expressed relief
that a major carrier had been chosen.
   When the United flight was aborted, however, she said, many
reporters broke into a chant: ``Key Air, Key Air.''
</TEXT>
