<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-Nazi     08-25 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Nazi,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dane Identifies Alleged Nazi Criminal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish immigrant testifying in
court identified a picture of an alleged Nazi war criminal believed
responsible for the deaths of at least 100 Jews, a judge said
Thursday.
   Henrik Gottlieb looked at a photograph of Josef Scwamberger and
said it was the man he saw commit executions in a Polish village,
said Judge Niels Erik Jensen.
   Gottlieb, 56, testified in Copenhagen city court, and his
testimony will be sent to authorities in Stuttgart, West Germany,
who will decide whether to request Schwamberger's extradition.
   Gottlieb, who immigrated here 17 years ago and took Danish
citizenship, lost his entire family during the Nazi occupation of
his village of Przemysl in eastern Poland during World War II.
   He told the court that as a 12-year-old he witnessed
Schwamberger participate in the killings of many Jews, including a
woman and 25 children who were forced to dig their own graves and
then were shot.
   Schwamberger, 76, is a former SS officer suspected of ordering
killings in Przemysl in 1943 and 1944. He is imprisoned in
Argentina.
   ``I saw him whipping children and forcing people to dig their
own graves and then shooting them. That man is responsible for the
deaths of thousands of people,'' Gottlieb was quoted as saying by
the B.T. newspaper.
</TEXT>
