<HEAD>Hezbollah Buries 5 Fighters Killed In Clash With Israelis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOHMOR, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem militants
Thursday buried five of their fighters killed in a clash with the
Israeli Army in south Lebanon, and vowed to intensify their
guerrilla war.
   ``We shall escalate the fighting against Israel until victory,''
said Sheik Mohammed Yazbek, a leader of Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   He told about 100 mourners during the funeral of the five
guerrillas killed Wednesday: ``The martyrs who fell in the heroic
confrontation yesterday call upon all of you to take part in
military action against the Zionists.''
   Mourners chanted ``Allah akbar!'' (``God is great!'') as the
funeral procession moved through Sohmor village in the western
Bekaa Valley north of Israel's self-designated border security zone.
   Six Israeli soldiers were wounded in the clash with Hezbollah
near the village of Kawkaba, nine miles north of Sohmor.
   Israel established the six- to 10-mile zone in 1985, when it
withdrew the bulk of its army from south Lebanon three years after
invading the country.
   The zone, patrolled by 1,000 Israelis and more than 1,000
militiamen of the Israeli-armed South Lebanon Army, serves as a
buffer against cross-border raids.
