<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Simon     08-25 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Simon,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Discusses Apartheid with Foreign Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JOH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon and South
African Foreign Minister Pik Botha met Thursday and said they were
able to debate apartheid without yelling at each other.
   ``You name the controversial agenda ... we talked about it,''
said Simon, D-Ill., who favors U.S. economic sanctions against
South Africa. ``We had a good, frank discussion.''
   Simon, who unsuccessfully ran for president this year, is on a
five-day fact-finding tour of South Africa.
   Simon is chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee
on African Affairs and will play a major role in deliberations on
pending legislation to intensify U.S. sanctions against South
Africa. Limited sanctions have been in effect since 1986.
   ``We never yelled at each other,'' Botha said after the
100-minute meeting in a Johannesburg suburb. ``The senator has put
all the difficult questions. But he has given me the opportunity to
put my side. That's all I can ask.''
   Botha and other South African leaders say they are pursuing
gradual race reforms at their own pace and will not be pressured by
sanctions. They also say black South Africans stand to suffer the
most from any hardships caused by sanctions or foreign
disinvestment.
   Simon later flew to Cape Town, where he conferred with two
leaders of the anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party, including
Helen Suzman, the longest-serving member of Parliament. Mrs. Suzman
opposes sanctions.
   On Friday, Simon plans to visit Crossroads, a black shantytown
near Cape Town. His visit will coincide with one by President P.W.
Botha, who will be making his first official trip to Crossroads.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   A pro-government newspaper, The Citizen, editorialized Thursday
that Simon ``came here determined to find justification for
sanctions.''
   ``But then Americans do tend to have a simplistic _ should we
say a Simple Simon _ approach to other countries, and South Africa
is probably the worst example of this American madness to recreate
countries in their own image,'' the newspaper said.
   Earlier in his trip, Simon visited several black townships and
met with black leaders such as Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu.
   The senator's request to meet with imprisoned African National
Congress leader Nelson Mandela was rejected by the government. The
70-year-old Mandela, South Africa's best known black leader, is in
Cape Town's Tygerberg Hospital being treated for tuberculosis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
