<2ND_LINE>AM-Papandreou,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Premier to London For Medical Tests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou flew to London
on Thursday for medical tests after doctors diagnosed he was
suffering from a heart problem, a government spokesman said.
   The 69-year-old premier was diagnosed as suffering stenosis of
the aorta, and will undergo further tests, said the spokesman,
Sotiris Kostopoulos.
   Stenosis of the aorta is a constriction of the main artery
pumping blood from the heart and can be corrected by surgery.
   Papandreou underwent tests Tuesday night at the cardiac unit of
Athens General Hospital. Looking flushed, he told reporters as he
walked out of the hospital, ``I simply decided to have a
cardiogram.''
   Three Greek cardiac specialists flew with Papandreou to London,
where he has been treated before for a circulatory problem,
Kostopoulos said.
