<DOCNO> AP880825-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1743EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Analysis     08-25 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Analysis,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chile Moves Toward Legitimizing Presidential Plebiscite; Doubts
Persist</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military President Augusto Pinochet's
decision to lift all states of emergency helps meet opposition
conditions for fair play in an October presidential referendum.
   But other measures being urged by critics have yet to be
adopted, and the critics say doubts persist that the vote will
enjoy legitimacy.
   ``We still have to wait and see,'' Patrico Aylwin, president of
the centrist Christian Democratic Party, told foreign reporters.
   Gen. Pinochet on Wednesday signed decrees to end all states of
emergency for the first time since he seized power in a 1973 coup.
The decrees take effect upon publication in the official bulletin,
expected this week.
   His right-wing government plans a referendum on a single
presidential nominee to be picked by military commanders, including
Pinochet, at a meeting set for next Tuesday. Pinochet, who is also
the army commander, is expected to be nominated.
   No exact date has been announced for the yes-or-no ballot, but
Pinochet said it will be in early October. If a majority vote yes,
the nominee will be president until 1997. If most voters reject
him, open elections will be held in 1990, with Pinochet remaining
in place until then.
   Opposition parties and the local Roman Catholic Church set four
basic conditions for a fair ballot: high voter registration; an end
to the states of emergency; equal access to the mass media, and a
vote free of fraud and intimidation.
   By mid-August more than 7 million of Chile's 8 million eligible
voters had registered, thus resolving the first condition
   The second condition was met, at least formally, by Wednesday's
decrees. Under the emergency states, the right to assembly and
freedom of the press could be restricted and the government could
jail and expel leftist critics.
   With the lifting of the measures, opposition groups can stage
rallies without government authorization. ``It's impossible to
image conducting a campaign without the right to gather publicly,''
Aylwin said.
   He said the opposition would wait and see if the government is
sincere about its vows to respect civil liberties.
   Ricardo Lagos, a prominent Socialist in a 16-party opposition
coalition, said Thursday, ``I'm left with the sensation that this
is a cosmetic operation.''
   Monica Madariaga, a former justice minister under Pinochet who
now is critical of his government, said the president ``has placed
the country under a state of observation'' and could declare a new
state of emergency if the opposition failed to behave.
   On Tuesday, navy commander Jose Merino warned that even stronger
emergency measures could be adopted if public disturbances occurred.
   But Roman Catholic Church leaders expressed confidence in the
government's good faith. Cardinal Juan Francisco Fresno said in a
written statement that he received news of the measure ``with
satisfaction, and asks all Catholics to intensify their prayers for
the welfare of the country.''
   Still pending is the question of access to television and the
press. Television, which is tightly controlled by the state, and
the biggest newspapers have provided little space to the
opposition. Political groups campaigning for a ``no'' vote complain
that their advertisements are rejected but there is intensive
pro-government propaganda.
   ``Under these conditions, the plebiscite loses legitimacy,''
Lagos said in a recent interview.
   Election laws drawn up by the government guarantee each side 15
minutes of free television time each day in September, from 10:45
p.m. to 11:15 p.m. Opposition leaders say the hour is too late for
many people and that this still fails to compensate for hundreds of
pro-government ads broadcast and published during the past year.
   ``There is an immense abuse and fraud by the government in
access to television,'' said Andres Zaldivar, a Christian Democrat.
   He said that because of unfair conditions, if the government
declares a victory in the ballot ``the immense majority of Chileans
are not going to believe it, and the entire world is not going to
believe it.''
   But he and other opposition leaders virtually discount the
possibility of a fraudulent count on the night of the ballot. They
said election laws authorizing the presence of independent monitors
at polling places will make any attempt at direct fraud too obvious.
   The opposition coalition, pro-government parties and a
church-sponsored group each has established a network of thousands
of monitors to provide parallel vote counts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Noblet is Santiago bureau chief for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
