<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PsychiatricEmergency     08-25 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Psychiatric Emergency,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Squeeze: State Declares Emergency At 2 Facilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials declared a state of emergency Thursday
at two Brooklyn psychiatric hospitals, saying patients were
squeezed into overcrowded rooms and forced to sleep in shifts on
cots in hallways.
   The action allows the state to begin moving patients to less
crowded facilities without permission of family or guardians, said
Steve Osborn, a spokesman for state Mental Health Commissioner
Richard C. Surles.
   ``There is no patient privacy, no ability to accommodate
patients who are not able to be admitted as in-patients right
away,'' said the city's mental health chief, Dr. Sara Kellermann,
who had urged Surles to declare the emergency.
   ``As a result they end up eating with trays on their laps, end
up sleeping on very rudimentary cots ... and they are literally
sleeping in hallways in four-hour shifts,'' she said. Hospital
employees would wake patients up after a few hours to allow others
to lay down, she said.
   Though officials were aware of overcrowding at psychiatric
facilities in New York City, they said they did not realize the
magnitude of the problem until they conducted an in-person
investigation.
   The city-run Kings County Hospital has 160 beds for mental
health patients and a current population of 195, according to
Osborn.
   Matters are worse at nighboring Kingsboro State Psychiatric
Center, where there are 566 beds and 736 patients. Osborn said it
was not unusual to see six patients squeezed into a room intended
for four.
   Kellermann said she was extremely distressed at the conditions
she found. In one case, she said, psychiatric patients were placed
in an open, atrium-style emergency room _ sometimes for days _
waiting for a bed.
   State officials denied a request to tour the facility. Osborn
cited patient confidentiality.
   The transfer of about 240 patients from the two centers to
facilities outside New York City should start within a few days,
Osborn said.
   In addition to overcrowding, the state cited Kings County for
``patient idleness,'' lack of privacy and building safety code
deficiencies.
</TEXT>
