<DOCNO> AP880825-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Floods     08-25 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Floods,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Struggles With Shortages; Nile Recedes After Floods</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Name Abdelrhman cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flood-ravaged Sudan scraped for such
basics as bread, electricity and drinkable water on Thursday.
Floodwaters covered about 280 square miles of land in the north,
the state-run Sudan News Agency said.
   Electricity, transportation, communications were badly affected.
   The Irrigation Ministry reported a slight drop of 1.2 inches in
the swollen Nile River at this capital city of 4 million people,
and forecast a continued decrease over the next few days.
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi has warned, however, that the
flood situation could deteriorate again in the first week of
September, the peak rainy season.
   The Sudan News Agency said water covered an area stretching from
Merowe, 200 miles north of Khartoum, to Abri, 100 miles south of
the Egyptian border. It said islands in the Nile were completely
submerged and their inhabitants had been evacuated to safe areas.
   The Nile overcame levees in several areas in Khartoum, including
one containing many diplomatic residences. Military units were
mobilized to help stop the waters' advance.
   Whole suburbs in Khartoum were flooded. Streets were turned into
impassable mud tracks, hampering relief operations.
   Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 triggered the worst floods in this
northeast African country's history. The floods have left 1.5
million people homeless, at least 91 dead, tens of thousands of
homes destroyed and some of Sudan's most fertile farmland inundated.
   Worst affected were shantytowns at the outskirts of Khartoum.
The towns, made up of tin, canvas and mud hovels, house between
750,000 and 1 million displaced Sudanese who fled to the capital to
escape the 5-year-old civil war in the south.
   Despite concerted international relief efforts by about two
dozen countries since the floods started three weeks ago, lines of
children, women and elderly people waiting for bread remain common,
even at night.
   Information Minister El-Sayed Abdallah Mohammed Ahmed on
Wednesday night harshly criticized Europe and the United States,
especially Sudan's former colonial power, Britain, accusing them of
not doing enough in light of the scope of the disaster.
   Opposition parties, however, claimed the government is
distributing relief supplies only to its supporters.
   Eliaba James Sarur, leader of the opposition in Parliament and
chairman of the Union of Sudanese Parties, told a news conference
Thursday the government's parties ``distribute the aid to their
supporters through their members in the Parliament, their election
committees and some of their organizations.''
   The problems have been compounded by the start of the annual
flood of the Nile, which already has overflowed in central and
northern Sudan and in parts of Khartoum.
   Luxurious hotels along the Nile have been surrounded by water.
   In nearby Omdurman, many owners had to abandon flooded dairies
and poultry farms, making the scarcity of fresh milk and eggs worse.
   Britain on Thursday contested claims by Sudan that British aid
for flood victims was inadequate. The Foreign Office said six
planes had flown out with government and charity supplies, not just
one as Ahmed had said.
   Sudanese Charge d'Affaires Gubara Abdelrhman Gubara was summoned
to the Foreign Office in London to be told of Britain's displeasure.
   The International Red Cross said Thursday in Geneva that an
estimated 100,000 trapped victims of the flood disaster will
probably have to be supplied by air.
   Dan Prewitt, head of the International Red Cross delegation at
Khartoum, reported that the airlift was needed because the flooded
area north of the capital was virtually inaccessible.
</TEXT>
