<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0743,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crashes Into Print Shop; Three Killed, Three Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with condition of seriously injured woman;
quotes from fire official, relative of injured worker, other
details.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed through the
roof of a print shop Thursday, killing three people in the plane
and severely burning one person on the ground, officials said.
   ``It doesn't appear there were any survivors'' from the plane,
said police Sgt. Keith Plant.
   Plant said it is believed there were three people in the
building, located in a small strip shopping center, and three
people in the plane when it crashed.
   Two people in the building escaped with minor injuries but the
third, a 24-year-old woman, was in critical condition with
second-degree burns over her face, neck, chest and arms, said Linda
Hamlin, spokeswoman for Hollywood Memorial Hospital.
   ``The people heard the crash, heard the explosion, and had time
to get out,'' Fire Capt. Sam Halpert said. ``It was a split-second
decision.''
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Jack Barker in Atlanta
said the plane was a Piper Aerostar that took off from the nearby
North Perry Airport about 3:30 p.m. The plane can seat six people.
   Halpert said rescuers, who were waiting for the fire to cool
down, hoped that no one else was in the plane or the building. ``We
know we're going to find people dead (from the plane); we're hoping
it's as few as possible,'' he said.
   Ray Saks, who works at the Pembroke Auto Center across the
street from the crash, said he heard the plane ``sputtering and
misfiring up above us.''
   ``Next time we turned around, the wing tip went right into the
roof of Neway Printing on the other side of the street,'' Saks said.
   ``We had an immediate explosion and a fire that went up probably
about 70 feet in the air,'' he said.
   Saks said he was worried because the print shop contained large
amounts of chemicals.
   ``There is the possibility of toxic chemicals,'' Plant said,
adding that hazardous waste teams were on the site. But he said the
fire was under control and the situation was not considered
dangerous.
   Police closed off all roads in the vicinity. The accident cut
power to many homes in the neighborhood.
   Ralph DiGiamo, who owns a nearby deli, said his son Joe, who
worked at the the print shop, and the shop's co-owner, Pat
Goldberg, were the two people who were slightly injured. The
seriously injured woman was another worker, he said, but he didn't
know her full name.
   ``She's lucky she didn't get killed because she works right in
that back end where the plane hit,'' said the elder DiGiamo. ``My
son ran out the front door right away.''
</TEXT>
