<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0695,0706</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Masked Palestinians Kill Collaborator, Injure Workers Defying
Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 2 grafs SUB for grafs 12-13 pvs, When asked ... his death.
UPDATING with Israeli officer reprimanded. PICKS up 14th graf pvs,
Palestinians went ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked Palestinians wielding axes killed an
Arab farmer suspected of cooperating with Israel, witnesses said
Thursday. Other masked men attacked Palestinian laborers defying a
strike order and injured three.
   The attacks reflected growing divisions among Palestinians over
the future of their 8{-month uprising.
   Israeli aircraft bombed a Palestinian guerrilla base near the
southern Lebanese port city of Sidon, the army command said.
   Israeli military sources and Lebanese police said rocket-firing
helicopter gunships were used in the air raid, Israel's 13th in
Lebanon this year.
   Lebanese police said 10 people, including one guerrilla, were
wounded in the six-minute attack on targets in the Ein el-Hilweh
refugee camp on the outskirts of Sidon.
   Two Israelis, including a 10-year-old boy, were slightly injured
when attackers threw a firebomb at an Israeli passenger bus
northeast of Jerusalem, police said.
   In the West Bank village of Yatta south of Jerusalem, masked men
broke into the home of Saadi Hazaza late Wednesday, dragged him
outside and hacked him to death with axes, Arab witnesses and
state-run Israel radio reported.
   Underground leaders have urged Palestinians to halt all
cooperation with Israeli authorities, including working for the
Israeli military government, and have called for attacks on
Palestinians who give Israel information.
   Hazaza, 32, was the third suspected collaborator to be killed
since the uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip began
Dec. 8. His death brought to 253 the number of Palestinians killed,
although most have been killed by Israeli gunfire. Four Israelis
also have died.
   The army said Hazaza may have been killed as part of a
longstanding family feud.
   But the radio and witnesses who spoke to The Associated Press
said he had carried a weapon _ a privilege Israel grants only to
Palestinians who provide information to authorities.
   Israel radio also reported that the deputy chief of staff, Maj.
Gen. Ehud Barak, severely reprimanded a senior officer for shooting
and killing a Palestinian after chasing him in a helicopter. Barak
found that the officer, identified only as Col. G., did not shoot
the Palestinian from the air, as had been reported, and convicted
him of improper use of weapons, not manslaughter. The incident
occurred in February near Bani Naim village.
   Israeli newspapers have said the officer intended to resign from
the army.
   Palestinians went on strike Thursday for the third time this
week to protest the deaths of four prisoners in Israeli jails.
   Merchants shut businesses and public transport was halted, but
some Palestinians complained and others tried to reach work in
Israel. Two dozen were seen at a Jerusalem archaeological site.
   Masked men trying to enforce the strike hurled stones at cars
carrying Arab laborers from Bethlehem, injuring three.
   On Wednesday in the northern West Bank village of Azzun,
hundreds of villagers stoned two Palestinian brothers suspected of
collaborating with Israel as they passed in their car, Israel radio
and Arab witnesses said.
   The two were identified as Tahseen Mansour, 43, an
Israeli-appointed regional leader, and Basseem Mansour, 35.
   Tahseen Mansour opened fire, wounding a 20-year-old among the
crowd, the witnesses said, adding that both men escaped.
   The Israeli army maintained curfews Thursday on six areas in the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, confining some 255,000 Palestinians to
their homes.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in a message to U.S.
Secretary of State George P. Shultz that Israel would ``continue
its policy of selective deportations,'' a Shamir aide said.
   Shamir sent his spoken message through U.S. Ambassador Thomas
Pickering. It came in response to criticism from the State
Department, which said continued Israeli deportations could
threaten relations between Jerusalem and Washington.
   Since the start of the Palestinian uprising, Israel has deported
33 Palestinians and ordered another 25 expelled.
   ``The U.S. is not responsible for order here _ we are,'' Shamir
said in remarks broadcast by Israel radio.
</TEXT>
