<HEAD>Handicapped Children Injured In Accident</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Name McGarrigl is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mobile home carrying American
handicapped children slipped off a road in this Nuevo Leon state
capital Thursday, and two children and the driver were slighly
injured, Federal Highway Police said.
   Police Commander Raul Sandoval said the children, aged 6 and 11,
and the 45-year-old woman driver were treated at Monterrey
University Hospital and released.
   Sandoval identified the woman as the director of the Hope House,
a home for handicapped children in Austin, Texas. He said he did
not know her name and referred further inquiries to the U.S.
Consulate.
   Jorge Cavazos, a U.S. Consulate official, said her name was Rosy
White McGarrigl, but he did not have the childrens' identities. He
said the three were in fine condition and apparently would go home
Thursday.
   The Americans were returning from a vacation trip to
Guadalajara, capital of Jalisco state, about 600 miles southwest of
Monterrey.
   Sandoval said the mobile home, with four or five children
aboard, was on a highway on Monterrey's northeast when the driver
attempted to turn into a gasoline station.
   The wheels of the vehicle apparently locked and it slid off the
road into a 5-foot ditch. A small wheelchair was found at the
scene. The accident happened shortly after 6 a.m., Sandoval said.
   ``She was driving very slowly. It's just that she had some
mechanical problems,'' Sandoval said in a telephone interview.
   He said the mobile home was being followed by a bus carrying
about 25 children from the same institute and both vehicles were
heading toward the border at Laredo, Texas, about a three-hour
drive from Monterrey.
