<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen-Stocks     08-25 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen-Stocks,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Betsen Orders Stocks In South Africa Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen last week ordered stocks in companies doing business
in South Africa sold after finding his blind trust had invested in
them, his spokesman said Thursday.
   ``He just did it'' without any prodding from anyone, spokesman
Jack Devore said, confirming a report Thursday in The Patriot
Ledger of Quincy, Mass. The report said the Texas senator saw the
blind trust stock holdings for the first time on Aug. 12, about a
month after his nomination for the vice presidency.
   The newspaper report said the trust had invested $120,000 to
$400,000 in the companies.
   By selling the stocks, Bentsen avoided a conflict with the
Democratic Party platform, which calls for South Africa to be
listed as a ``terrorist'' state and calls the nation a ``uniquely
repressive regime.''.
   The Democratic platform also promises to set a date for U.S.
corporations to withdraw from South Africa.
   According to Bentsen's financial disclosure form, his blind
trust included investments worth between $15,000 and $50,000 in
each of the following companies, which the state says do business
in South Africa: Caterpillar Inc., Chevron, Colgate, Palmolive,
Johnson & Johnson, Minnesota & Manufacturing, Monsanto Co., Tenneco
Inc., and Unisys Corp.
