<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Rights     08-25 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Rights,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Conference Opens Amid Polish Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 600 activists from East and West
came together for an unofficial human rights conference Thursday,
while the government confronted workers striking to legalize
Solidarity.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa was scheduled to give the opening
address at the conference, one of the largest ever held in an East
bloc country. But he sent his apologies, saying he could not come
because he was holed up with other strikers at the Lenin shipyard
in Gdansk.
   ``The highest necessity forces me to stay away,'' the 1983 Nobel
Peace Prize laureate wrote to conference participants. ``I am
taking part in a strike to defend human and workers' rights.
   ``I believe that the epoch of totalitarian systems based on
violations of human rights seems to be coming to an end in this
part of the world.''
   Also at the conference Thursday, U.S. congressional staffer
Michael Hammond announced that the Congress would soon approve a $1
million grant to help Solidarity, which was outlawed by the Polish
government in 1982. Solidarity was the first independent labor
movement in the East bloc.
   Hammond, general counsel to the Senate Steering Committee, which
does research and provides support for Conservative members of the
chamber, said the United States already has provided two such
grants to Solidarity.
   He called on the Polish government to legalize the trade
federation.
   ``Any improvement in relations between the U.S. and the
government of Poland must be predicated on an improvement in the
human rights situation in Poland,'' Hammond said. ``I can tell you
with authority that this means Solidarity must be legalized.''
   The conference opened in a church in Nowa Huta, an industrial
suburb of Krakow in southern Poland, a region at the hub of the
current strikes that began 10 days ago. Nowa Huta is also home of
the sprawling Lenin steel mill, where police violently broke a
major strike in May.
   The conference was organized by Solidarity's Commission of
Intervention and Lawfulness, which monitors human rights in Poland,
and the outlawed peace group Freedom and Peace. It is scheduled to
end Saturday.
   Poland was represented at the conference by filmmaker Andrzej
Wajda, literary critic Jan-Jozef Lipski and senior Solidarity
adviser Bronislaw Geremek. Miner Adam Giera came to deliver a
message from striking miners in the city of Jastrzebie, about two
hours away.
   American guests included Jeri Laber, executive director of the
U.S. Helsinki Watch Group; and Boston Mayor Raymond Flynn.
   Conference organizers invited government officials, including
Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak. But only a lower-level
official from the ministry came, and he made no statements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
