<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Journalists     08-25 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Journalists,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chilean Journalist Arrested, Others Protest Government Treatment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile-Analysis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Thursday arrested a
journalist accused of slandering a military prosecutor, and other
news people stopped work for one hour to protest their treatment by
the right-wing government.
   About 60 journalists also rallied in front of the presidential
palace to protest what they describe as persecution of journalists
by the military government of President Augusto Pinochet.
   Francisco Herreros, director of the leftist weekly magazine
Cauce, was arrested Thursday, according to records filed at a
military court in Santiago. He was held on a government-filed
complaint of slandering a military prosecutor in an article
published in June.
   Radio news broadcasts were suspended during the work stoppage
from 11 a.m. to noon, and many print reporters and television
journalists also joined the protest. The protest had been planned
before the arrest.
   About 60 members of the Chilean Journalists' Association, which
called the protest, gathered in front of the presidential palace
for a brief rally. They released a letter of protest addressed to
Interior Minister Sergio Fernandez.
   ``Persecution of journalists has continued,'' the letter said.
It said 29 journalists now face criminal slander charges filed by
the government in either military or civilian courts.
   The charges stem from articles critical of Pinochet, government
officials or the armed forces.
   In a presidential referendum to be held sometime in October,
Chileans will vote ``yes'' or ``no'' on a single candidate to be
picked Tuesday by Pinochet, as commander-in-chief of the army, and
by his counterparts in the navy, air force and national police.
Pinochet himself is considered virtually certain of gaining the
nomination.
</TEXT>
