<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 3rdLd-Writethru a0709 08-25 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0709,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle: I've Answered Enough Questions, I'm Qualified to Be
President</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, A scheduled...National Guard,'' to explain
circumstances of canceled news conference,'' SUBS 8th graf, Quayle
stayed...campaign chairman, to show prior media availability,
picking up 9th pvs, Quayle was...the presidency.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOONVILLE, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle, countering suggestions that he is not mature enough to be
president, said Thursday he is qualified ``if that situation
arises.''
   As for his youth, the 41-year-old Indiana senator said, ``I'm
very close to the same age as Jack Kennedy was when he was elected
_ not vice president, but president.''
   Quayle also said he had answered questions about his military
record and that the American public is ``getting a little bit
sick'' of hearing about the issue.
   ``I've answered questions for seven days now,'' Quayle told
reporters as he arrived in Colmbia, Mo. ``We're going to talk about
the future. We're going to talk about jobs. We're going to talk
about other issues that the American people are interested in.''
   The Indiana senator scheduled a series of stops in Missouri,
ending with an appearance in Sedalia at the state fair.
   A scheduled news conference there was canceled at the last
minute along with another event because of what aides said were
time constraints. Quayle took questions from farmers at the state
fair but told them, ``I won't take any questions about the Indiana
National Guard.''
   Most of the farmers' questions centered on Medicare reform,
drought relief legislation and the newly-signed trade bill, which
Quayle opposed in the Senate debate but described Thursday as ``a
good first step to send a message that we are serious about trade.''
   Apart from the canceled news conference, Quayle allowed
reporters to question him Thursday in an apparent shift in campaign
strategy. Quayle had stayed away from the press on Wednesday so
attention would focus on his speech to a group of National
Guardsmen, said Stuart Spencer, Quayle's campaign chairman.
   Quayle was asked about remarks Wednesday by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen,
his Democratic counterpart, suggesting that Quayle was not mature
enough for a job that was a heartbeat away from the presidency.
   ``I am qualified, if that situation arises,'' Quayle said,
adding that he felt he had special expertise in national defense
and security issues.
   He told reporters in Boonville that he did not regret his vote
against establishing a Veterans Administration Cabinet post. But he
said he was ``a team player'' and would support the new Cabinet
post since Bush favored it.
   Quayle had indicated Monday to a Veterans of Foreign Wars
convention that his vote might someday be viewed as a youthful
indiscretion. But Thursday, he insisted he did not regret the vote.
   ``I still believe my vote was correct,'' he said.
   Quayle's aides insisted that the controversy over whether he
pulled strings to enter the National Guard during the Vietnam War
had faded, especially after a rousing reception from the Guardsmen
Wednesday night.
   ``We think the issue is behind us,'' he said. ``We want to keep
it behind us.''
   Spencer said Bush's pollster, Robert Teeter, was doing regional
polling to see if the American public agreed.
   Quayle was greeted in Columbia by a contingent of supporters,
although some in the crowd chanted ``Quayle's a chicken.'' Some
negative signs were sprinkled among the pro-Quayle signs, reading
``Sissy Rich Boy,'' ``Dump Quayle'' and``War Wimp.'
</TEXT>
