<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-25 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cool and Wet in Northeast, Scattered Showers in Parts of South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cool, wet air covered parts of the Northeast on Thursday, and a
few showers and thunderstorms hit scattered parts of the South and
Southwest.
   Hazy skies stretched from Wyoming as far away as Denver as
forest fires in Yellowstone National Park continued to spew smoke.
Visibility was poor over western Wyoming.
   Cool, unstable air over western New York State and Lake Ontario
generated showers while rain and fog covered parts of northern New
England and kept temperatures down in the 50s and low 60s.
   Afternoon temperatures were only in the 60s over the northern
Great Lakes and northeast Minnesota.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over portions of
southwest Texas as well as over Florida and along the coast of the
Carolinas. Thunderstorms also were developing over the mountains in
central Arizona.
   Temperatures were in the 90s from Texas across the lower
Mississippi Valley and the Gulf Coast to Florida.
   Isolated showers also doused northwest Montana.
   Temperatures ranged from 90 to above 100 degrees in the desert
Southwest and the Great Basin. Most other regions showed readings
in the 70s and 80s.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 54 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 102 degrees at Chase Field Naval Air Station, Beeville,
Texas. The early morning low was 29 degrees at Jackson, Wyo.
   Friday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over Florida, southern Georgia and along the North Carolina coast
in the Southeast, and over Arizona, western New Mexico, southwest
Colorado and Utah in the West. Showers and thunderstorms also were
forecast for the Black Hills of South Dakota. Showers were expected
from the northern Great Lakes to northern New England.
   Highs were predicted to be in the 70s and 80s over much of the
northern half of the nation and along the California coast, with
highs only in the 60s over Upper Michigan and northeast Minnesota.
Highs were forecast to be in the 90s over the central and southern
Plateau and New mexico, and from the southern Plains across the
lower Mississippi Valley to the Gulf Coast, Florida, the Tennessee
Valley and the southern Atlantic Coast states. Highs were expected
to be near 100 degrees from central Texas into south-central Kansas
and between 100 and 105 in the desert Southwest and the valleys of
central and southern California.
</TEXT>
