<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Politics     08-25 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Politics,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two of Israel's Main Political Parties Merge Formally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two parties forming Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's rightist Likud bloc formally merged Thursday into a single
party that will take part in November general elections.
   The union was a formality because the two parties have fielded a
joint list of candidates for parliament since 1965. But some
political observers said it constituted a final victory for the
right-wing views of the Herut movement over the more moderate
Liberal Party.
   The union of Herut and the Liberal Party also put an end to any
hopes nursed by the left-leaning Labor Party that the Liberals
might bolt the Likud and form a coalition with Labor.
   Herut has 28 seats in the present parliament and the Liberals
13. The Likud and Labor share power in the current coalition
government but elections polls indicate a slight advantage for the
new party, called the Likud-National Liberal Movement, and its
right-wing allies, over the leftist parties headed by Labor.
   Before the official union, leaders of Herut and the Liberals
signed a covenant stating that Israel had an indisputable right to
all of the Land of Israel, including the occupied territories.
   Former Prime Minister Menachem Begin, who founded the Herut
movement in 1948 and was architect of the 1965 partnership with the
Liberal Party, sent a letter of congratulations to the participants.
   Three thousand Likud supporters attended the signing ceremony,
where Shamir delivered a speech attacking his Labor Party rivals.
   Shamir charged that Labor blamed Israel instead of the Arabs for
the Palestinian uprising that began last Dec. 8 and the failure to
reach a peace settlement.
   ``I thought we had gotten rid of this cursed guilt complex a
long time ago,'' Shamir said.
</TEXT>
