<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2153EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath     08-25 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dismissal Motions Delay Start of Trial in Recruit's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking officer received a letter
of reprimand and four other supervisory personnel were given
nonpunitive letters of caution in the death of a rescue swimmer
trainee, a Navy spokesman said Thursday.
   The information was disclosed as proceedings began in the
court-martial of Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, former officer in charge of
the Navy Rescue Swimmer School where Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki,
19, of Appleton, Wis., died March 2.
   Testimony at a June investigative hearing indicated Mirecki died
from a fear-induced heart attack or drowning. Instructors allegedly
pushed Mirecki back into a swimming pool and held his head under
water after he had panicked, climbed out and shouted that he wanted
to quit.
   Torchia's former boss, now-retired Capt. C.L. Lavinder Jr., who
headed the Navy Schools Command at Pensacola Naval Air Station at
the time of Mirecki's death there, received a letter of reprimand
for dereliction of duty from Rear Adm. David R. Morris, said Lt.
Cmdr. Dennis Hessler, a public affairs officer.
   Hessler said the letters of caution were issued to an officer
and three enlisted men with ranks of chief petty officer or above,
but their identities could not be disclosed because the punishment
didn't go on their records.
   Torchia and an enlisted instructor scheduled for trial Monday
are the only personnel facing court-martial in the case.
   Nonjudicial punishments against four enlisted rescue swimmer
instructors, including reductions in rank for two of them and
fines, were ordered by Morris on June 29 and made public then.
   The letters of reprimand and caution were not disclosed before
Thursday because no one asked, Hessler said. He was asked Thursday
after Lavinder's punishment was mentioned during a hearing on
motions to dismiss dereliction-of-duty charges against Torchia.
   Torchia, 32, of Princeton, Ill., was in his office overlooking
the pool, talking on the telephone, at the time of Mirecki's death,
witnesses have said.
   He had been offered unspecified nonjudicial punishment but
requested a court-martial so he could have an opportunity to clear
himself.
   Cmdr. Newell D. Krogmann, the military judge, denied a motion to
dismiss the second of two counts against Torchia. The motion
alleged insufficient evidence.
   The judge later Thursday heard testimony on a motion to dismiss
both counts on grounds the chief of naval education and training,
Vice Adm. N.R. Thunman, who convened the court-martial, was biased
against Torchia.
   Krogmann said he would make a decision when proceedings
reconvene Friday. The trial will begin if he denies the motion. He
has two other options: dismiss the case or remove it from Thunman
and shift it to another admiral of equal or higher responsibility
for an independent decision on whether a court-martial is warranted.
   Thunman ordered the court-martial against the advice of the
investigating officer, Cmdr. Daniel J. D'Alesio, who recommended no
disciplinary action against Torchia.
   A guilty verdict could bring Torchia up to three months'
confinement, loss of pay and a formal reprimand that could make
future advancement in the Navy extremely difficult.
   Scheduled for trial Monday is Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael W.
Combe, 26, of Tempe, Ariz. He is charged with involuntary
manslaughter, battery and conspiracy to commit battery.
   Combe is accused of holding Mirecki under the water. If
convicted he could be dishonorably discharged and sentenced to
prison for more than three years. He was denied the option of
accepting nonjudicial punishment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0189 </DOCNO>
