<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HighwayExplosion     08-25 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Highway Explosion,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, Four Injured In Rush Hour Explosion</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CARROLLTON, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One person was killed and four others
were injured Thursday when a tractor-trailer carrying 8,000 gallons
of diesel fuel overturned and exploded on the Capital Beltway
during the evening rush hour, fire officials said.
   Washington area traffic was snarled as a two-mile stretch of the
Beltway, the highway that forms a loop around the District of
Columbia, was closed for four hours. Traffic in one direction on
that section of the highway remained halted later into the evening.
   The accident occurred when the truck struck a van, lost control
and rolled over the highway's center barrier, said Prince George's
County Fire Department spokesman Tony DeStefano. Sparks from the
skidding truck ignited the fuel as the fuel container broke up in
the wreck.
   The truck's 32-year-old driver was taken to Prince George's
General Hospital with burns on 18 percent of his body.
   One person, believed to be male, smashed into the wreckage in a
car and was instantly killed, DeStefano said.
   One man in the van that was struck by the truck suffered spinal
injuries and was flown to a shock trauma center in Baltimore,
DeStefano said. Two other men in the van received minor injuries.
   Names of the victims had not been released late Thursday.
   Authorities said the explosion posed no immediate danger to area
residents, and let the fire burn out by itself.
   ``It posed no hazard because the tank had already opened and was
burning,'' DeStefano said. ``The best way to dispose of the product
is to let it burn.''
</TEXT>
