<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0752 08-25 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0752,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Walks Out of Vote-Certifying Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with session resuming with
public gallery closed. PICKS up 5th graf pvs bgng, The July 6 ...
DELETES 10th graf pvs `Opposition leaders ..' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CONCEPCION BADILLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition legislators on Thursday stormed
out of a session to certify a new national House of Deputies and
accused the governing party of blocking inquiries into charges of
voting fraud.
   ``We have to seek new ways (of protest), because the official
party is legitimizing fraud more and more every day,'' Alfredo
Noyola of the opposition National Action Party said.
   The opposition parties, who had left before dawn Thursday after
a nightlong debate, returned to the chamber when a new session
began Thursday afternoon, and the lengthy wrangling resumed.
   The House of Deputies is sitting in as an electoral college to
certify the deputies elected in July 6 nationwide balloting.
   Press sections were open at the new session Thursday afternoon,
but public galleries were closed because opposition sympathizers
had been chanting, whistling, and sometimes throwing coins and
other objects.
   The July 6 elections were tainted by widespread accusations that
the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, won by
tampering with voter registration rolls, packing ballot boxes and
destroying ballots for opposition candidates.
   Since then, opposition leaders have accused the PRI of bullying
and steamroller tactics to speed up vote certification, especially
in the House. That chamber must also certify the presidential
election by the Dec. 1 inauguration day of President-elect Carlos
Salinas de Gortari.
   The two major opposition candidates have barnstormed the nation
urging Mexicans to reject the election results.
   After a heated nightlong debate, all 227 opposition deputies
walked out of the Congress building early Thursday, temporarily
paralyzing the 500-member electoral college. The body must finish
its work in time to seat a new House by Sept. 1.
   On that date, both the House and the Senate are to meet in joint
session to hear outgoing President Miguel de la Madrid's
state-of-the-union address.
   The Senate, sitting as a second electoral college, continued
hearings normally Thursday to certify the election for its
64-member body.
   The PRI had not lost a presidential election since it was
founded in 1929.
   But the July 6 balloting marked the first time the PRI won the
presidency with less than 70 percent of the votes cast. Returns
this time gave Salinas victory and a single six-year term by 50.36
percent of the vote.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a former PRI leader that broke away to head
the leftist National Democratic Front coalition, came in second
with 31.1 percent. Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National
Action Party came in third with 17 percent.
   For the first time also, the PRI lost its complete domination of
the Senate. Four opposition senators already have been certified
for their posts.
   By law, the deputies- and senators-elect sit as separate
electoral colleges to certify their own elections, and then the
500-member House sits as an electoral college to certify the
presidential election.
   Both Cardenas and Clouthier have been claiming the election was
fraudulent and accusing the government of denying the electoral
colleges access to documents from about half the 55,000 polling
stations nationwide to conceal irregularities. The de la Madrid
administration has denied the charge.
   ``The PRI members are denying us a voice and are turning down
all requests by the opposition (that fraud be investigated) in
their hurry to conclude the (House electoral college) process,''
Noyola said Thursday in a telephone interview.
   Guillermo Jimenez Morales, leader of the PRI delegates to the
House electoral college, denied the charge in a newspaper interview.
   ``In any case, the attitude adopted by the opposition shows
clearly that we are living within a democratic framework and a free
world, and each one can do what he wants with his freedom,'' he
told the newspaper Excelsior.
   The House had voted unanimously to close the public galleries
minutes before the opposition members walked out, college spokesman
Pedro Pablo Trevino said.
   ``The decision was taken because several deputies were not only
grossly insulted by sympathizers from opposition groups, but many
had coins and other objects tossed at them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
