<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParkerMemorial     08-25 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Parker Memorial,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Memorial Garden for Dorothy Parker Designed to Improve
Black-Jewish Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER BRANDLON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ashes of celebrated writer and wit Dorothy
Parker will be interred in a memorial garden at NAACP headquarters
in a gesture of friendship between blacks and Jews, the director of
the civil rights organization said Thursday.
   The dedication of the garden on Sept. 16 will put an end to the
homelessness of Parker's ashes, which have resided for years in a
New York office file cabinet.
   Parker, who was Jewish, was an outspoken civil libertarian. When
she died in 1967, she left her estate to the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr., and, on his death, to the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
   ``In celebrating Ms. Parker, we proudly celebrate our
relationship with the Jewish community, reaffirming and renewing
our commitment to work hand in hand to erase the stain of all forms
of racial, religious, sexual and ethnic injustice and intolerance
from our society,'' said Benjamin Hooks, executive director of the
NAACP.
   Rabbi Murray Saltzman of the Baltimore Hebrew Congregation
called the memorial ``a testament of good will toward Dorothy
Parker, and, through her, to the Jewish community.''
   Hooks offered to have the ashes buried at the organization's
national headquarters after learning this spring they were being
kept in lawyer Paul O'Dwyer's office.
   Hooks said most people know little more about Parker than her
oft-repeated quip, ``Men seldom make passes at girls who wear
glasses.''
   ``There was much more to Ms. Parker than those sparse and not
totally accurate two lines _ her short stories, her reviews, her
essays, her plays, her movie scripts and her conversational gems,''
Hooks said.
   ``One of my favorites was her reported remark when one of her
archrivals was described as her own worst enemy. `Not while I'm
around,' Ms. Parker retorted. They don't make them like that
anymore.''
   The memorial garden will be located in a tiny grove of towering
white pine trees behind the chapel of a former monastery now
occupied by the NAACP. Its centerpiece will be a plaque on the
ground surrounded by a circle of brown brick. Plans call for
leaving a natural floor of soft pine needles.
   The circle represents the Round Table at New York's Algonquin
Hotel, legendary for the gab sessions held there by Parker and a
collection of the best-known literary figures of her time, said
Harry Robinson, dean of the Howard University School of
Architecture and Planning.
   The architecture school provided the design and a minority-owned
construction company will do the work, Robinson said. Hooks said he
did not know how much the project would cost.
   The evening before the garden's dedication, a one-woman show
about Parker's life, written by and starring Laurel Ollstein, will
premiere at the Arena Playhouse in Baltimore. The play is titled,
``Hope, Laughter and a Sock in the Eye.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0646 08-25 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Booed by VFW While Defending Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds six grafs to UPDATE with Tennessee appearances.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen, a decorated World War II bomber pilot, was booed by
veterans on Thursday when he said Michael Dukakis and the Democrats
could be trusted with the nation's defense.
   ``The simple truth is this: Gov. Dukakis is a veteran, a
patriot, and an advocate of American strength and steadiness,''
Bentsen told the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention in Chicago.
``He can be trusted as a defender of American security _ and as a
champion of American values.''
   While President Reagan has been a strong advocate for the
military, he ``has purchased military strength at the expense of
national solvency,'' Bentsen said, warning of the threat of the
huge national budget and trade deficits.
   Bentsen himself was warmly received by the crowd and got a
standing ovation. But in trying to make the case for Dukakis on
defense, he was interrupted four times by boos or jeers _ once when
he mentioned former President Carter's name.
   At one point, when Bentsen talked about Dukakis ``bringing
fiscal responsibility and management competence to our national
defense programs,'' the VFW's national commander, Earl L. Stock
Jr., had to stand and quiet the crowd. Bentsen then asked for the
``courtesy to debate,'' and received applause.
   The booing of Dukakis appeared to be led by the Massachusetts
delegation to the convention.
   Jim Reynolds of Florida, a retired veteran who said he was once
the Democratic chairman in Saugus, Mass., said Dukakis was
``anti-veteran'' and had appointed a non-veteran to head the state
soldier's home.
   The Dukakis campaign staff brought out John Halachi, the state
commissioner of veterans affairs, to respond to the event and gave
reporters papers on the governor's positions on veterans issues.
   Halachi, a Vietnam veteran, said the Massachusetts delegation
included a vice chairman of Veterans for Bush. He said the
criticisms of Dukakis were untrue, and that former Gov. Edward King
had appointed the non-veteran.
   Bentsen told reporters he had been prepared for some flak.
   ``I had a tough assignment and I fulfilled it. And I think I
really gave them something to think about,'' he said. ``Obviously,
some of them didn't want to hear it.''
   Bentsen, in his speech, said the Republicans were circulating
``scurrilous charges.'' Bush and Quayle spoke before the VFW
convention on Monday.
   ``At times, I'm afraid, our Republican friends have behaved as
if the flag were a partisan and not a personal virtue,'' he said.
   He received applause when he asserted: ``My friends, if I
believe that there was a thread of truth in that garish tapestry of
partisan blame, I would not have joined Mike Dukakis on the
Democratic ticket.''
   Bentsen wore his American Legion cap as he delivered the address.
   ``I have been in the crosshairs of the enemies of freedom,''
said the 67-year-old former bomber pilot. ``I have been there. And
I yield to no person or party in my passion for freedom.''
   Bentsen cited Dukakis' emphasis on improving non-nuclear
weapons, maintaining a nuclear deterrent, and support of the
Stealth bomber, the cruise missile and a new submarine-launched
missile.
   While praising his running mate, Bentsen blasted both Vice
President George Bush and Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., for supporting
cuts in veterans health care programs.
   ``Each time the Reagan-Bush administration proposed cuts, the
Democrats fought them off,'' he said.
   From Chicago, Bentsen went to an event to honor veterans at the
Gibson County fair in northwest Tennessee, among them about 20
World War I veterans about the age of Bentsen's father, a flier in
the Great War.
   In a talk there, Bentsen said Reagan rejected a military
spending bill because of partisan politics.
   ``The reason he vetoed it was because George Bush came in with
his pollsters and said they wanted to be able to charge the
Democrats with weakness on defense,'' said Bentsen.
   Some of the participants were angry with Bentsen's appearance.
   ``I took my vacation to help my daddy do this,'' said Leanne
Hutchison. ``We were told no politicians would be here, that this
wouldn't be a political thing.''
   ``This has turned into a political party,'' said Brenda Davis as
she helped prepare the military staple ``SOS'' _ creamed chipped
beef on toast.
</TEXT>
