<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChallengerCenter     08-25 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Challenger Center,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Challenger Center `Mission Site' Opens in Houston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two and a half years after the
Challenger exploded, relatives of the crew turned the astronauts'
dream of teaching children about space into reality Thursday with
the opening of the first Challenger Center.
   The center at Houston's Museum of Natural Science, paid for with
a $150,000 private grant, will give students an opportunity to make
a simulated space flight complete with a mission control center and
scientific experiments.
   ``We knew we couldn't launch a satellite. Discovery will do that
for us, but we could continue scientific and education objectives
of that mission,'' said June Scobee, widow of Challenger commander
Dick Scobee and chairman of the board of the Challenger Center.
   ``The Challenger Center mission began with the Challenger crew.
The idea to continue it was a mission by the families,'' she said,
accompanied at the opening by relatives of other crew members.
   ``This is a milestone event,'' said David J. Barram, vice
president of corporate affairs for Apple Computer Inc., which
donated computers to the center. ``The center and its educational
innovations are giant steps down new pathways to knowledge for our
children _ and for us.''
   Mrs. Scobee and the other Challenger relatives conceived the
center as a memorial to the deceased crew and their educational
mission. The Challenger carried Christa McAuliffe, a Concord, N.H.,
high school teacher who was to have conducted the first classroom
experiments from space.
   The Houston center is expected to serve as a model for dozens of
similar centers, or Mission Sites, planned for science museums
throughout the country.
   The planned hub of the network will be the Challenger Center
Space-Life Station, a $15 million facility to be built in
Washington.
   Throughout the summer, 580 Houston-area students have been
training at the Houston Mission Site, which can accommodate 30
students at a time.
   ``It's confusing. It's very complicated to memorize
everything,'' said 10-year-old Lindsay Kemp, who sat in as captain
of mission control during Thursday's simulated flight somewhere
between Earth and Mars. ``But I'm very interested in space and am
learning things.''
   The flight simulator is named ``2061 Simulator'' and is designed
to give children the impression they are on a mission in that year.
   Kerry Joels, director of educational facilities for Challenger
Center, said that year is significant because it will mark the
100th anniversary of spaceflight, the 75th anniversary of the
Challenger, and the next visit to Earth's solar system of Halley's
Comet.
   Museums in 31 cities and five foreign countries have expressed
interest in participating in the program, with Boston; Atlanta;
Charlotte, N.C.; Chicago; St. Louis; Alamagordo, N.M.; Seattle,
Portland, Ore.; and San Diego already taking part in planning
sessions, Challenger Center officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cyprus     08-25 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting Generated Goodwill, But Huge Gap Remains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Vassiliou of Cyprus said Thursday
that his first meeting ever with Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash generated goodwill, ``but there is still a huge gap
between our positions.''
   ``We did not make an effort to narrow or to widen this gap. What
we concetrated on was to get to know each other and agree on the
procedure for future intensive negotiations,'' he told The
Associated Press in an interview.
   ``The fact that we did agree on the procedure so quickly is a
good omen.'' Later, an anonymous bomb threat delayed Vassiliou's
return to Cyprus, but a search of the Olympic Airways Boeing 737
proved the call to be a hoax, said the commander of the Geneva
airport security force, Maj. Roland Troyon.
   U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar invited Vassiliou
and Denktash to Geneva in an effort to break the nearly 3-year-old
deadlock in negotiations for the reunification of the east
Mediterranean island.
   In Ankara, an announcement by the Foreign Ministry expressed
Turkey's pleasure that the two Cypriot leaders decided to start
intercommunal negotiations to seek a settlement.
   Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned since a Turkish
invasion in 1974 following an Athens-backed coup by supporters of
union with Greece.
   The U.N. chief said Wednesday that after conferring with him,
the two men agreed to embark on intensive negotiations in the
island's capital, Nicosia, on Sept. 15. They will meet him again in
New York about six weeks later to review any progress achieved.
   Vassiliou was elected president last February as a non-party
independent candidate with support from both the left and right.
   Four previous top-level meetings since the Turkish invasion,
between Denktash and then-President Spyros Kyprianou and
Kyprianou's predecessor, the late Archbishop Makarios, all failed
to achieve progress.
   The two sides have agreed on a settlement based on establishing
a bizonal federation to reunify the island and dissolve the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state established in north Cyprus in Nov.
1983 and recognized only by Turkey.
   They disagree over constitutional arrangements and the
implementation of U.N. resolutions on Cyprus ignored by Turkey.
   These demand withdrawal of the estimated 30,000 Turkish
occupation troops and 50,000 settlers from Turkey brought to north
Cyprus, and the return of 200,000 expelled Greek Cypriot refugees
to their homes there.
   Denktash reiterated in Geneva his rejection of the troop
withdrawal before the dissolution of the internationally recognized
Cyprus government and the establishment of a joint Greek and
Turkish-Cypriot interim administration.
   But Denktash indicated there were better prospects of a
settlement in talks with Vassiliou, who has stated repeatedly he
wants to settle the problem before the end of his first year in
office.
   ``This is the sort of man I wanted, and I found him. He is the
type I can negotiate seriously with,'' Denktash said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
