<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MarilynQuayle     08-25 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marilyn Quayle,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20-20 Interview: Controversy Media Made</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marilyn Quayle says the controversy over her
husband's service in the National Guard was created by bored,
biased journalists who have ``gone too far.''
   Mrs. Quayle made her comments in an interview Wednesday with
Barbara Walters for the ABC News program ``20-20,'' set to air
Friday night.
   Asked why she thought people are reacting so strongly to the
question of whether Dan Quayle pulled strings to enter the National
Guard at the height of the Vietnam War, Mrs. Quayle replied: ``I
don't think people are. I think it's a total creation of the
media.''
   Mrs. Quayle said it had ``crossed her mind'' that journalists
are out to get the Republican vice-presidential nominee.
   ``I can't substantiate that,'' she said. ``I think part of it is
just the fact that there were so many members of the media down in
New Orleans with nothing to do. And they decided they would find a
story. And they looked wherever they thought they could and dug
something up.''
   She said the race is ``extraordinarily important to our
country.''
   ``And when you deal in rumors and innuendo instead of dealing
with the issues that are important to the continuation of the
success of our country, not only is that an insult to every voter
in this nation, but it's not fair to the voters,'' she said.
``They've (the media) gone too far.''
   Mrs. Quayle said her husband may attract more scrutiny from some
members of the media because of his conservative views.
   ``I just have the feeling that there is in a great deal of the
media a bias not only towards Republicans, but especially towards
conservative Republicans,'' she said. ``And it's come out many
times over, it's something we deal with all the time.''
</TEXT>
