<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Suriname     08-25 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suriname,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suriname, France Sign Agreement to Repatriate 10,000 Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France and Suriname signed an accord
Thursday paving the way for voluntary repatriation of about 10,000
Surinamese refugees who fled into French Guiana to escape fighting
between rebels and the army.
   ``This is a significant step to solve this grave human suffering
and is cause to be hopeful,'' said Gaston Le Paudert, the French
charge d'affaires in Paramaribo.
   France has pledged to help pay the cost of repatriation.
   The agreement did not specify how or when the refugees will be
repatriated. It said, however, that as a first step the refugees
will receive special identification cards.
   Also signing the pact were the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, George Gordon-Lennox, who drafted the text, and
Suriname's foreign affairs minister, Edwin Sedoc.
   ``For the voluntary return of the refugees it is necessary that
peace return in the eastern part of Suriname,'' Le Paudert said.
   Rebel leader Ronny Brunswijk has led a guerrilla war since 1986
against the army in Suriname, a former Dutch colony in northeast
South America. Brunswijk refused to stop the insurgency in the tiny
country despite the election last November of civilian President
Ramsewak Shankar, who replaced junta leader and present army
commander Desi Bouterse.
   Under the accord, the refugees must return voluntarily and
France, which now pays about $1.5 million a month to house and feed
them, cannot evict the refugees from French Guiana.
   The refugees have said they will not go home until they have
guarantees the fighting will stop.
   Meanwhile, 14 barefoot gold miners in a dug-out canoe arrived
Thursday in a small village in Brokopondo province in central
Suriname, and said nine rebels with machine guns had attacked their
isolated camp two days earlier.
   They said the guerrillas beat them and stole all their
valuables. The miners said the rebels took the small amount of gold
they had, loading it onto two boats owned by the mine, and made off
with their shoes, a refrigerator, cooking utensils and shotguns.
   The 14 men reached the village after paddling two days down
Sarakreek River in a large canoe given to them by the rebels, who
told them their mining camp was operated by Bouterse and ordered
them to abandon it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
