<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 2313EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-SDI     08-25 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-SDI,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Deployment Decision Depends on More Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision on whether to deploy a full or
partial Star Wars defense system must await more research into its
capabilities and costs, Republican George Bush said in a published
interview.
   ``We don't know yet, which system is going to be the most
effective, so my view is full funding of the research and then make
the deployment decision when you have all the cards on the table,''
Bush said in an interview published in Friday's editions of The New
York Times.
   The vice president, in an apparent softening of earlier promises
to deploy the Strategic Defense Initiative ``as soon as feasible,''
indicated that cost would be a factor in determining whether to
deploy it. President Reagan has advanced SDI _ an anti-missile
system using new, space-based technologies _ as a shield against
nuclear missiles which could make those weapons obsolete.
   ``I don't think we yet know what the price tag will be,'' Bush
said. ``If you went to a full deployment of a full strategic
defense, it would be very expensive. What I want to do is to
continue reserach at the levels of funding, essentially, that we
have requested.''
   The Reagan administration has asked for more than $4 billion for
SDI research this year.
   Bush also said that he recently has become interested in the
concept of a limited system _ ``not a full shield, but a partial
deployment.''
   ``If I can get convinced by the experts that that would be a
guardian, a safeguard against a weapon accidentally fired, or
weapons in the hands of some terrorist state, then I'd be
interested in this partial deployment,'' he said.
   ``At this juncture I am not prepared to endorse it, but I'm not
prepared to totally reject it,'' Bush added.
   The Times said the interview was conducted as Bush flew to
Houston after a rally in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
   In Bush's speech accepting the Republican nomination for
president last week, he said he would ``continue our policy of
peace through strength,'' and added: ``I will modernize and
preserve our technological edge and that includes strategic
defense.''
   A passage in the Republican Party platform reads, ``We are
committed to rapid and certain deployment of SDI as technologies
permit....''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
