<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-GroceryExpress ADV28   08-25 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Grocery Express, ADV 28,0705</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Recovering Company Delivers Convenience to Busy Customers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Supermarkets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2 of Aug. 23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unassuming green building in this
city's produce district looks like a warehouse and, like a
warehouse, it's filled with row after row of boxes and cans of food.
   But Mary Garvey sees it differently.
   ``This is a laboratory,'' she says. ``We're creating a new
industry.''
   Garvey, 31, is president of Grocery Express, a company that
delivers just about anything you can find on a supermarket shelf to
people who can't or don't want to shop and who are glad to pay a
little extra for convenience.
   ``People have less and less time. And that trend is not
reversing,'' Garvey said in a recent interview.
   About 5,000 people in the city and the northern San Francisco
Peninsula save time by ordering groceries from Garvey's 7-year-old
company and having them delivered for a flat fee of $4.25. Prices
are about 15 percent higher than at large supermarkets and about
the same as at a corner grocery, Garvey said.
   Forty percent of her patrons are businesses, elderly and
homebound people, but the rest are two-income couples, professional
singles or families with young children.
   ``These are people who have no time but lots of demands on their
time,'' she said.
   Katherine Craven, a writer and homemaker, first called Grocery
Express 6{ years ago when she was pregnant and didn't want to climb
stairs to her second-floor Victorian flat with bags of groceries.
   ``For me it's been a great thing, and particularly in the winter
or if someone is sick, it's just a godsend,'' said Craven.
   Customers order from among several hundred items in Grocery
Express' catalog, a 128-page guide that includes fresh flowers,
restaurant meals and food gift baskets as well as fresh meat and
produce and canned and packaged goods.
   Each item has a number, which Grocery Express' clerks punch into
a computer, noting whether customers want their chicken boned or
bananas barely ripe. Customers also can file orders through their
home computers.
   Orders are put together in the company's 18,000-square-foot
warehouse and delivered in one of seven vans.
   Garvey, who has an economics degree from Stanford University,
learned about business from her family's company, Garvey
Industries, a Wichita, Kan.-based concern dealing in oil and gas,
grain and real estate.
   Grocery delivery, while not a new idea, has not been a very
profitable one. Over the past 15 years, other entrepreneurs have
started companies like Grocery Express but failed, Garvey said.
   Grocery Express nearly became one of those failures after an
enthusiastic beginning. Garvey was an original investor, but it was
her former husband, Michael Meagher, and friend John Coghlan who
were the real founders, she said. Garvey became more involved in
the business and took it over two years later.
   In 1984, the company's sales had leveled off at about $2
million, but the firm had yet to turn a profit. Grocery Express
raised its prices, but lost customers and even more money.
   The next year, it came close to shutting down. But Garvey, who
describes herself as eternally optimistic, was sure she could turn
the company around.
   ``I was just certain this is a business people need,'' she said.
``I looked at it from a different point of view _ long term _ and
was willing to spend the additional time and money.''
   Since 1985, Garvey has put between $1.5 million and $2 million
into the firm, reduced prices and used direct mail and radio ads to
regain former customers and win new ones.
   In 1986, sales rose to $2.3 million with a loss of $330,000, and
last year, sales increased to $2.7 million while the company's loss
shrank to $75,000.
   Garvey expects to turn a profit this year. She's also planning
to expand her delivery area and is considering opening another
warehouse.
   Of her company's future, she said, ``It's going to be
interesting to see.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Aug. 28</NOTE>
