<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc. of Los Angeles
and Batus Inc. have ended a bitter eight-month takeover battle,
with Farmers agreeing to be bought by the tobacco and retailing
company for $5.2 billion cash.
   The definitive agreement announced late Wedneady for a friendly
merger at $75 a share would give Louisville, Ky.-based Batus'
British parent, BAT Industries PLC, a long-sought foothold in the
U.S. financial services industry.
   Chairmen of the two companies jointly announced the merger
agreement, which is subject to approval by state regulators and a
majority of Farmers shareholders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. trade deficit shrank 14.9 percent
from April through June, helped by a record high level of exports
and the first quarterly decline in imports in three years, the
government has reported.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday the difference between
what America spends and sells abroad narrowed to a deficit of $29.9
billion in the second quarter, compared to a deficit of $35.2
billion in the first three months of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and South Korea say they regret the U.S.
trade bill that was signed Tuesday by President Reagan, and claim
it has protectionist provisions.
   Reagan called the trade bill a step toward opening worldwide
markets to American products, but expressed displeasure with some
of the provisions.
   In Tokyo, Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Wednesday he
regretted the trade bill but hopes the U.S. government will
implement the law ``in a manner to curb trade protectionism.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's automakers have reported a 13.2
percent dip in their mid-August sales of cars and trucks, but
analysts attribute much of the drop to the curtailment of buyer
incentives.
   General Motors Corp.'s share of the U.S. market slipped during
the period to 46.4 percent, down from 54.3 percent during the same
period last year, according to figures released Wednesday.
   Ford Motor Co. boosted its share from 28.6 percent to 31.6
percent, and Chrysler Corp. increased its share from 11.2 percent
during mid-August 1987 to 13.6 percent during the same period this
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has unveiled some of its
1989 models, including redesigned Thunderbirds and Cougars, and
projected a strong economic picture with total sales of more than
3.7 million cars and trucks.
   The nation's second-largest automaker said it will increase
capacity at some plants to meet higher demand for 1989, which
analysts said may cut into Ford's industry-record earnings so far
this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have opened an investigation
of claims that the rear seat belts on 1.7 million Ford Escort and
Mercury Lynx cars can cripple passengers in a crash, the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration said.
   But the agency said Wednesday the belts, which have an unusual
design, comply with federal standards.
   NHTSA granted part of a petition by a La Plata, Md. couple whose
son was crippled in a 1985 accident while riding in a Ford Escort.
</TEXT>
