<TEXT>
   The International Monetary Fund has offered
Brazil $1.41 billion in new credits to add to the $120.2 billion
the nation is expected to owe at the end of the year.
   The Brazilian government, hard hit by inflation, may draw
installments of the loan through Feb. 28, 1990. Under the fund's
usual practice, reviews are held after each installment to decide
if the borrower has been performing as agreed and whether the next
installment can be drawn.
</TEXT>
