<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices continue to drift lower in
slow summer trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, oil futures finished mostly
lower for a second straight day Wednesday in light trading.
Contracts for October delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, slipped 2 cents a barrel to
close at $15.68, after falling 21 cents a barrel on Tuesday.
   Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline
rose 0.33 cent to finish at 47.51 cents a gallon. Most other
contract months for gasoline declined. Wholesale heating oil for
September fell 0.28 cent to 43.75 cents a gallon.
   Analysts say trading continues to be driven mostly by technical
market factors, as traders await fresh news affecting supply and
demand and, particularly, developments involving the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``The fundamentals are unchanged,'' said Chris Gohler, an energy
futures broker at Elders Futures Inc.
   Even the American Petroleum Institute's weekly report on U.S.
oil inventories, released after the close of trading Tuesday,
failed to shake up the market.
   For the week ended Aug. 19, the API figures showed a decline in
crude oil stocks to around 340 million barrels from 344 million the
previous week, which normally would be bullish for crude prices.
</TEXT>
