<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DrugTests     08-25 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Tests,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Develop On-Site Drug Tests To Cash In On Anti-Drug Trend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small New Jersey company and the local arm
of international pharmaceutical giant F. Hoffmann-La Roche hope to
profit from the fight against drug abuse, through their disposable
drug testing kits.
   The kits are aimed at law enforcement agencies and businesses
that engaged in on-the-spot drug testing, but can be hampered by
the time consuming process of having to send samples off to a lab
for analysis.
   Drug Screening Systems Inc., of Blackwood, is marketing a system
called InstaScreen that it says is as easy to use a brewing a cup
of coffee _ which is where the idea originated.
   ``While making a cup of coffee in a Mr. Coffee machine, we said,
`Hey, why not do something like this?' And that was it,'' said
Raymond F. Akers Jr., a founder of Drug Screening Systems.
   ``Quite honestly, it was one of those, `ah hah!' things,'' he
said in an interview.
   To use the company's device, a urine sample is poured through a
disk-shaped filter that collects detectable amounts concentration
of any illegal narcotics. The filter is chemically treated to hold
any drug traces, and turns the color red if drugs are present.
   Drug Screening's device likely will face competition from the
number of similar tests being created by other companies. One such
competitor is Hoffmann-La Roche Inc. of Nutley, an unit of the
Swiss pharmaceutical giant F. Hoffmann-La Roche & Co.
   Hoffmann-La Roche plans to put its Ontrak system on the market
in October, said Albert Seidner, director of drug abuse marketing
for Hoffmann-La Roche subsidiary Roche Diagnostic Systems.
   Ontrak costs about $2 per test for a specific drug. Urine is
placed on a channeled slide and a chemical is added to detect drug
traces. The tests come in packages of 40 or 100 and are being tried
by criminal justice agencies, said Seidner.
   Patents have been issued for the Hoffmann-La Roche product, he
said. They have been approved for InstaScreen, said Akers' patent
lawyer, Carl Spivak of Philadelphia, but not yet issued.
   InstaScreen kits, which cost about $5, contain gloves, two
collection cups, strainer, chemical disk and vials. It also
includes a bottle for sending positive samples to a lab for
confirmation.
   On-site tests reduce the chance of a mix-up because the samples
do not have to be sent to a lab. Also, the tester does not have to
wait the usual days or weeks for the sample to be returned.
   InstaScreen and Ontrak also are immune to befuddlement by
vinegar or salt, condiments commonly used to mask the presence of
drugs.
   Salt flicked from under a fingernail or vinegar added from a
hidden vial prevents most immunoassay tests from working, Akers
said. In such tests, antibodies bind with the drug chemicals to
register a positive result, but salt and vinegar interfere with the
reaction.
   However, InstaScreen uses chemicals and not antibodies to
identify a drug presence, Akers said.
   Hoffmann-La Roche's test, although it is an immunoassay, is a
type that is not defeated by salt or vinegar, said Seidner.
   Akers founded Drug Screening with his father Raymond F. Akers
Sr. in March 1987. The company went public in May with a $3 million
stock offering. Drug Screening will report its first fiscal year
earnings in several weeks, and expects a profit on a projected $3
million in sales, said Akers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   08-25 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Slip In Mid-August, But Incentives of Last Year Skew Numbers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically-produced cars slipped 18.5
percent in mid-August compared with the same period last year, but
analysts said buyer incentives a year ago colored the latest
figures.
   U.S.-made truck sales fell 1.8 percent during the Aug. 11-20
period, making for a 13.2 percent overall decline in sales of
vehicles from U.S. factories, automakers reported Wednesday.
   The companies reported selling 298,580 cars and trucks during
the period this year, compared with 343,845 vehicles during the
same time last year. There were nine selling days in both periods.
   ``Incentives were just coming in last year and there are no new
incentive programs right now,'' said David Healy, an auto industry
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   Healy said the numbers were misleading because of the
incentives, and that ``They (sales) are very strong.''
   Arvid Jouppi, an analyst in Detroit, disagreed with the strength
of the sales.
   ``The simple story is it's going to take incentives and an early
influx of 1989 models to get the sales moving up again,'' he said.
   Car makers have scheduled their 1989-model introductions through
the coming month. Ford Motor Co. unveiled its 1989 lineup on
Wednesday.
   ``I would say that there is every indication that the industry
has to do one of two things _ get into a very intense
share-of-market war or they have got to simply come up with
innovative new incentives,'' Jouppi said.
   General Motors Corp. showed the largest decline in the 10-day
sales, a 30.3 percent decline to 88,394 cars from 126,887 during
the period last year.
   Ford's sales fell 10 percent, to 60,184 cars from 66,907 cars
last year, and Chrysler Corp. sales fell 0.8 percent to 25,985 this
month from 26,200 during the period last August.
   For the year through Aug. 20, each of the Big Three reported
increased sales compared with the same period last year; GM by 1.2
percent, Ford by 9.9 percent and Chrysler by 13.7 percent.
   During the Aug. 11-20 period, GM's market share fell to 46.4
percent from 54.3 percent during mid-August of last year. Ford's
market share rose to 31.6 percent from 28.6 percent and Chrysler's
share moved up to 13.6 percent from 11.2 percent.
   Honda North America Inc. said it sold 9,259 cars during
mid-August of this year compared with 7,563 cars in the same period
last year _ a 22.4 percent increase.
   Nissan Motor Corp. USA's sales fell 4.5 percent during the
period from 4,380 cars in mid-August 1987 to 4,182 in the same
period this year. Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. reported sales of
1,429 cars during the period this year compared with 1,188 last
year, an increase of 20.3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
