<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Ford-1989 Bjt   08-25 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ford-1989, Bjt,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Unveils 1989 Car Line; Projects 6.7 Percent Annual Sales Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co.'s 1989 model Thunderbirds
and Cougars could help the nation's No. 2 automaker cut further
into sales of industry leader General Motors Corp., according to
one analyst.
   ``Ford has been on a hot streak recently and I wouldn't be
surprised if the new Thunderbird and Cougar allows them to eat some
more of General Motor's lunch as far as market share is
concerned,'' said David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Ford on Wednesday unveiled the redesigned Thunderbird and Cougar
and said it hopes to sell about 1.6 million cars and 1.6 million
trucks in 1989, a 6.7 percent increase over this year's projected 3
million total sales.
   Overall, the industry is forecasting a drop from expected sales
of 10.4 million cars this year.
   At a news conference held to coincide with an auto dealer
convention in neighboring Boston, Ford executives said the company
is targeting sales of about 130,000 each for the new Mercury Cougar
and Ford Thunderbird, which underwent broad design changes in a
five-year, multimillion-dollar development effort.
   Ten-day U.S. automotive sales figures released Wednesday gave
Ford a 31 percent market share compared with 28 percent last year
at this time, while GM slipped from 54 percent to 45 percent.
   ``GM's share has been slipping and I wouldn't be surprised if
these new models keep that trend going,'' Healy said.
   Ford executives said the company will increase production
capacity at some plants to meet higher demand for 1989. The sales
targets for the new Thunderbird and Cougar mark a 30 percent
increase over this year. The company said both cars would be priced
under $20,000.
   ``We're convinced at Ford that the economy is going to remain as
good as it is today,'' said Ross H. Roberts, general manager of
Ford's Lincoln-Mercury Division. ``We see nothing on the horizon,
none of those black clouds you frequently hear about, that says
business is going to be bad.''
   The new Cougar is two inches shorter than current models, the
wheelbase is nine inches longer and the car sits lower to the
ground. Roberts said the 113-inch wheelbase adds 10 cubic feet to
the passenger compartment. It has just six carryover parts from
this year, including the name and crest.
   The 1989 model Thunderbird, which led Ford's move to aerodynamic
styling five years ago, has a nine-inch longer wheelbase than this
year's model, low profile headlamps, and larger wheels and brakes.
   Some of the new Cougars and Thunderbirds will be equipped with a
standard 3.8-liter V-6 engine.
   ``These vehicles are going to come on strong with higher
performance engines,'' said Thomas O'Grady of Integrated Automotive
Resources, a market researcher in Wayne, Pa.
   Ford earned $1.66 billion in the second quarter of 1988, setting
an industry earnings record for the second straight three-month
period. In the first quarter, Ford earned $1.623 billion.
   Aside from the Cougar and Thunderbird, other new Ford lines
showed few if any changes for 1989, the 50th anniversary of the
Mercury name.
   Production of Thunderbird and Cougar is to begin in October. The
cars will be on introduced to the public Dec. 26 _ both late starts
for a new model year, which officially begins Oct. 1.
   Lincoln-Mercury is targeting total sales of 717,000 cars next
year, a 7 percent market share of a projected 10.25 million car
sales. That would be an increase of 0.3 percentage points over this
year and give the division its best year since 1978.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SchererFight     08-25 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer Fight,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Leaves Open Possible Challenge To Stockholder Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.P. Scherer Corp.'s management said it plans
to seek a review of the election of two directors who represent a
group that favors selling the pharmaceutical capsule maker.
   Dissident shareholders led by the company founder's daughter,
Karla Scherer Fink, elected the new directors to the 11-member
Scherer board, according to proxy voting results announced
Wednesday.
   The vote, which took place at the company's Aug. 17 annual
meeting, left directors who back management and oppose selling
Scherer with a 6-5 edge on the board, compared with 8-5 before the
vote, the dissidents said.
   Scherer Chief Executive Officer Peter Fink, Karla Fink's
estranged husband, said acknowledged the election of dissident
candidate Frederick Frank to the board, but said the results of
close voting in the seat apparently won by dissident Theodore
Souris, who unseated incumbent Peter Dow, would be reviewed.
   Theodore won 3,019,449 votes to Dow's 2,670,876.
   Karla Fink and her shareholders' committee disputed the need for
a review, spokeswoman Beth Lyons said. ``The election is final and
official,'' she said. ``That is the certified count from the
inspectors.''
   But Peter Fink said the company would insist on a complete
review of proxy cards voted for Souris and Dow.
   In a statement to employees following the meeting, he said,
``Perhaps the most important fact for you to remember is that
regardless of the outcome of the election, we have received no
offers to buy the company.''
   ``Furthermore, even if Mrs. Fink's nominees for directors are
both seated, she would still not have enough support on the board
of directors to gain approval for her proposed sale of the
company,'' Fink said.
   Karla Fink has said she would try to convince additional
directors of the wisdom of putting the company up for sale, and
launch another proxy fight at next year's annual meeting to try to
elect additional directors backing her position.
   Scherer Chairman Wilber Mack adjourned the meeting until 10 a.m.
Sept. 1, saying results of the review would be announced then.
   Karla Fink and board member John Scherer, the son of company
founder John S. Scherer, disputed Mack's authority to adjourn and
stated they were accepting the voting results as announced.
   Scherer, with 2,800 employees, is a leading maker of soft
gelatin capsules for drugs, vitamin supplements and similar
products. It had record sales of $290.7 million and earnings of
$15.1 million for its fiscal year ending March 31.
</TEXT>
