<HEAD>Dollar Lower in Europe, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mostly lower against the major
currencies in European markets today.
   Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said their markets were nervous and
inclined to sell ahead of developments expected later in the day,
including U.S. gross national product statistics, the British trade
figures and German interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.54 yen to a closing 133.76 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 133.55 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates, included: 1.8767 West German marks, down from 1.8915; 1.5820
Swiss francs, down from 1.5950; 6.3735 French francs, down from
6.4250; 2.1185 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1370; 1,393.50.Italian
lire, down from 1,403.50; and 1.2330 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2321.
   In London, the British pound was trading at $1.6825, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.6788 rate.
   Gold, which gained $2.75 a troy ounce in New York on Wednesday
as the dollar fell, opened in London at a bid price of $434.70 a
troy ounce. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $434.80. Both were up from Tuesday's
late bid of $433.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $434.75, up from $433.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.1 to close at a bid $436.10.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.78 a troy
ounce, down from $6.81 at Wednesday's close.
</TEXT>
