<HEAD>Stocks Rise, Dollar Falls Slightly in Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices recovered moderately in thin trading
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, while the dollar edged downward.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 70.77
points, or 0.25 percent, to close at 27,870.44.
   The market's main index rebounded toward the end of the
afternoon trading despite its 31.32-point decline during the
morning session. It opened at 27,924.39.
   Trading was thin with 400 million shares, due to a strong
wait-and-see mood among investors, according to Nikko Securities'
Yoshio Shimoyama.
   ``Investors just weren't buying enough, waiting to see what
happens to the West German bank's decision on its discount rate. In
addition, the U.S. GNP report is coming out right after that,'' he
said. The revised U.S. gross national product figure for the second
quarter will be announced Friday.
   Among the issues that led the market's recovery today were steel
and real estate stocks.
   Investors on the foreign exchange trading were also in a
cautious mood, although some dollar-selling in Europe and Tokyo
weakened the value of the U.S. currency, said an exchange dealer at
a commercial bank in Tokyo.
   ``Nothing starts until the West German decision (on the discount
rate) comes out,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
