<DOCNO> AP880825-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Farmers-Batus Bjt   08-25 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farmers-Batus, Bjt,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Insurance Group Agrees to $5.2 billion Buyout by Batus
Inc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc. has agreed to a
$5.2 billion cash acquisition by Batus Inc., ending an acrimonious
eight-month takeover battle.
   The agreement at a price $3 per share higher than Batus' last
publicly announced bid was revealed Wednesday night by the chairmen
of Los Angeles-based Farmers and Batus, the Louisville, Ky.-based,
tobacco and retailing company.
   The agreement for a friendly merger at $75 a share would give
Batus' British parent, B.A.T Industries PLC, a foothold in the U.S.
financial services industry.
   The two sides began discussing a friendly buyout late last week
when Batus offered $72 per share, an increase of $9 per share over
its previous best offer.
   Stock of Farmers, the seventh-largest property and casualty
insurer, dipped 50 cents to $69.25 a share in active
over-the-counter trading Wednesday. The agreement was announced
hours after the market closed.
   ``In reaching its unanimous decision, Farmers' board of
directors considered the concerns regarding this combination which
have been raised during regulatory hearings, and has been satisfied
that these concerns will be adequately addressed in the merger of
the two companies,'' said Leo E. Denlea, Jr. chairman and chief
executive officer of Farmers Group Inc.
   ``We firmly believe that Farmers and Batus can work with the
insurance regulators to give the assurances necessary to enable
this merger to be accomplished to the benefit of all parties,''
Denlea added.
   Farmers' resistance to Batus included suggestions that the
company had suppressed research pointing to the dangers of smoking.
Farmers also persuaded a number of state and national lawmakers to
attack the British parent firm because it has operations in
racially segregated South Africa.
   But the merger talks, which began last Wednesday, were strictly
business, said Patrick Sheehy, chairman of both B.A.T and Batus.
   ``I think often things that are said in court are much more
acrimonious than one's true feelings,'' Sheehy said in an
interview. ``When it came to sitting down and talking, we both
decided we were going to do it in a spirit of trust and good will.''
   Sheehy said Farmers was pursued because it was found to be the
U.S. insurer most like B.A.T's British insurance business.
Attractions included similar lines of insurance and a
company-operated network of 14,000 agents.
   Sheehy said negotiations were complicated by Farmers' structure.
The Farmers group is made up of three policyholder-owned insurance
exchanges and a company-owned life insurance business.
   Farmers has 68.4 million common shares outstanding.
   Batus promised that Farmers' operations would be essentially
unchanged under the new ownership and Farmers suggested it would
drop its fierce resistance to Batus in hearings before insurance
regulators in several states.
   A joint announcement said that Batus, Farmers, Farmers Insurance
Exchange, Fire Insurance Exchange and Truck Insurance Exchange, the
reciprocal insurance exchanges managed by Farmers, have agreed to
provisions that would assure that the exchanges and their
policyholders would not be adversely affected in the merger.
   Batus began pursuing Farmers in January with a friendly offer of
$60 a share that was spurned by Farmers' management.
   Farmers resisted the buyout in hearings before insurance
regulators in nine states where the merger needed approval.
   The company claimed that Batus, which owns the maker of Kool and
Viceroy cigarettes, was unlikely to continue Farmers' emphasis on
non-smoker insurance discounts. Batus has vowed to continue the
discounts.
   The merger won the approval of insurance regulators in Arizona,
and was given conditional approval in Ohio and Illinois. Idaho,
Washington and Oregon have rejected the deal and decisions or
hearings are pending in Texas and Kansas.
   California regulators rejected the merger, but that decision was
overturned by a state court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
