<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru   08-25 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0426</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES 6th graf to indicate market down more than 50 points</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit spurted 72
percent to a record 2.65 billion pounds, the equivalent of $4.5
billion, in July, the government reported Thursday.
   Immediately after the report was released, the Bank of England
signaled a full percentage point increase in the British commercial
banks' base lending rate to 12 percent.
   Barlcays Bank PLC, Midland Bank PLC, Lloyds Banks PLC and
National Westminster Bank PLC quickly responded.
   That was the eighth time the central bank signaled an increase
in the benchmark rate since early June when it stood at a 10-year
low of 7.5 percent. All the previous increases had been half-point
gains.
   Stock prices plunged, but the pound, uncertain, darted up and
down on the news.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, which had
been down just about 3 points earlier, fell 50.6 points, or 2.8
percent, to 1,768.6 by 2:00 p.m.
   The pound was quoted at 1.6805 dollars after the news vs. 1.6915
dollars before.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said the interest rate
hike was necessary and that interest rates would remain at current
levels from some time.
   ``The import figures confirm that the economy has been growing
too fast. We have to slow it down and that means higher interest
rates,'' Lawson said in a British Broadcasting Corp. radio
interview.
   ``The government is determined to do whatever is necessary to
keep inflation under control,'' Lawson said.
   The deficit compared with a revised shortfall off 1.54 billion
pounds (2.6 billion dollars) in June and a 1.02 billion-pound (1.7
billion-dollar) gap in July 1987, the Department of Trade and
Industry said.
   Britain's current account deficit spurted to 2.15 billion pounds
($3.6 billion) in July, compared with a revised deficit of 1.04
billion pounds ($1.8 billion) in June and a deficit of 323 million
pounds ($546 million) in July 1987.
   The current account includes ``invisible'' trade, such as
services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer
payments, which was estimated to be in surplus by 500 million
pounds ($845 million) in July.
   July's deficits were much larger than expected by the markets,
which had anticipated a merchandise trade gap of 1.51 billion
pounds ($2.6 billion) and a current account deficit of 1.01 billion
pounds ($1.7 billion).
   The department originally reported June's trade deficit as 1.52
billion pounds ($2.6 billion) and the current account deficit as
1.02 billion pounds ($1.7 billion).
</TEXT>
