<2ND_LINE>PM-Pan Am-Labor, 1st Ld-Writethru,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pan Am, Flight Attendants Break Off Contract Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 1-3 to UPDATE with Pan Am confirmation, statement
from spokesman; DELETES 4th graf pvs now redundant; picks up 5th
graf pvs bg'ng, Pan Am management ...; SUBS 8th graf to CLARIFY
that cooling-off period would follow declaration of impasse; picks
up 9th graf pvs bg'ng, Margaret Brennan, ...; SUBS 10th graf to ADD
that Transport Workers also sought mediation; picks up 11th graf
pvs bg'ng, Pan Am had ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks between ailing Pan Am Corp. and
its flight attendants union are at an impasse, and the airline is
seeking federal mediation, according to Pan Am and union
representatives.
   The union made a proposal countering the company's offer at a
Tuesday meeting, but Pan Am rejected it without discussion, flight
attendants union spokeswoman Lois Schneider said Wednesday.
   Pan Am spokesman Alan Loflin refuted that statement today. ``We
were willing to negotiate,'' he said.
   Loflin said Pan Am officials asked the National Mediation Board
Wednesday to bring a federal mediator into the negotiations. New
contract talks have not been scheduled yet.
   Pan Am management has been seeking $90 million in wage
reductions from the Independent Union of Flight Attendants over
three years, as part of its plan for financial recovery.
   The union's counter-proposal involved smaller wage cuts, Ms.
Schneider said.
   ``At this point, we're considering options,'' she said.
   The flight attendants' contract expires on Aug. 31. Under
federal labor rules, the union could strike at the end of a 30-day
``cooling-off'' period following the declaration of an impasse by
the mediator.
   Margaret Brennan, the union's president, issued a statement
contending Pan Am's latest action shows it intended to take labor
relations ``back to the dark ages.'' She asked for a congressional
investigation into Pan Am and its actions in the negotiations.
   Members of the largest union at Pan Am, the Transport Workers,
recently rejected a wage freeze agreement that would have saved the
company an estimated $81 million over three years. The Transport
Workers union also has asked for federal mediation.
   Pan Am had a net loss of $265.3 million last year and is seeking
about $540 million in pay cuts and other concessions over three
years to turn itself around. Its chairman, Thomas Plaskett,
recently said the airline might sell its Latin American routes if
labor concessions are not made.
   The two unions representing pilots and flight engineers at Pan
Am agreed earlier this year to wage cuts totaling about $240
million over three years.
   Pan Am also has imposed $35 million in cuts under federal labor
rules on employees represented by the Teamsters union.
</TEXT>
