<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened lower today, unable to
extend the brisk rally of the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which climbed 37.34
points on Wednesday, was down 14.40 at 2,012.27 after 30 minutes of
trading.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 7 to 2 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 199 up, 713 down
and 455 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 19.69 million shares as of 10 a.m.
on Wall Street compared with 18.09 million shares at the same point
Wednesday.
   Analysts said interest rate worries continued to weigh upon the
market.
   Before the New York stock market opened today, the West German
central bank raised a key lending rate and banks in several other
European countries followed suit.
   Those developments sent the U.S. bond market lower in early
trading.
   The 30-year Treasury bond, for instance, lost about $7.50 for
every $1,000 in face value while its yield jumped to 9.47 percent
from 9.40 percent.
   Analysts said the increase in European rates stirred speculation
that U.S. rates could also be headed higher. That hurt stocks
because higher rates could cut corporate profits and make
government notes and bonds more attractive.
   The U.S. government's announcement today that it had revised its
estimate of second-quarter economic growth upward to 3.3 percent
rate from 3.1 percent had been anticipated and appeared to have
little impact on the market.
   Today's activity comes on the first anniversary of the Dow Jones
industrial average's peak of 2,722.42.
   Among the early active issues on the NYSE, International
Business Machines was off } at 112, American Express fell { to 28\
and American Telephone & Relegraph was down \ at 24}.
   In over-the-counter trading, Farmers Group was up { at 69}. The
company agreed to a $75-a-share takeover offer from B.A.T.
Industries of Britain.
   The NYSE index was off 0.95 at 146.98. On the American Stock
Exchange, the composite market value index fell 0.64 to 293.42.
   On Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 37.34
points to 2,026.67, its biggest gain in nearly a month.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5-to-2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,089 issues up, 376 down and 498 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 127.80 million shares,
up from 119.54 million in the previous session.
