<2ND_LINE>PM-Gillette,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette Secures $1.2 Billion In Credit For Stock Buyback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. said it has secured $1.2 billion in
credit for the stock repurchase program it created as part of a
settlement with a dissident shareholder group that fought for
control of the toiletry company.
   A syndicate of banks will supply the credit, including $730
million to buy back stock from shareholders, Gillette said
Wednesday.
   The stock repurchase plan was announced earlier this month as
part of an out-of-court settlement that ended a bitter proxy fight
between Gillette and Coniston Partners, a New York investment firm.
Coniston wanted control of Gillette's board to sell the company to
the highest bidder.
   Both sides sued each other, charging violations of of federal
securities laws during the proxy fight.
   Under the stock buyback plan, stockholders will be able to sell
one-seventh of their shares to Gillette at or above a market price
of $45. Stockholders also have the right to sell their options.
   Gillette said it plans to repurchase 16 million shares of its
112 million outstanding shares. Coniston, Gillette's largest
shareholder, would net a profit of about $14.4 million before
expenses by selling back 1.1 million shares. It still would own
about 6 million Gillette shares.
