<1ST_LINE>u f PM-InterestRates     08-25 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Interest Rates,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germans Raise Key Interest Rates; Other Europeans Follow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank raised a key interest rate today to
3.5 percent from 3 percent because of the stronger dollar, and
central banks in several Western European countries quickly
followed.
   The action marked the latest in a round of higher interest rates
worldwide and came a few weeks after the U.S. Federal Reserve
tightened credit in the United States by pushing interest rates
higher.
   The U.S. currency slumped in response to the action today by the
West German Bundesbank and other European banks. The dollar was
quoted at around 1.8660 West German marks at midmorning in New
York, down sharply from 1.8820 marks late Wednesday.
   In Britain, the Bank of England signaled a full percentage point
increase in the British commercial banks' base lending rate to 12
percent, following a government report on the country's trade
deficit in July.
   The report showed the July trade gap soared 72 percent to a
record 2.65 billion pounds, or about $4.5 billion.
   The central banks of Switzerland, Austria and the Netherlands
announced interest rate hikes shortly after the Bundesbank move.
   In Tokyo, however, a senior Bank of Japan official said there is
``absolutely no need to consider an adjustment in Japan's monetary
policy just because the Bundesbank and the Bank of England raised
their base rates.''
   The higher West German discount rate goes into effect on Friday,
the Bundesbank said in a statement. The discount rate is the
interest the Bundesbank charges on loans to other banks.
   The Bundesbank was selling dollars in the open market shortly
after making its announcement, according to currency dealers in
Frankfurt, West Germany.
   Karl Otto Poehl, president of the Bundesbank, cited the weakness
of the West German mark against the dollar as a reason for lifting
the key rate, which makes mark-denominated investments more
attractive.
   ``Today's step is an important signal which will be understood
by the foreign-exchange and capital markets,'' Poehl said. ``It
should lead to stabilization of the (currency) and capital markets
and the first reactions should show this is the case.''
   Following the Bundesbank action, the dollar slid to 1.8640 marks
at the Frankfurt currency exchange in early afternoon.
   Earlier, the U.S. currency had fallen to an official Frankfurt
fixing of 1.8764 marks from Wednesday's official level of 1.8960
marks.
   Poehl told reporters that the dollar's strength against the mark
endangered efforts to adjust trade imbalances between the world's
major trading partners.
   He also said the Bundesbank will ``continue to do everything to
stem the decline of the mark against the dollar.''
   The Bundesbank president also said the discount rate increase
was aimed at curbing West German inflation and bringing the
country's above-target money supply growth back into the proper
range.
   The Bundesbank has adjusted domestic interest rates upwards
three times in the past eight weeks.
</TEXT>
