<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   08-25 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GNP Strong, Inflation Rises, Foreign Interest Rates Up, Home Sales
Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with interest-rate hikes
abroad, home sales report and stock market reax. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, The difference ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   America's economy and corporate profits expanded briskly this
spring, the government said today, but the news was overshadowed by
higher inflation, rising interest rates, slumping financial markets
and a slowdown in home sales.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of economic health, rose at an annual rate of 3.3
percent from April through June despite severe shock from the
drought that seared much of the country. The GNP rate of expansion
was unchanged from the first quarter.
   Without the drought, the GNP would have shot up at a 4.3 percent
annual rate in the April-June period.
   The government also said after-tax corporate profits shot up
11.5 percent in the second quarter following a 2.5 percent rise in
the first quarter. The performance was the best since a 14.5
percent rise in the 1983 second quarter.
   But April-June inflation as measured by a GNP price index rose
at an annual rate of 5.1 percent, the fastest increase since a 5.8
percent rise in the third quarter of 1982, the department said. The
surge was blamed on higher prices for clothes, food and fuel.
   Further obscuring the GNP and corporate profit news was that key
West European nations raised interest rates today, blaming the move
on the stronger U.S. dollar and consequent weakness in their own
currencies. The increases signaled another round of higher interest
rates worldwide.
   Those developments helped incite a selloff in the bond market, a
sensitive barometer of interest rates and the economy. The
Treasury's key 30-year issue fell nearly $7.50 per $1,000 in face
amount and its yield rose to 9.46 percent from 9.39 percent late
Wednesday.
   On Wall Street, where traders were recalling the stock market
peak a year ago today, prices slid as well. The Dow Jones
industrial average was down about 18 points to the 2,008 level by
late morning.
   Rising interest rates also played a key role in a 5 percent drop
in existing single-family home sales last month, a real estate
trade group said today. The National Association of Realtors said
the decline was partly the result of higher mortgage costs.
   The developments came a day after the government reported
America's trade deficit shrank 15 percent in the April-June
quarter, which heartened Republicans fighting to retain the White
House but didn't impress the financial markets.
   The difference between what the United States spends and sells
abroad narrowed to a deficit of $29.9 billion in the second
quarter, compared with a $35.2 billion deficit in the first quarter.
   Many economists regard the trade deficit as one of the most
visible weaknesses in the economy, reflecting a relentless
addiction to cheap imports and consequent difficulty for domestic
companies trying to compete. Democrats have attempted to make the
trade deficit an issue in the presidential campaign.
   But the improvement reported Wednesday suggested U.S.
manufacturers were making strong gains in selling abroad. Some
economists are predicting the trade deficit will drop by nearly 25
percent for the entire year, marking the first annual improvement
since President Reagan took office.
   Republicans are hoping voters will focus on the improvement,
which already has shown up in the Commerce Department's monthly
merchandise trade reports.
   In other economic news, major automakers said Wednesday that
mid-August sales of U.S.-made cars and trucks fell by 13.2 percent
from the same period a year earlier, when sales were inflated by
buyers taking advantage of dealer incentives.
</TEXT>
