<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Chocolate,0160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dingell Urges Japan to End Restrictions on U.S. Chocolate Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan should eliminate barriers that restrict
U.S. chocolate manufacturers from promoting their products in that
country, says the chairman of the House of Representatives' Energy
and Commerce Committee.
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said in letters made available
Thursday that discriminatory trade practices ``directly affect more
than $75 million in retail sales by American chocolate
manufacturers in Japan.''
   In the letters, sent on Monday to Nobuo Matsunaga, Japan's
ambassador in Washington, and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter, Dingell called for swift action to end the chocolate
restrictions.
   ``In the Japanese system, industry trade associations can
establish fair competition codes, which are then adopted by the
Japan Fair Trade Commission,'' Dingell said.
   ``Among other things, these codes limit promotional activities,
such as lotteries or premiums offered to consumers _ activities
that Japanese companies can conduct freely in America,'' he said.
</TEXT>
