<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders started out looking for confirmation of rumors that
China was planning a big soyoil purchase that would be subsidized
under the U.S. export bonus program. But when that failed to
materialize, they promptly took a big chunk of the top of soyoil
prices.
   Wheat, meanwhile, took a hit when a Department of Agriculture
official denied that a one-year extension of the grain accord with
the Soviets already was complete.
   That pact, the first step in what is anticipated to result in
another five-year deal between the superpowers, still is expected
to be complete sometime soon.
   On the opening, wheat was 3 cents to 4{ cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.94 a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1\ cents higher, with September at $2.54{; corn was } cent
to 2{ cents higher, with September at $2.85 a bushel; and soybeans
were 6 cents lower to 7 cents higher, with September at $8.35 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures prices opened mixed at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower .22 cent higher, with October at
71.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .23 cent
higher, with August at 81.60 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent
lower to .10 cent higher, with October at 40.50 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .45 cent higher, with February
at 54.40 cents a pound.
