<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ColaPriceFixing 1stLd-Writethru f0054 08-25 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cola Price Fixing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0054,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sentencing of Md. Businessman, Former 7-Up President Delayed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs to UPDATE with judge denying new-trial
motion. Picks up 4th graf pvs, At the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today denied motions for a
new trial for a Maryland entrepreneur, the former president of the
Seven-Up Co. and a soft drink bottler who had been convicted of
price fixing.
   Morton M. Lapides, 57, chairman of the board of Alleghany
Beverage Corp. of Cheverly, Md., and James J. Harford, former
president of Mid-Atlantic Coca-Cola Bottling of Silver Spring, Md.,
and the Alleghany Bottling Co. were convicted following a six-week
trial in April and May.
   Lapides and Harford face a maximum three years in prison.
Alleghany faces a maximum $1 million fine. U.S. District Judge
Robert G. Doumar was expected to impose sentences today.
   ``I am very concerned with restitution to the public,'' Doumar
said. ``People who believe money is the answer to any crime because
they are a corporation should think differently when they enter
this court.'
   At the time of his conviction, Harford was the president of
Seven-Up, but resigned that post three days after the conviction.
Harford's conviction was the result of actions while heading the
Coca-Cola bottling firm, and did not involve Seven-Up.
   The convictions were part of an on-going Justice Department
probe of the soft drink industry, which has resulted in 11 grand
jury investigations in eight other states.
   Lapides and Harford were convicted of rigging the wholesale
price of their respective products in 1983 and 1984. Alleghany
Beverage was the parent company of Alleghany Pepsi-Cola Bottling
Co. until 1985 when Lapides sold the subsidiary for $160 million.
   During the trial, the defense contended that neither man knew of
the scheme and that if the allegations were true, then it was the
work of lower level employees who made decisions without their
bosses' knowledge.
   Federal prosecutors argued that the two bottlers reached an
accord to halt the previous bitter competition by fixing the
wholesale price of their products sold to schools, motels, hotels,
and other commercial buyers in Maryland and Virgina.
   Mid-Atlantic pleaded guilty to earlier, similar indictments and
agreed to pay $2 million in fines for price rigging in Virginia and
Washington, D.C., markets.
   In March, both bottling firms also agreed to rebate $45,000 to
Virginia to be distributed to school districts for overcharges on
their soft drink purchases. The agreement drawn up by Attorney
General Mary Sue Terry called for Mid-Atlantic to pay $30,000 and
Alleghany $15,000.
   Prior to the April conviction, several other soft drink
executives have been found guilty or pleaded guilty to a variety of
charges.
   In February 1987, Armand S. Gravely, a former Richmond division
manager for Alleghany, was convicted of price fixing and
obstruction of justice. He was sentenced to four months in jail and
fined $15,000.
   Edward L. Wynns, a Mid-Atlantic vice president, pleaded guilty
in May 1987 to charges he lied to the grand jury investigating the
price fixing.
   The former president of Alleghany Bottling, James P. Sheridan of
Timonium, Md., was given a 3-year sentence, with all but 120 days
suspended, and fined $45,000 in August 1987 after pleading guilty
to price fixing.
   A third executive indicted along with Lapides and Harford, Odis
R. Allen, a Mid-Atlantic vice president, pleaded guilty to price
fixing in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
