estimate of second-quarter economic growth to 3.3 percent rate from
3.1 percent. While that revision was in line with expectations,
analysts said a simultaneous upward revision in an inflation
measure tied to the gross national product worried some traders.
   Prices in the U.S. credit market moved lower in the early going,
pushing interest rates higher.
   The 30-year Treasury bond, for instance, lost about $7.50 for
every $1,000 in face value, while its yield jumped to 9.48 percent
from 9.40 percent late Wednesday.
