<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RailSale     08-25 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rail Sale,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds CNW Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has ruled that CNW Corp.
may sell 208 miles of railroad without giving labor unions a voice
in the sale.
   The decision by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals affirms an
earlier U.S. District Court ruling.
   The decision also bars a threatened strike against CNW's Chicago
& North Western Transportation Co. railroad by unions opposed to
the proposed track sale.
   The Railway Labor Executives' Association had filed a motion to
stop the railroad from closing the sale to FRVR Corp., a subsidiary
of Chicago-based Itel Corp.
   The association said Wednesday it was considering appealing the
circuit court decision to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The labor group, citing the Railway Labor Act, had argued that
the railroad was obligated to negotiate over the effects of the
sale on its employees because it will result in changed pay,
seniority and working conditions.
   CNW contended the labor issues involved constitute a minor
dispute that should be resolved in binding arbitration.
   ``We are free to sell branch lines to regional line operators,''
said company spokesman James Foote after the ruling. ``The decision
means the unions can't strike over the sale because it's a minor
dispute.''
   The section of track, which runs from Milwaukee to Green Bay,
Wis., will be called the Fox River Valley Railroad after the sale
to FRVR is complete, Foote said.
   Chicago-based CNW is the holding company for the railroad, a
leading Midwest freight hauler that also operates area commuter
trains used by 41,000 people.
   The sale of the line is not related to a contract dispute over
train crew size that caused a brief strike at C&NW earlier this
month. The walkout was halted by Congress, which extended a
cooling-off period until Sept. 9.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
