<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1326EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-IllegalExports 1stLd-Writethru   08-25 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Illegal Exports, 1st Ld-Writethru,0844</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Thinks Illegal Exports Aided Soviet Fighter Production</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to update. A version moving on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon said today it believes the Soviet
Union's jet fighter program has benefitted from the diversion of
French milling equipment in a case of illegal exporting that rivals
the wrongdoing by Japan's Toshiba Corp.
   Fred Hoffman, a Pentagon spokesman, said a French concern by the
name of Forest Line is under investigation by authorities in France
and the United States.
   ``The investigation involves the alleged diversion of dozens of
very sophisticated milling machines to military users in the Soviet
Union,'' Hoffman added.
   ``We believe the machines were used in the Soviet MiG (jet
fighter) program.''
   Hoffman was asked about the investigation after another top
Pentagon official, Stephen D. Bryen, told a group of Pentagon
reporters Wednesday that U.S. authorities have been deeply involved
in investigating a ``serious'' technology diversion case.
   Bryen, the deputy undersecretary of defense for trade security
policy, refused at the time to identify the company under
investigation. He said only that American investigators were
receiving ``splendid cooperation'' in the matter; that some
individuals already had been charged and other arrests would
follow, and that he hoped to make more information available in a
few months.
   Other government sources then disclosed Wednesday the
investigation concerned a French company known as Forest Line that
once went by the name of Ratier-Forest, and that information was
subsequently acknowledged by Hoffman.
   ``The case ... involves a French company which is currently
under investigation by the French government,'' said Hoffman. ``The
company name is Forest Line.''
   The other sources, who insisted on anonymity, said U.S.
intelligence agents tipped the French early this year about alleged
Forest Line sales of heavy milling equipment to the Soviet Union.
   ``There has been good cooperation,'' said one source. ``We
shared information with them and they moved quickly.''
   The French case surfaced last spring but attracted little notice
then.
   French authorities disclosed in April that four people had been
arrested under anti-espionage laws, including Louis Tardy, chairman
of Machines Francaises Lourdes, and Jean-Paul Chamouton, president
of Forest Line.
   Machines Francaises Lourdes, now bankrupt, was the parent
company of Forest Line, which specialized in manufacturing heavy
tool equipment.
   No trials have been held, and the status of the cases is unclear.
   The Toshiba scandal came to a head earlier this year when the
Toshiba Machine Co., a majority-owned subsidiary, was found guilty
in a Japanese court of illegally trading high-tech items with the
Soviet Union. The firm was convicted of selling sophisticated
milling machines to the Soviet Union in the early 1980s. The
machines can be used to fashion quiet submarine propellers.
   U.S. military experts claim the Toshiba sale has complicated
dramatically the task of locating Russian subs.
   Bryen, while never naming the company now under investigation,
drew attention to the matter Wednesday when asked if the Pentagon
had become involved in any other major export probes since Toshiba.
   ``There's even a bigger one, but it's different,'' Bryen
replied. ``It's a different kind of case because, first of all,
we've had splendid cooperation on it. There's more, much more
involved than the Toshiba case.
   ``It's certainly serious and it's in a different field; it's in
the aerospace area,'' he said. ``It's under investigation and there
have already been some equivalent of U.S. indictments on the case,
in another country. There's going to be some others.
   ``But I'm going to be real cagey on this because I don't want to
spring it yet. But I think in the next few months we should be
prepared to describe it in more detail.''
   Asked if any American citizens were known to be involved, he
replied: ``Not that I know of at the moment.''
   The Toshiba incident helped lead to enactment of new trade
legislation and sanctions against that company in the United States
as well as a Japanese government overhaul of export licensing
procedures.
   Last fall, when revelations about the Toshiba case were
surfacing, a Norwegian police investigation found that several
European companies _ including Forest Line _ had conspired to
divert sensitive technology to the Soviets dating back to the 1970s.
   The U.S. sources said Wednesday, however, that the current
investigation involved equipment sales that continued at least
through 1986 and possibly 1987 _ long after the last Toshiba
transaction.
   ``That's what makes it serious,'' one source said.
   The Forest Line equipment, said to include huge milling
machinery that can be used to fabricate aircraft fuselages and jet
engine turbine blades, was allegedly sold to the Soviets after
corporate executives submitted fraudulent applications for export
licenses, the sources said.
   Bryen told reporters the Reagan administration has made great
strides in clamping down on the exports of sensitive military
technology to the East bloc and in convincing U.S. allies to do the
same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
