<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-JapaneseSinging Bjt   08-25 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japanese Singing, Bjt,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Sing for Success in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the thought of giving an after-dinner speech
makes you nervous, singing in a foreign language for prospective
clients might cause you to lose your appetite.
   Honolulu attorney Wallace Fujiyama did not like the idea, but
after socializing with Japanese clients, he realized American
business skills were not enough to assure success in Tokyo.
   He spoke Japanese, but, he says, he needed to learn to sing it.
   ``If you're going to succeed as a businessman, you have to do
business the way they do it, and in Japan, everybody sings,'' says
Fujiyama. ``Everybody from the ordinary salary worker to the
corporate presidents and executives.''
   The songfests usually begin after a business meeting or social
gathering, he says, when the company's executives take their turn
at the microphone singing popular Japanese tunes. After they are
finished, their guests, such as Fujiyama, are invited to give it a
go.
   ``For you to refuse is a great insult, but to sing badly is even
worse,'' he says.
   So Fujiyama began to practice, first by singing along in his car
with ``karaoke'' tapes, which are high-quality instrumental
versions of popular songs. Later, one of his Japanese clients gave
him with an elaborate sound system for his downtown Honolulu
office, complete with laser disk, two tape players and an oversized
video screen so he could watch his technique.
   A star was not quite born, but Fujiyama swears he is improving.
   ``I still don't want to sing out in public, but I've gotten
better. I can carry a tune now,'' he says.
   Fujiyama cannot explain the cultural differences that cause
Japanese _ young and old _ to sing at home along with variety shows
(which flash the lyrics on the television screen) and at
``karaoke'' bars with professional equipment, light shows and
audiences; while Americans tend to sing in their cars with the
windows rolled up and are relieved when they manage ``Happy
Birthday'' without embarrassing themselves.
   But Bill Feltz, who specializes in Japanese culture at the
East-West Center here, has some ideas.
   ``Japanese, as in many countries, are not as ashamed of singing
as we are in the United States,'' says Feltz, who as an
ethnomusicologist studies music of Asian cultures. ``There you're
not expected to sing like Bruce Springsteen or Beverly Sills.''
   In many Asian cultures, Feltz says, people have a common
repertoire and sing songs they learned as children for their entire
lives. In the United States, he said, more emphasis is put on the
quality, so elementary school students who once belted out ``My
country 'tis of thee....'' with abandon learn to be self-conscious
and clam up as they grow older.
   That's what happened to Adrian Mangiboyat, 32, who left his job
as a reporter for the Pacific Business News here to teach English
in a Japanese village.
   ``I guess I sang at school as a little kid, but I outgrew that.
I never sang along with the radio, in the shower, nothing like
that,'' he says. ``But when I applied for the job (in Japan) they
said singing was an integral part of Japanese culture, and I knew I
was in trouble.''
   Mangiboyat earned the teaching position in a program sponsored
by the Japanese government, but before he departed for
Yabuki-Machi, a small town 100 miles north of Tokyo, he enrolled at
the University of Hawaii.
   In a nine-week course called ``Voice Training for the Tone
Deaf,'' Mangiboyat and other would-be warblers spent two hours a
week learning scales, pitch and simple songs. Their homework
included taking the stage at a local ``karaoke'' bar popular with
Japanese tourists.
   ``The Japanese officials said being able to sing will give me an
edge with my students and the other villagers. It will show them
that I really tried to learn about their culture.''
   Fujiyama agrees.
   ``By asking you to sing with them, they're saying `let's be
friends.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
