<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Germany-RateHike     08-25 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Germany-Rate Hike,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West German Central Bank Raises Key Interest Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's central bank
raised a key interest rate Thursday to defend the value of its
currency and fend off inflation, leading a round of rate hikes in
Europe.
   The Bundesbank raised its discount rate, which it charges on
loans to other banks, by half a percentage point to 3.5 percent.
   Karl Otto Poehl, president of the Bundesbank, cited the weakness
of the mark against the U.S. dollar as a main reason for lifting
the discount rate.
   The higher discount rate should cause other interest rates to
rise. That would support the exchange value of the mark by making
mark-denominated investments more attractive.
   The dollar eased more than a pfennig to level around 1.8650
marks soon after the Bundesbank's announcement.
   France, Great Britain, Switzerland, the Netherlands and Austria
followed the Bundesbank's lead and raised rates.
   ``Today's step is an important signal which will be understood
by the foreign exchange and capital markets,'' Poehl said.
   Poehl told reporters that the dollar's strength against the mark
endangered efforts to adjust trade imbalances between the world's
major trading partners.
   He also said the Bundesbank will ``continue to do everything to
stem the decline of the mark against the dollar.''
   Poehl also said the discount rate increase was aimed at curbing
inflation and bringing the country's above-target money supply
growth back into the proper range. The mark's weakness has
contributed to inflation by raising import prices.
   The Bundesbank decided to keep its Lombard rate steady at 5
percent, and indicated no change in its rate on securities
repurchase agreements.
   The Bundesbank has adjusted German interest rates upwards three
times in the past eight weeks. It raised the Lombard rate to 5
percent from 4.5 percent on July 28, following a hike in the
discount rate to 3 percent from 2.5 percent on June 30.
</TEXT>
