<DOCNO> AP880825-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-Economy Bjt   08-25 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Economy, Bjt,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Interest Rates Raised Following Record Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government, trying to curb inflation,
on Thursday pushed up interest rates to a 2{-year high after
announcing a record trade deficit for July that was nearly double
the previous record.
   The July deficit and the interest-rate hike, both unexpectedly
large, rocked British financial markets.
   Share prices plummeted on the London Stock Exchange and trading
volume picked up. The British pound first fell on the trade news,
and then had a mixed reaction to the interest-rate hike.
   The British rate rise came amid a round of key interest-rate
increases in Western Europe. The Bundesbank, West Germany's central
bank, raised its discount rate by half a percentage point to 3.5
percent. The central banks of France, Switzerland, the Netherlands
and Austria followed the Bundesbank, hiking their own key rates.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index,
which plunged more than 50 points before recovering some of its
losses, closed 39 points, or 2.1 percent, lower at 1,768.6, amid
moderate trading volume.
   The pound soared to $1.6995 late Thursday from $1.6788 late
Wednesday, but it fell to 3.16 West German marks from 3.17 marks.
   The Bank of England signaled a full percentage point increase in
the commercial banks' base lending rate to 12 percent, soon after
the Department of Trade and Industry reported that Britain's
merchandise trade deficit soared in July to a record 2.65 billion
pounds, or about $4.5 billion.
   The previous record trade gap was 1.7 billion pounds, or around
$2.9 billion, in May.
   Britain's four leading commercial banks _ Barclays Bank PLC,
Midland Bank PLC, Lloyds Bank PLC and National Westminster Bank PLC
_ quickly responded to the Bank of England's signal.
   Many market watchers had anticipated an increase of only half a
percentage point in the base lending rate.
   It was the eighth increase in the benchmark rate since early
June, when the rate stood at a 10-year low of 7.5 percent, and it
brought the base lending rate to its highest level since January
1986. The previous hikes were half-point increases, with the most
recent coming on Aug. 8.
   ``The import figures confirm that the economy has been growing
too fast. We have to slow it down and that means higher interest
rates,'' Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson said.
   Spurred by Britain's strong consumer spending, imports jumped 13
percent, across the board, to 9.43 billion pounds, or about $16
billion, in July, while exports fell 0.9 percent to 6.78 billion
pounds, or $11.5 billion.
   ``The government is determined to do whatever is necessary to
keep inflation under control,'' Lawson said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. radio interview. ``The economy as a whole is
doing extremely well,'' he added.
   The full-point interest-rate hike was viewed as a major
additional tightening of monetary policy to help reduce the growing
inflationary pressures in the economy. Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher has repeatedly said that reducing such pressures is her
top economic priority.
   Inflation in Britain increased to an annual rate of 4.8 percent
in July from 4.6 percent in June.
   A spate of recent economic reports has confirmed
faster-than-expected growth in the British economy.
   On Tuesday, for example, the goverment reported that Britain's
inflation-adjusted gross domestic product, measured by the output
of goods and services, rose 1.3 percent in the second quarter from
the first. The markets had expected a rise of only 1 percent.
   Recent weakness in the pound, exacerbated by the latest trade
report, has given the Thatcher government room to increase interest
rates without pushing the pound dangerously high, which would hurt
British exports even more.
   ``We now have a genuine balance-of-payments crisis. These
figures are appalling,'' said John Shepperd, director of the London
investment firm Warburg Securities, referring to the July trade
report.
   The latest trade deficit compared with a 1.02 billion pound, or
$1.7 billion, gap in July 1987.
   Britain's current-account deficit jumped to 2.15 billion pounds
in July, up from a revised deficit of 1.04 billion pounds in June
and a deficit of 323 million pounds in July 1987.
   The current account includes ``invisible'' trade, such as
services, foreign investment earnings and official transfer
payments, which was estimated to be in surplus by 500 million
pounds in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
