<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 0708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-BehindtheWheel Adv03-04   08-25 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Behind the Wheel, Adv 03-04,0870</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Grand AM Is No Typical 4-Cylinder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not often that a compact car with a
four-cylinder engine can offer a decent sporty-car ride. But the
1988 Pontiac Grand AM SE is no typical four-cylinder compact.
   For starters, the standard 2-liter, fuel-injected engine is
turbocharged and can produce 165 horspower. Pontiac adds it can go
from 0 to 60 in a brisk eight seconds.
   The Grand AM SE's standard suspension package includes Goodyear
Eagle GT+4 all-season radial tires and stabilizer bars that make
for a firm, stable ride.
   Inside, there's a sporty feel with the thick, leather-wrapped
steering wheel, contoured front bucket seats _ molded to hold your
body in place _ and turbo boost gauge set amid a sporty driver area.
   Outside, the Grand AM SE is one of the prettiest of General
Motors Corp.'s cars, with bumpers and front, side and rear skirts
that match the body so there's no gaudy chrome.
   In fact, the styling, which debuted in the 1985 model year,
helps explain why the Grand AM is the Pontiac Division's volume
leader.
   From the buyer's perspective, it has snazzy styling, said
Pontiac spokesman Reggie Harris. Exterior styling and cost are the
two main reasons cited by buyers, he added.
   The lowest-priced Grand AM is $10,269, including $400 for
shipping, Harris said. But the SE test car totaled just under
$15,000.
   That $10,000-$15,000 price range encompasses many of the Grand
AM's competitors, such as the Buick Skylark and Dodge Lancer, which
start around $10,400, and the Honda Prelude, which starts around
$13,600.
   Harris noted the Grand AM _ which comes in three versions, the
Grand AM, the LE and the SE _ is particularly adept at luring young
buyers.
   Median age of buyers is 32, with 63 percent under age 35, Harris
said. Forty-even percent are male, 55 percent are married and 38
percent have college education. Median income is $40,000 annually.
   The test car, an SE, was fun to drive. The suspension and
engine, linked to a three-speed automatic transmission, offered
somewhat of a muscle-car ride complete with throaty rumble from
under the hood during hard accelerations.
   Handling was admirable, even at high speeds. There was no roll,
no sway.
   The trunk was roomy, and the rear seats split and folded down
for more storage space.
   There were nice touches inside for driver and passengers. Map
lights were available in front and rear.
   Front visors had slits in the material to slip paper, maps,
etc., and netting on the back of the front seats offered spots for
newspapers, magazines for rear-seat passengers.
   Controls for the AM-FM stereo and cassette player as well as
ventilation were conveniently located at the front of the center
console.
   Fit and finish inside and out was excellent.
   I noticed a few problems, too. At 5-foot-4, I found it difficult
to put the seat belt into its latch alongside the driver seat once
I had the seat moved up to where I could touch the pedals
comfortably.
   The seat belt latch was jammed between the driver seat and the
center console storage area. It was also difficult to unlatch the
belt without first moving the driver seat back a ways, for the same
reason.
   The Grand AM has a cruise control system found in many other GM
cars that is mounted on the turn signal stalk. As with the other GM
cars, I sometimes discovered the lever in the on position even when
the cruise wasn't actuated.
   Still, it's unsettling to glance down and see it on.
   Rear seating, for three, might be snug.
   The car also gulped down the gasoline. Fuel economy is rated at
20 miles per gallon in the city and 27 mpg on the highway, but in
my demanding city-highway driving I didn't get 20.
   Lastly, the center console had yellow spots that would light up
to indicate what gear the automatic transmission was in. But in
bright sunlight, it was murder trying to see what gear the shifter
had settled in.
   Consumer Reports says the 1986 Grand AM with four-cylinder
engine, the latest model it has information for, had an average
record for trouble, up from worse-han-average for the 1985 model.
Still, 1988 looks to be the best year for Grand AM yet, with
projections of 220,000 sales compared with 216,065 in the 1987
model year and 190,994 in the 1986 model year.
   We're in great shape for that car line, Harris said, noting
sales have been on target.
   He said even Mary Kay, the cosmetics company, has ordered a
fleet of 5,000 Grand AMs for its employees. But he quickly added
they won't be pink.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Job, former executive business editor of The
Detroit News, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The Associated
Press. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 3-4</NOTE>
