<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-NewsCorp     08-25 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-News Corp,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>News Corp. Fourth Quarter Net Down 67.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp. Ltd., a vast communications
conglomerate with holdings that range from British newspapers to
the Fox Broadcasting Co., reported a 67.5 percent drop in
fourth-quarter earnings Thursday, attributing the results to Fox
startup costs and a big decline in asset sales.
   Excluding those factors, News Corp. said, its earnings rose 41
percent from the comparable period a year earlier.
   The company, based in Sydney, Australia, and controlled by
publishing-entertainment entrepreneur Rupert Murdoch, earned $128.1
million in the three months ended June 30, vs. $394.4 million a
year earlier.
   Earnings for the previous quarter and year were inflated by more
than $300 million in special gains, largely property sales.
   Earnings per share for the latest quarter, stated in American
Depositary Receipts listed on the New York Stock Exchange, were 82
cents vs. $2.61 a year earlier. An ADR represents two of the
company's ordinary shares.
   The company said fourth-quarter revenue totaled $1.2 billion, up
22.3 percent from $981.3 million.
   In a statement from its New York office, News Corp. based the
figures on what it called the average rates of exchange between
U.S. dollars and Australian dollars prevailing in each period.
   For the year, News Corp. said earnings totaled $341.27 million,
or $2.20 per ADR, a 37.3 percent decline from the $544.43 million,
or $3.72 per ADR, earned in fiscal 1987.
   Revenue totaled $4.35 billion, vs. $3.5 billion, a 24.2 percent
increase.
   News Corp. is a diversified international media and
entertainment company with primary interests in newspapers,
magazines, book publishing, movie and television production and
distribution, and commercial printing. Principal operations are in
Australia, the Pacific Basin, Britain and the United States.
   Besides Fox, which the company is attempting to build into the
fourth major U.S. network, News Corp.'s American holdings include
Metromedia TV stations and number of magazines and newspapers,
among them the Boston Herald American and San Antonio Express-News.
Most recently the company acquired Triangle Publications Inc.,
publisher of TV Guide and Seventeen, for $3 billion.
</TEXT>
