<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     08-25 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers-Batus Agreement Ends Eight-Year Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Insurance Group Inc.'s agreement to
be bought by Batus Inc. for $5.2 billion ends a bitter eight-month
battle that included unusual skirmishing over the evils of smoking
and investment in South Africa.
   Spokesmen for the Los Angeles insurer and the Louisville, Ky.,
tobacco and retailing conglomerate couldn't say Thursday just how
many lawsuits and administrative proceedings have been spawned by
their fight.
   But the merger deal, which was announced late Wednesday, calls
for the companies to cooperate in unraveling the tangle and
cooperating in pressing for approval of the purchase by insurance
regulators in various states.
   Farmers agreed to be bought by Batus for $75 a share, $3 a share
higher than Batus' highest previous publicly announced offer and
$12 more a share than Batus has been offering stockholders on the
market.
   No date has been set for a needed vote on the merger by
shareholders of Farmers, the nations' third-largest home and auto
insurer and seventh-biggest property and casualty insurer.
   Batus, the American subsidiary of BAT Industries PLC of Britain,
owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., maker of Kool, Viceroy and
other brands, Appleton Papers and retailiers including Sak's Fifth
Avenue and Marshall Field's.
   The deal requires the approval of insurance regulators in nine
of the states where Farmers does business, and hearings before
those regulators were the forum for the most acrimonious
accusations in the takover battle.
   Farmers representatives maintained that Batus, as a tobacco
producer, would end non-smoker discounts for Farmers policy
holders. When Batus vowed to continue the discounts, Farmers
suggested ownership by Batus would prevent it from crusading
against smoking as strongly as it has in the past.
   Farmers also lined up numerous local, state and national elected
officials to blast Batus' British parent, BAT Industries PLC, for
maintaining businesses in racially segregated South Africa.
   After the deal was cut, Batus Chairman Patrick Sheehy said the
earlier acrimony hadn't effected the week-long negotiations.
   ``I think often things that are said in court are much more
acrimonious than one's true feelings,'' Sheehy said in an interview.
   One or the other of the companies has challenged or threatened
to challenge the seven state regulatory decisions issued to date,
some in court and some in appeals to the regulators.
   By dropping various lawsuits and jointly appealing regulators'
decisions, the companies said, officials believe they can clear the
regulatory path to a merger as early as the end of the year.
   The merger won the approval of insurance regulators in Arizona,
and was given conditional approval in Ohio and Illinois. Idaho,
Washington and Oregon have rejected the deal and decisions or
hearings are pending in Texas and Kansas.
   California regulators rejected the merger, but that decision was
overturned by a state court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880825-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-88 1626EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Insilco 1stLd-Wriethru f0159 08-25 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insilco, 1st Ld-Wriethru, f0159,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insilco Agrees To $1.1 Billion Buyout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, In active ..., with one graf to UPDATE
with closing stock price. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Two weeks ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insilco Corp. said Thursday it accepted a
$1.1 billion buyout offer from two Texas oilmen, tossing aside a
previous takeover agreement with a management-led group.
   Under the latest arrangement, INR Holdings Inc., headed by Cyril
Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown of Midland, Texas, will pay $31.75 in
cash for each of Insilco's outstanding 25.6 million shares.
Including debt, the deal has an indicated value of about $1.1
billion, Insilco said in a statement.
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Insilco closed
up $1.12{ a share Thursday to $31.12{.
   Two weeks ago, Insilco agreed to a management-led leveraged
buyout with First Boston Corp. But Insilco's board said Thursday
that it had withdrawn its support of the $29-a-share offer, which
valued the company at about $950 million.
   Dissenting shareholders last week filed lawsuits against
Insilco, charging that management's offer was too low.
   In a leveraged buyout a company is acquired largely through
borrowed funds that are repaid through the target company's profits
or asset sales.
   Anaylysts had said higher bids would increase the chance a buyer
would have to sell at least some divisions of Insilco to finance
the purchase.
   Once a leading silver operation known as International Silver
Co., Insilco restructured itself into an industrial holding company
and producer of specialty consumer and high technology products.
   Several subsidiaries have wide brand-name recognition, including
Rolodex desktop equipment, Red Devil paints and Taylor school
yearbooks.
   Insilco reported a flat overall earnings for the first half of
1988, $21.7 million, or $1.02 a share, vs. $21.5 million, or $1.02,
a year ago. But its profit from ongoing operations increased about
11 percent and sales rose almost 21 percent.
   Wagner and Brown are engaged in the exploration and production
of oil and natural gas, the operation of gas pipelines, real estate
development and other businesses.
   Earlier this year, the pair launched a hostile tender offer for
USG Corp., a Chicago-based building products concern. But Wagner
and Brown terminated their offer in June, a month after they lost a
bid for six seats on USG's board in a heated proxy contest.
   To finance the Insilco acquisition, INR Holdings said it has
obtained commitments totaling $980 million from Wagner, Brown and
Merrill Lynch & Co.
   The deal received the unanimous endorsement of a special
committee of outside directors, Insilco said. INR Holdings will
begin a cash tender offer within five business days of the
execution of a definitive merger agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
