<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     08-25 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>M1 Down $2 Billion; M2 Down $699.4 Million; M3 Down $1.8 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply fell in the week ended Aug. 15, the Federal Reserve Board
reported Thursday.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 fell to a seasonally
adjusted $3,027.5 billion in that week, from $3,028.2 billion the
previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, fell to 3,823.4 billion from
$3,825.2 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, fell to $780
billion from $782 billion the previous week.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts such as
savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus
less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum
denominations of $100,000.
   In judging monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted attention from M1 to the two broader money supply measures
   For the latest 13 weeks, M1 averaged $778.1 billion, a 6.4
percent rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks, the Fed said,
although it has not set a specific target range for that figure
since early last year.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $1.16 billion in
the week ended Aug. 17, compared with a gain of $440 million the
previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System averaged $592 million a day in the week ended
Wednesday, up from $556 million the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $281.9 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $280.2 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
