<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HomeSales 1stLd-Writethru f0259 08-25 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0259,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Sales Drop In July</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs The median...to RESTORE dropped word
`higher' after percent change for South. Picks up 9th graf,
Tuccillo said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes, jolted
by rising mortgage rates, dropped 5 percent in July, the first
decline since January, a real estate trade group said Thursday.
   The National Association of Realtors said that sales of existing
homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63 million
units last month, following a 6.4 percent increase in June.
   The decline was the first since a 4.8 percent drop in January
with analysts blaming the setback on rising mortgage rates.
Fixed-rate mortgages climbed to a nationwide average of 10.5
percent at the end of July and have risen even faster in August,
topping 10.71 percent last week.
   John Tuccillo, chief economist for the Realtors, said even with
the July drop in demand, sales were still at the second highest
monthly level of the past year.
   ``Even with the recent and prospective increases in interest
rates, sales in 1988 will almost certainly be higher than we
anticipated at the beginning of the year,'' he said.
   The median price of a home rose from June to July by $1,400 to
$91,600, up 3.7 percent from a year ago, when the median sales
price for an existing home was $88,300.
   For the first time in a decade, the Midwest led in
year-over-year price changes, with an increase of 7 percent to a
median price of $70,600. The Northeast remained the highest-priced
region of the country, with a median price of $146,700 last month,
up just 0.6 percent from a year ago.
   The median price in the West was $123,500 last month, 4.2
percent higher than a year ago, while the median price in the South
of $85,600 was 5.7 percent higher than a year ago.
   Tuccillo said that the big jump in home prices in the Midwest
reflected a rebound in the region's rust belt industries because of
the boom in manufacturing caused by rising export sales. He said
the smaller price increase for the Northeast reflected some
softening in demand after two years of strong sales.
   All regions of the country except the West suffered sales
declines in July.
   The sharpest decline occurred in the South, where sales were
down 7 percent in July to an annual rate of 1.32 million units. In
the Northeast sales dropped 6.8 percent to an annual rate of
690,000 units while sales in the Midwest fell by 5.1 percent in
July, compared to June, but were 4.4 percent higher than a year ago.
   The West saw sales rise 3.2 percent to an annual rate of 690,000
units in July.
</TEXT>
